<HEADLINE>Position must be clear about jobs without interviews</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DICK LOUDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>LOUDEN CLEAR</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650331</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OVER the summer The Herald has been highlighting questionable
practices in appointing senior staff to the new single-tier councils.
What is your opinion -- or do you always have to say The Herald is
right?
No, I don't always have to say that but on this issue I certainly
agree with The Herald's line.
The most publicised case is that of the appointment without interview
of Mrs Liz Reid, Lothian's director of education, to the post of
director with the new Edinburgh council. By repute she has done a
first-class job and would have been a clear favourite for the Edinburgh
post, but to appoint her without interview was inexcusable.
This was not a case of a simple transfer. Though Mrs Reid is moving
from a larger to a smaller authority, she was applying for a
newly-created post with its own contract, salary and conditions of
service. Such a method of appointment has no place in the open arena of
local government.
It also shows a distinct lack of consideration for the other
candidates, who applied in good faith and who in some cases would have
gained valuable benefit from the experience of a high-level interview
and from being able to use their success in reaching the short leet in
future CVs.
The Staff Commission, which has been overseeing the process
nationally, had not issued strict enough guidelines to prevent what
happened in Edinburgh but that is no justification. Senior councillors
know full well the sensitivities of appointment procedures and the need
to be seen to do what is right. The councillors concerned may not have
been held to account this time but you can be sure they will not do the
same again.
It was equally unacceptable that there were cases where councillors
who had agreed to act as referees for candidates then served on the
interviewing panels. They may argue that they had not yet been nominated
to the panels at they time when they were asked to stand as referees but
that argument holds little water. They may genuinely feel that they
could still take a dispassionate view but, in the eyes of other
applicants and outside observers, they had placed themselves in a
compromised position and should not have allowed this to happen.
I HAD hoped that my daughter would be able to take the new Higher
Still courses when she enters fifth year in August 1997. Is the year's
delay which Michael Forsyth has announced bad news for her?
It may not be. The rationale behind Higher Still is that it is
intended to create ''opportunities for all''. For example, by offering
Higher courses in modular form, it can ensure that pupils gain formal
credit for each unit they achieve. Likewise, the new Advanced Highers --
which will replace the Certificate of Sixth Year Studies -- are seen as
having the potential to attain wider uptake and credibility and to serve
as a more natural bridge between school and higher education.
The delay could therefore be unfortunate in particular for those
pupils of your daughter's age who may struggle to achieve full Highers.
On the other hand, it is now clear that the process of introducing the
new courses in 1997 was going to involve a precipitate rush and that
would not have been good news for your daughter's ''guinea-pig'' year
group.
The Higher Still reforms have been described as urgent. If they are
urgent now, they were urgent many years ago. I tend to the view that the
present Highers system, whatever its deficiencies, largely enjoys the
confidence of parents, employers and the higher education sector and
should only be discarded when a demonstrably better arrangement is fully
ready to be put in place.
WHY are the teacher unions making such a fuss over class sizes? To
parents like me there seem better ways of spending educational money.
The main argument, it seems to me, is that the class-size agreement
was drawn up over 20 years ago and since then classroom teaching has
undergone a revolution. The days of ''chalk-and-talk'' are largely gone
and in their place is an emphasis on group and individual teaching.
''Differentiation'' -- the process by which the particular needs of each
child are catered for -- is not only the in-term but the in-practice and
rightly so.
However, the downside of these highly desirable developments -- whose
sole purpose is to benefit the pupil -- is that they add considerably to
the burdens of the teacher. Large classes are manageable when you are
lecturing to a whole class and then overseeing them as they all carry
out the same tasks. The more complex the class organisation becomes, the
less attention can be devoted to the needs of each child.
I can't really say whether class sizes should be the number one
priority for spending at the moment. Teachers themselves will hold
differing opinions on this, though I have no doubt that the unions are
accurately reflecting a view widely held within the profession. They are
probably also reacting to ominous signs south of the Border.
In England and Wales, where unlike Scotland, there is no national
agreement on maximum class sizes pupil numbers will rise by 150,000 this
session, yet it looks as if schools will employ 4500 fewer teachers.
This situation arises from the Government's refusal to fund this year's
2.7% salary rise for teachers. According to a study commissioned by the
National Governors' Council, the result will be that more than 40% of
primary pupils will be in classes of more than 30 within a year if extra
money is not found.
Extra money for smaller classes is a proposition unlikely to attract
the sympathy of the Government at the moment, which helps to explain why
the Educational Institute of Scotland has decided that its class-size
campaign will be an extended one, without recourse to industrial action,
in the run-up to the next General Election.
</TEXT>
