<HEADLINE>Malting first from Highland Grain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650332</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND Grain, the specialist malting barley co-operative, has become
the first business in Scotland to offer maltsters dried bulk supplies
drawn exclusively from farms registered under the Scottish Quality
Cereals assurance scheme.
Alan Whiteford, chairman of Highland Grain, said his board had made a
commitment to the scheme at a very early stage and had sought to assure
its members that, as professional malting barley growers, they had much
to gain from it.
The co-operative has 62 farmer-members based in Ross-shire,
Inverness-shire, Morayshire, Caithness and Sutherland. It has a dryer
and store at Tore on the Black Isle, where it processes up to 17,000
tonnes of malting barley a year.
A Scottish Agricultural College study on the financial outcomes from
Scottish cereals during the 1993 crop year shows that winter barley
proved to be the most profitable at #361 a hectare net margin. This was
followed by winter wheat at #297, with spring barley bringing up the
rear at #239.
</TEXT>
