<HEADLINE>Rovers slump to third loss in a row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE TONGUE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650333</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Blackburn 1, Man Utd 2
BLACKBURN Rovers knew it would not be easy defending their Premiership
title, but were not expecting this. Last night's home defeat by the team
they snatched the championship from in May was their third in succession
and confirmed that they are not functioning in any department as
effectively as last season.
As ever, when these sides meet, there was an edge to the game, and
United's Roy Keane was sent off after receiving two of the eight yellow
cards issued by referee David Elleray -- his second for diving over
Colin Hendry's leg in the penalty area.
United deserved Lee Sharpe's opening goal just after half-time and
Alan Shearer's equaliser on the hour was Blackburn's first shot on
target. It was one of the four youngsters in the visiting team, David
Beckham, who curled in the winner seven minutes later.
Concentrating in the early stages on taking some of the ferocious pace
out of the game, United required almost 20 minutes before registering a
threat, but should have scored from it. Cole wriggled round goalkeeper
Flowers, only for Hendry to recover and slide the ball off the line.
Blackburn could not complain at falling behind only 30 seconds into
the second half. Flowers beat the ball away three times in a scramble
before Sharpe finally knocked it back past him.
Shearer drove in a half-volley following a corner, but Beckham's
sweeping shot as he turned was a worthy winning goal. United held on to
extend a run in contrast to that of the champions -- three successive
wins.
</TEXT>
