<HEADLINE>'Crazy' rule hurts Matsuoka</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650334</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE match of the day at Flushing Meadow yesterday ended with a scream
and Japan's Shuzo Matsuoka crumpled on the hard court, overcome by
severe cramps in both legs.
He and Czech Petr Korda were locked in a titanic struggle that had
gone three tie-breaks in the first three sets and was headed for a
fourth when the Japanese player collapsed with screams of pain.
The 27-year-old Matsuoka, who led 6-7, 7-6, 7-6, 5-6 after three hours
and 26 minutes of full-speed action, lay in a heap screaming for several
minutes -- unable to be helped, according to the rules, and physically
unable to call for help.
Finally, first aid arrived. Matsuoka left under his own power and
Korda, the 1992 French Open finalist, advanced to the second round.
''Many times when I had to bend low, I started feeling it and it was
scary, but this is the US Open. I had to keep going,'' said Matsuoka,
who took Pete Sampras to four sets in the quarter-finals at Wimbledon.
Players are not allowed to be helped when they cramp, as the injury is
seen as a by-product of conditioning. Matsuoka wanted assistance but
could not speak through his pain, and courtside officials would not help
him at first for fear of causing his disqualification.
Korda watched helplessly. ''If you are cramping, no-one can help you.
Otherwise, I would get some penalty points because I cannot cross the
net,'' he said. ''No-one could help him at that point unless he could
help himself, which I feel is very crazy, a crazy rule.''
Former champion Stefan Edberg celebrated his fiftieth consecutive
grand-slam tournament by crushing Czech Martin Damm. The 29-year-old
Edberg is unseeded in New York for the first time in 11 years, but the
Swede charged into the second round 6-0, 6-3, 7-6 in just under two
hours.
Britain's top-ranked player Greg Rusedski lost 7-6, 6-3, 6-7, 6-1 to
Joost Winnink, of Holland, and refused to blame his defeat on a mild
dose of food poisoning. Jeremy Bates went down 6-2, 6-2, 6-3 to Emilio
Sanchez, of Spain. With Mark Petchey also beaten, Tim Henman, who beat
Juan Albert Viloca (Spain) 6-3, 4-6, 6-3, 6-2 is Britain's sole survivor
in the singles.
Other singles results included (* denotes seed):
Men: 4* Boris Becker (Germany) beat Alex Lopez Moron (Spain) 6-1, 6-0,
6-3; Jerome Golmard (France) beat 10* Wayne Ferreira (S Africa) 7-5, 7-6
(7-5), 6-1; Marcos Ondruska (S Africa) beat Mark Petchey (Britain) 7-6
(7-0), 6-1, 6-0.
Women: Martina Hingis (Switzerland) beat Nancy Feber (Belgium) 6-2,
6-3; Larisa Neiland (Latvia) beat Beate Reinstadler (Austria) 6-2, 6-4;
9* Gabriela Sabatini (Argentina) beat Adriana Serra-Zanetti (Italy) 6-1,
6-1;  Gigi Fernandez (USA) beat Irina Spirlea (Romania) 4-6, 6-1, 7-5;
6* M Pierce (France) beat M de Swardt (S Africa) 6-4, 6-1.
