<HEADLINE>Schumacher under scrutiny</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650336</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE driving of Michael Schumacher will be under intense scrutiny for
the remainder of the Formula One season following the one-race suspended
ban he was handed aftre winning the Belgian Grand Prix on Sunday.
The ban will not come into effect unless the world champion commits
further driving offences at any of the next four races.
Schumacher had been harshly criticised by the Williams team and Damon
Hill for his irregular, defensive driving. The Williams team lodged a
protest which was upheld by the race stewards.
Benetton immediately lodged an appeal, setting up another Paris
hearing of the International Motoring Federation, the sport's governing
body, to decide Schumacher's fate.
He now faces a challenge to clear his name before the Italian Grand
Prix at Monza on September 10 when he is certain to receive a warm
reception because he is joining Ferrari next year.
It has also been suggested that David Coulthard, now with Williams, is
favourite for a seat with McLaren alongside Mika Hakkinen. It could be,
if hints from McLaren's boss Ron Dennis are accurate, that he is
considering signing Coulthard to be part of a three-car team next year,
with Alain Prost possibly making a return.
Meanwhile, Hill has only six races left to wipe out Schumacher's 15
point lead. But Schumacher is unlikely to be fazed by the threat of a
one-race ban. Having come close to losing the title last year after
sitting out two races through disqualification, the 26-year-old will not
risk wrecking his championship hopes again.
Schumacher knows he has gained the upper hand and that victory at the
Italian Grand Prix a week on Sunday could virtually seal the title,
especially if Hill fails to add to his points tally there.
</TEXT>
