<HEADLINE>Windies fail to cash in after double breakthrough. Captain Atherton steers England to merited draw</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDY JALIL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650337</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS A conclusion to a series which remained vibrant to the final day
and in which the performances of both sides excelled at different
stages, a draw was, perhaps, the fairest outcome.
The stalemate reached at the end of the sixth Test at The Oval
yesterday was not entirely unexpected and, once again, as in previous
Tests of this remarkable series, there were achievements of the highest
order.
Appropriately, it was the England captain Mike Atherton who played the
most important role on the last day to force a draw.
His innings, just five short of a sixth Test century, must merit a
place among the best in terms of sheer resolve and pluck. His batting
effort in the entire series brought him England's player-of-the-series
award adjudicated by the West Indies manager, Wesley Hall.
His statement paid high tribute to the England captain: ''Mike
Atherton provided the defining difference to the result of the series
both by his highly accomplished batting and his astute captaincy.
''In his batting he led his team from the front, breaking the fire of
the West Indian pace bowlers unflinchingly. For me, the real test for
any player -- or captain -- comes when he is under pressure. Atherton's
perennial unflappability, his seemingly good humour, and his quiet
dignity were key ingredients not only in holding his team together, but
also in fostering a spirit of conviviality which prevailed between the
teams.''
Atherton modestly said: ''I am pleased with our performance, but
disappointed we couldn't get the upper hand in the last two Tests.''
Brian Lara's extraordinary innings of 179 from 206 balls in this Test
had transformed the match and put the West Indies in a commanding
position, bringing him the match award and the West Indies's
Man-of-the-Series award, but from England's point of view Atherton's
display yesterday was of vital importance.
It was exemplary in terms of single-mindedness for his team. He knew
he had to occupy the crease and that he did for nearly six hours, during
which he faced 269 balls in scoring 95. He was finally dismissed,
glancing Bishop and being snapped up by a diving wicketkeeper.
For the Windies, it was imperative to get an early breakthrough when
play began yesterday with England's score 39 without loss. They needed
199 more to make the tourists bat again and certainly the pressure was
on them with six hours of play ahead.
Atherton and Jason Gallian faced 12 overs, scoring 21, before Curtly
Ambrose found a way in by having Gallian edge the ball to Williams at
third slip. There wasn't any significant ball movement, but Gallian
failed to get behind the line and got a thick edge.
Ambrose, who has bowled with renewed vigour in this match after
resting from the previous Test, struck again four overs later. This time
he removed John Crawley through a catch behind the stumps. Again it was
a poor shot, Crawley played from the crease and simply dropped his bat
to the ball.
England were 64 for two after an hour's play and with 75 overs
remaining for the day at that stage, it had begun to look a little grim
for them. It also had given great encouragement to the West Indian
bowlers and made the task for the remaining England batsmen more
difficult.
Graham Thorpe, whose 74 was a substantial contribution in England's
first innings, joined Atherton and the two proceeded to repair the early
dent created by the pace of Ambrose.
When the left-handed Thorpe departed after a 68-run partnership with
his skipper, he had become the only England batsman to score more than
500 runs in a series between the countries in a rivalry which began as
far back as 1928.
Atherton was unperturbed and soon settled into another lengthy
partnership, with Graeme Hick. They added 80 for the fourth wicket.
After the England captain's departure, Hick went on to a patient,
unbeaten 51 in just under three hours, his second half-century of the
Test following the brilliant 96 from the first innings.
