<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S two boats competing in the 220-mile four-stage Teacher's
Round Britain Challenge maintained their unbeaten record on the start
line of each leg to date.
Glendronach, skippered by Jon Fitzgerald, and Lord Inverforth,
skippered by Paul Jeffes with sailmaker Chris Owen steering for the
departure from Rothesay, lead the 10-boat, five nations-fleet away on
the 740-mile third leg to Hartlepool.
Jeffes was quickly engaged in a tussle with Irish race leader David
Harte in Dream of Erin, but both Scottish flagged boats had the Welsh
team -- who lead them, and the overall standings by two points --
comfortably behind.
* RACING on the second day of the Brut British Olympic Trials at
Weymouth was postponed until mid-afternoon. To simulate wind strengths
most likely next year in Savannah, selectors have set a ceiling of 15
knots at the start of each race. It was a better day for the Scots.
Shirley Robertson was again on form in the Europe single-handed class,
winning twice, while in the Men's 470 Class Helensburgh's Andy Richards
and Ian Park finished second and third. Details:
