<HEADLINE>More Scots homeless in London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650343</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 10% of people forced to sleep on the streets of London are
Scots, a charity claimed yesterday.
Borderline, set up in 1990 by the Church of Scotland London Advisory
Service in response to the growing number of Scots sleeping rough in the
capital, also claimed in its annual report that it was dealing with
three times more people now than in 1991.
Labour and the charity Shelter Scotland expressed ''great concern'' at
the figures while calling for action to reverse the trend.
The Scottish Office, meanwhile, claimed that most of the 300 or so
people sleeping rough on the streets of central London in any one night
were locals, although it recognised the good work done by Borderline,
which received #36,000 of Government funding in the past year.
The charity said it helped more than 700 homeless Scots in the past
year -- most of those in the 21-40 age group. Teenagers were now the
smallest group assisted, accounting for 2.8%, while 17.8% were older
than 40.
Of the 700, 29.8% received help with accommodation, 29.2% returned
home, and 26.5% were given other forms of assistance.
The largest group of homeless Scots -- 54% -- were from Strathclyde,
while 10.7% were from Lothian.
Mr Gareth Davies, the charity's director, said the organisation
remained ''deeply concerned'' about the future of direct hostel
provision, especially for those aged over 25.
Mr Tommy Sheppard, assistant general secretary of the Scottish Labour
Party, said the charity's survey underlined the shocking results of the
Government's housing and economic policies.
Mrs Tricia Benzie of Shelter Scotland said: ''Up until now, the most
anecdotal reasons for the influx of Scots to London has been the
attraction of the bright lights and the lack of opportunities north of
the Border.
''We have asked young people in London the reasons why they go there.
Once we have had a chance to analyse our research, we may be able to
address the problem in a more practical fashion.''
</TEXT>
