<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ryder gamble on last card</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BERNARD Gallacher yesterday stepped gingerly out of the awkward corner
into which administrative ineptness had painted him when he confirmed
Nick Faldo and nominated Jose Maria Olazabal to complete the European
Ryder Cup team to meet the United States from September 22 to 24 at Oak
Hill, Rochester, New York. But the captain's footprints will surely lead
towards changing, yet again, the method of selection.
Despite Faldo's impoverished form, especially in the four majors since
he won at Doral in March, the presence of the world No.3 was never in
doubt. Who, anyway, would have had the nerve to omit him? But in
deciding to make the Spaniard twelfth man, given the obvious discomfort
his injured right foot continues to give him, Gallacher has made himself
a hostage to fortune.
Gallacher justified his decision thus: ''I picked Jose on his form of
the last three weeks. I know he probably won't be able to play twice a
day (in the foursomes and fourball games), but in three weeks' time the
injury may be better and certainly his partnership with Seve (only two
defeats in 15 outings) had a bearing on my choice.
''Jose is having this week off before he plays in the Lancome
tournament,'' Gallacher continued, ''and if his condition deterioriates
then we will discuss the possibility of replacing him.''
Gallacher's gamble may or may not backfire, but in opting for a
manifestly unfit player, who has now qualified automatically only once
in five attempts, he has overlooked the experience of Ian Woosnam,
frayed as his form is, and the promise of Jesper Parnevik, the other
most-favoured candidate.
But Gallacher must accept his share of the responsibilty (along with
the Ryder Cup committee) for having reduced the wild-card option from
three to two. When, after three terms of office, Gallacher passes the
baton on, presumably to Ballesteros, those responsible will clearly have
to re-think the system.
Woosnam -- who, ironically, was last night guest of honour at a
Variety Club of Great Britain dinner -- was, however, already resigned
to his fate. ''I think there will be someone blasting down Bernard's
ear,'' he said, an unspoken reference to Seve Ballesteros. But Gallacher
responded: ''When Ian won the British Masters last season and went to
the top of the points table I didn't think there were any circumstances
in which he wouldn't make the team. Things have just not worked out.''
Two other players who were then in the first 10, Angel-Miguel Jimenez
and Pierre Fulke, also have been eliminated. On the other hand,
Ballesteros's performances late last year were so conclusive that his
subsequent falls from grace cost him only four places, from first to
fifth.
But Olazabal, unlike Woosnam, made the cut in the recent US PGA
Championship and finished sixth and ninth in the last two US Tour
events. Woosnam's putting last week was in such disarray that one day he
put two putters in his bag, one of them long-handled. But Faldo, despite
his self-inflicted tortures by technique, will equal Christy O'Connor
Sr's record of 10 appearances.
Thus Woosnam, after six successive appearances, becomes one of the
four changes from the 1993 side, beaten by two points at The Belfry. He
loses his place along with Barry Lane, Peter Baker, and Joakim Haeggman.
Philip Walton and Per-Ulrik Johansson are the new caps, and Howard
Clark, after a six-year absence, and David Gilford, after four, return
for their sixth and second matches respectively.
Experience is certainly in Europe's favour -- 49 appearances in the
match and 13 major titles compared with the United States's 15 and six.
And to Europe's modest refreshing of the ranks the American have five
newcomers in Phil Mickelson, Tom Lehman, Loren Roberts, Jeff Maggert,
and Brad Faxon. Nevertheless, the respective odds are 2-5 the hosts, 9-4
the guests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
