<DOCNO>GH950829-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McLeod warns the SRU will not be held to ransom. Rugby's top players may be set for confrontation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Rugby Union will not be made bankrupt or held to ransom
by its international stars in the brave new world of professional rugby.
The warning was issued yesterday by SRU president Ian Todd and
International Board representative Freddie McLeod as the union responded
to the weekend announcement by the IB in Paris that the amateurism laws
are to be rescinded and that from next month the game will become open.
Todd and McLeod were irritated by reported comments by a couple of
players in the wake of the weekend announcement to the effect that it
was now up to the international squad to force the hand of the SRU to
get what they were worth.
McLeod, who, along with fellow Scottish IB representative Allan Hosie,
was a member of the IB council which reached the momentous decision to
consign amateurism to the dustbin after three days of talks in the
French capital, also underlined yesterday that international players
would not be able to capitalise on the thistle which adorns the Scotland
jersey.
''A major aspect of our work in the aftermath of the weekend's
decisions will be the retention of our intellectual property. By this I
mean that the players will not be able to exploit the logo which is the
property of the union,'' he declared.
Todd said: ''With the advent of the World Cup and the high profile of
our game in the media and TV and of large sponsorship deals it was
evident that things would have to change. With the high demands on our
players, recompense, we all agree, was inevitable. However, the radical
decisions in Paris have taken many of us by surprise.
''But let me make this absolutely clear. Those of us in Scotland will
do as we think best for the game in this country. We will not see the
union bankrupt and, more importantly, we will safeguard the clubs at all
levels from financial stress. There is no use in looking back. We have
to look forward and we should remember, too, that for the vast majority
of players this is still a recreational sport,'' he added.
The comments by McLeod and Todd surely represent the first salvoes in
what has the potential to be a period of furiously hard pounding for
both the union and the players as both bodies try to come to terms with
events of the last few days.
McLeod, who said that there would be a special meeting of the SRU soon
in light of the new regulations and that there would be a meeting, too,
with the clubs, added: ''I find it sad that certain individuals are
saying that the issue will have to be forced and that they have to find
their worth. We do not seek confrontation.
''Whatever agreement we come to will be based upon our ability to pay.
The financial situation of the union will not be placed in jeopardy and
it is essential that we continue the development of the game at all
levels.''
''There is Press comment this morning that certain players are looking
for confrontation and at this stage I find that regrettable. It was
suggested that we would be held to ransom and I find that sad. We will
be talking soon to the players and their agent to find a sensible
settlement.''
The international players' agent, former Scotland prop Ian McLauchlan,
met a number of the players prior to yesterday's Murrayfield press
conference at which he was an interested onlooker.
He declared: ''I don't think that the union can be held to ransom.
There is absolutely no point in bankrupting your employer. The players
realise that the new era isn't going to happen overnight and any that do
are in for a shock. This whole thing has to be done by mutual consent
but there is no doubt that the players have a very good grasp of what is
now available to them and that they will be able to capitalise on their
new found freedom.''
Neither the union or McLauchlan have set a target figure which the
internationals squad might expect to earn but it is likely that cotracts
will be in place before the first international match of the new season,
against Western Samoa, in November.
McLeod also indicated yesterday, although stressing that this was a
personal opinion as the union had not yet made a policy decision, that
the IB sanctioned policy of paying win bonuses might not find favour in
Scotland.
He said that even at international level this did not necessarily mean
that Scotland's players would be placed at a disadvantage and --
disregarding the fact that Scotland lost 34-10 -- he went on to suggest
that, when Scotland played the Springboks at Murrayfield last November,
the South Africans might have been on a contract which was in breach of
amateurism regulations then in place.
Scotland's 1990 Grand Slam captain David Sole, who figured in some
bruising confrontations with the SRU as the game drifted towards
professionalism, said yesterday: ''The board's decision does have a
knee-jerk quality about it, coming as it does so soon after the World
Cup and everything that has been happening with Murdoch and Packer and
so on, but it is the right decision and the main thing is that the
hypocrisy of shamateurism can now be brought to an end.
''This talk about the players holding the union to ransom is all very
negative. The players will have to work with the union to manage the new
situation as well as they can,'' he said.
'We will not see the union bankrupt, and we will safeguard clubs at
all levels from financial stress'
IAN TODD
'I find it sad that individuals are saying the issue will have to be
forced. We do not seek confrontation'
FREDDIE McLEOD
'Players realise the new era isn't going to happen overnight. Any that
do are in for a shock'
IAN McLAUCHLAN
'Now they are getting paid, I can't see many rugby union players
switching codes'
ALAN TAIT
</TEXT>
