<HEADLINE>Euphoria and despair greet Board decision</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REACTION to the International Board's weekend decision to scrap the
amateurism laws continued to flow in from around the oval globe
yesterday writes Derek Douglas. It ranged from the euphoria of Springbok
captain Francois Pienaar to the despair of former Irish RFU president
Ken Reid.
''It's fantastic. It's what everyone wanted. It is going to enhance
rugby in that the guys can now concentrate on what they are doing
without having to divert their energies elsewhere,'' said Pienaar.
Ex-Scottish rugby union international Alan Tait, who switched codes
with Widnes from Kelso in April 1988, has not ruled out a return to his
former sport if the opportunity arises. But he said his return north
would probably be in a coaching capacity and not as a player.
''Rugby union is a lot easier game to play and now they are getting
paid, I can't see many rugby union players switching codes. Now that
players will be going full-time and will be able to train more, I can
see rugby union becoming a better game than it has been,'' he said.
John Allen, secretary of English champions Leicester, who have the
biggest gate-takings in the country with a 16,000 capacity ground, said:
''All clubs will have problems initially in paying any money.''
Richard Mawditt, chairman of cup-holders Bath, said: ''Let's not kid
ourselves that the money is there. I don't believe that our club is in
the position to pay large sums of money in players' fees.
Former IRFU president Ken Reid said: ''We expected and recognised
changes had to come, but the nature and extent of the changes are going
to cause major difficulties. In my view it will be detrimental to many
of the aspects of the game in Ireland. I am stunned the IB has gone so
far.''
Irish centre Brendan Mullin welcomed the news. He said: ''The fact is
that the game has been professional for some time now in other
countries. When we took on the All Blacks in the World Cup we were
playing a professional side.''
In New Zealand, NZRFU chairman Richie Guy said: ''All we have done is
regulate the under-the-table payments, which will now be done on top of
the table. But from a practical sense, I don't think it will make a
great deal of difference.''
In France, newly-appointed French manager Andre Herrero is ready to
resign over the decision to end amateurism. ''I suppose that I am now a
professional and if it is so, I don't want to do this job for free,'' he
said.
''It's a step forward. We shall keep our rugby union culture, but
money will be on the table, not under it'', said French captain Philippe
Saint-Andre.
</TEXT>
