<HEADLINE>Forecast appears brighter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WENDY JACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EMPLOYMENT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650375</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Wendy Jack looks at factors that prevail in the Scottish jobs market
THOSE involved in the recruitment marketplace this summer, report a
pleasingly buoyant picture across the board.
In Glasgow, Stuart Macintyre, a director of Thomson Partners, says
that his company completed its busiest year ever, at the end of May.
''Since then,'' he continues, ''we've seen an intake of work over the
summer months at even a slightly higher level than the equivalent period
in 1994. Recently, we were working simultaneously on search assignments
to find the chief executives for each of three very well known quoted
Scottish companies.''
In terms of employing organisations' current thinking, Macintyre
responds: ''From the microcosm of our own viewpoint, I think they are
imposing even tighter parameters on the type of experience and past
achievement that they consider to be relevant and acceptable for a
particular post.
''This is not a new phenomenon, but one which continues unabated. From
the perception therefore of candidates, who are involuntarily in the
position of seeking a new job, or indeed someone who is eager to find a
fresh career challenge, I think there is a need to be increasingly aware
of the necessity to concentrate on the particular experience that you
have. It means that individuals actively wishing to do something else,
will have to reconcile themselves almost, to 'sticking to the knitting'
to some extent.''
For consultants involved in search these days, the response from those
they approach is now much more receptive to propositions which they
consider to be interesting -- which at least makes their lives a shade
easier and allows some movement to take place. Companies, says Stuart
Macintyre, continue to run very lean and will, he believes, go on doing
so. ''The continuing impact of technology, particularly in some of the
larger employers in Scotland, will I think, increase.''
Within companies these days, he sees the mood as cautious, but with an
underlying quiet confidence. On salary levels, he notes: ''Clearly they
are still moving up, but I think it's a very rare appointment now that
doesn't have a proportion of potential earnings available through
performance bonus. Previously, there would have been 10% available
through bonus, now it might be 20% or 30%.''
On the question of extra training and qualifications, Macintyre admits
to being uncertain these days that the once-magic key of an MBA now
makes a big difference to a candidate's chances. ''There's been a huge
proliferation of MBAs. It is valuable from a personal development point
of view, and for people's confidence levels about the input they're
making, but as a measurable aid to career development, I'm just not sure
it makes a big difference today. It was a feature of the seventies and
early eighties but I believe people have to be careful now about the
assumptions they make, before embarking on an MBA as a particular
business qualification.''
Search Consultancy, Scotland's largest independent recruitment agency,
with offices in Glasgow, Edinburgh and Dunfermline, also reports a very
buoyant market. Managing director Andrew Pert said: ''The electronics
market, both the OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturers) side and the
contract side are busy. The other area which has taken a major leap is
the call centre environment -- both inbound and outbound calls -- which
can be involved in customer service, telesales, helpline desks,
telemarketing operations, and so on. It is a massive marketplace.''
Another area of changing business is called ''Back Office
Processing''. One of the major projects, again in the West of Scotland,
has been the Royal Bank of Scotland mortgage centre based in Greenock.
''It has been relatively unique,'' explained Pert. ''Because we did
all the recruitment, both temporary and permanent labour bases, from
mailroom clerks through mortgage specialists to the management team.
Eventually there will be 300 jobs spread across the two phases; by
October the first phase of about 150 will be complete.''
A particularly interesting phenomenon highlighted by Andrew Pert, is
what is called generic training. ''There's a lot of it being
undertaken,'' he explains. ''Take for example, a call centre: there are
basic skills that people should have, before they can be assessed for
suitablity for the company. The LECs are setting up generic training
courses with the training providers, as a prerequisite before the
screening process is undertaken.
''It means that unemployed people can go on to these courses, then
people like ourselves will go in and assess them through our vetting
process, to see if they are suitable to go on to a job. It prepares
people for the job market. Clients have been very pleased with the
results of that.''
Another, more contentious area of growth is in flexible resourcing.
''It's contentious because a lot of people who are on these contracts,
although it's big business, have virtually no employment rights,'' Pert
explained.
''From a positive viewpoint, it's the state of the economy which
dictates generally what happens with a flexible resource market. In a
buoyant economy, such a market doesn't really exist because people want
the staff and offer permanent jobs. However, in a recession, it at least
provides training and jobs for those who would otherwise have nothing.
When things pick up, they have a track record and will hopefully be
considered for permanent employment.''
Overall Pert notes, companies appear ''to be in expansion mode, few
are still contracting in any major way. There's still caution, but we
are definitely seeing a lot more optimism.''
</TEXT>
