<HEADLINE>Index points to upturn in executive jobs market</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650376</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXECUTIVE recruitment has continued its rise throughout the first half
of 1995, according to the MSL Index, which has tracked the senior jobs
market quarterly since 1959, and is generally regarded as a respected
indicator of economic growth.
The Index currently stands at 102 (1959 base=100) which means it has
crossed the 100 threshold for two consecutive quarters. While down 10
points on the first quarter of 1995, it represents a rise of 16 points
on the same period last year.
Particularly encouraging is that the Moving Annual Total -- a 12-month
running total which irons out seasonal variances -- has not dropped for
10 successive quarters. The April-June quarter is the highest since the
first quarter of 1991, showing an increase of 4 points on the previous
three months, and a rise of 18 points on the equivalent period of 1994.
Within individual job categories, sales and marketing performed best
of all, with an increase of 57% over the year, although down 6% on the
quarter. Production did well also, increasing by 50% over the year, but
down 10% on the quarter, while research and development/design showed an
increase of 36% over the year, having fallen by 15% on the previous
quarter.
General management rose by 34% over the year, decreasing by 20% over
the quarter, with information technology rising by 12% over the year,
but falling by 23% over the previous quarter.
Accounting and finance fell by 8% over the year, and by 15% over the
previous quarter, while personnel similarly suffered a drop, this time
of 7% over the year, decreasing 32% over the quarter.
Most industry categories showed good increases over the year,
retailing being the most notable, up 26%. Food and drink wasn't far
behind with a rise of 24%, with energy up by 3% on the equivalent period
last year.
Ian Lloyd, managing director of the MSL Group, said: ''The latest
figures from the Index confirm our confidence in an upturn in the
executive jobs market. Although there has been a technical fall in
comparison with the first quarter of 1995, the MAT figures give us a
much more accurate and comprehensive view of the overall picture.''
The latest figures from the Index confirm our confidence in an upturn
in the executive jobs market
