<HEADLINE>Cyberian blizzard sweeps schools</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART MILLAR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650377</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pupils are discovering the World Wide Web is a level playing field
they can get stuck into, reports Stuart Millar.
IT all started with a vulture. A culture vulture that is. As part of a
project for Glasgow's Year of Culture, Richmond Park Special School in
Glasgow sent a story about a vulture around British schools by e-mail,
and invited pupils to add to the story. Five years on, Richmond Park is
just one of the many Scottish schools benefiting from the electronic
communications revolution that is now sweeping through education.
It is impossible to open a newspaper these days without running across
yet another tale of how the Internet is set to change our lives. But,
beyond the hype, the communications boom is having a radical impact in
schools. From electronic mail to Cyberspace and the World Wide Web, new
technology is breaking down geographical barriers, promoting
collaboration between schools and aiding staff development. The result
is that the education world is indeed becoming a smaller place.
And it is special schools like Richmond Park, which teaches around 100
primary age children with a wide range of physical and intellectual
disabilities, that are reaping the most benefits. ''For children with
special needs, it's a way of accessing the normal primary classroom,''
explains Maggie Pollard, the headteacher. ''In so many other areas,
access is a problem for these children, but with things like electronic
mail, they can communicate on their own terms.''
She tells the story of a primary seven pupil who developed a
friendship through e-mail. It was not until several months later when
the friends finally met face to face that they discovered the penpal was
not another pupil, but the assistant head of a Glasgow primary school.
And this, says Ms Pollard, is the beauty of the communication
technology. ''These children have physical disabilities, but with e-mail
nobody knows that. When they type in their names they are the same as
anybody else.''
Another special needs teacher, Ivan Mykitin, from Holybrook School in
the southside of Glasgow, is also a fanatic. ''I think for the kids this
will revolutionise their education. The children's information gathering
skils have developed. They now see their whole world as information they
can develop,'' he says.
The benefits to special needs children are indeed impressive. Ms
Pollard estimates that this sort of work improves their learning
potential by as much as 50%. And it is this sort of impact that has won
over initially sceptical staff.
''It's fascinating,'' she says. ''An awful lot of the teachers are
older and were a bit apprehensive. But when they saw what it means for
our children, what it does for their writing, their improvement and
their self-esteem, that was instant feedback.''
''It's not just the pupils who benefit,'' says Anne Bruce of the
Scottish Council for Edcuational Technology, which launches its own
initiative, Contact, next month. ''Schemes such as Contact allow
teachers, who are often isolated with small classes, to network with
other special needs teachers. For example, they can pool experience of
coping with specific sorts of problems that only arise once in a
while.''
Contact is a bulletin board service which combines electronic mail and
discussion forums with access to Internet conferences on education
topics. The pilot stage which began in February was so successful that
around 200 schools are already using the scheme.
Most of the new communications initiatives are based on First Class
software, making them, as one education adviser put it, ''simplicity
itself'' to use, another major attraction for teachers. ''Anyone who can
point and click a mouse can use a system such as Contact,'' says Ms
Bruce. ''Yet we are providing a very useful and sophisticated
application. We are giving people a reason for learning about using
technology. Instead of just being technology for its own sake, it helps
you access the world.''
Rural schools too are discovering the enormous potential of electronic
communcations. In Argyll and Bute, around 80% of the schools have fewer
than two full-time teachers, and some have a roll numbering just two or
three pupils. In remote areas like this the travelling time between some
schools can be measured in days rather than hours. Now the local
education division has established its own bulletin board service,
Argyll Online, to tackle the huge problems caused by the lack of peer
contact, for both staff and pupils.
Martin Mulholland, who is responsible for information technology in
the division's schools, explains: ''In some of the schools, there is
just one pupil in primary seven, then the next level down is primary
four. But sometimes the pupil will be doing a maths project that
requires them to work with a partner or in a group. Now they can do
that.
''Similarly, if you work in a large school and something like Five to
Fourteen comes in, the burden can be shared out among the staff. In a
rural school, you'd have to do it all yourself.''
The scheme has been such a success that Argyll and Bute is already
looking beyond the basic communications technology. Thirteen schools are
now using video conferencing, allowing pupils and staff to work face to
face.
According to Mr Mulholland, the impact has been ''quite stunning,''
especially in helping the social development of pupils. ''In parts of
Argyll and Bute, the quality of life can be fantastic. But children are
often denied the opportunity to meet, interact and play with their
peers. Video conferencing and e-mail are bridging that gap,'' he says.
One area that has greatly benefited is Gaelic language teaching. Just
four teachers are responsible for teaching more than 1500 primary school
pupils in Argyll and Bute who are learning Gaelic as a second language.
The establishment of video conferencing has drastically cut their
travelling time, allowing the resource to be used more effectively.
''A lot of people want their children to learn Gaelic,'' says Mr
Mulholland. ''But if they live in places like East Kilbride, it can be
difficult for them to hear a range of voices or accents. But whack
technology on top and the isolated learners in East Kilbride can talk to
Gaelic speakers in Tiree.''
However, installing the new technology is not cheap. Leasing a
dedicated phone line from British Telecom can cost as much as #12,000 in
the first year. And even a seemingly minor consideration like the lack
of access to telephone sockets is ''a major limiting factor,'' says Bill
Connolly, adviser in educational computing for Dunbarton division.
''The brave new world of the information superhighway is arriving at
the doors of the schools. The technology is already there. But the
problem is finding finance to put in the infrastructure so schools can
use it.'' The uncertainty caused by local government reorganisation is
only adding to the confusion.
For now, Maggie Pollard remains determined that nothing will disrupt
the progress being made at Richmond Park. ''The philosophy of this
school is that the technology belongs to the children. The rule is that
every child has to use the computers everyday, no matter what.'' At the
moment, she is less worried about financial considerations than the
school's impending foray onto the World Wide Web. ''It's very
exciting,'' she enthuses.
</TEXT>
