<DOCID>GH950829-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Japan teaches the world a lesson in first-class futures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER MCKENZIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650378</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Vouchers for pre-schooling are on the way in scotland. Alexander
McKenzie examines how the initiative compares with nursery provision
elsewhere.
'SIX is too late for the start of schooling'' reads a large notice at
the entrance of the Nishiki Early Learning Centre in Tokyo. ''Give your
children extra years of education'', the notice also goes on to state,
''and watch them flourish''.
The Nishiki is one of 100 or so early learning centres in the Japanese
capital which offer to provide children as young as one, two or three
with a head start in Japan's highly-competitive education race.
Japan is very keen on preschooling. Over 90% of the children entering
the nation's elementary schools have spent at least one year at
kindergarten or nursery school. Many have received two or three years'
preschooling and a growing number have received tuition at a
pre-kindergarten.
Japanese parents are happy to pay for a service which they say their
children enjoy and which, it is widely accepted, provides an excellent
preparation for elementary school. The #16 billion which is spent on
preschooling each year in Japan is reckoned to be the country's
shrewdest investment.
Many parents in the US are also convinced of the benefits of early
learning. Several American studies have shown that children who have
attended kindergarten often go on to settle, learn and behave better at
elementary school.
One much-publicised study concluded that pupils from disadvantaged
families who receive good preschooling fare better in employment than
children from similar backgrounds with no preschooling.
Yet it is left to parents to decide whether they want to invest in
kindergarten lessons. Although some government funds are available to
pay the kindergarten fees for children ''at risk'' most parents have to
pay full fees.
''Parents now realise what little minds are capable of,'' one American
newspaper editorial recently declared. ''Good preschooling means
learning rather than playing.''
In Australian kindergartens, however, the emphasis is still very much
on playing. Early learning, it is argued by many Australian
educationists, puts too much pressure on children and makes them nervous
about failing and risk-taking.
At the same time the increasing cost of kindergarten education is
forcing the Australian government to pass on more of the costs of
preschooling to parents. The increase in attendance fees in some
kindergartens has resulted in a sharp drop in the number of enrolments.
Many European countries, meanwhile, are taking steps to improve both
the quantity and quality of their preschool provision. In France, where
99% of three, four and five-year-olds attend nursery school, the focus
is on improving the quality of the country's early education.
Nursery schools in France, as well as those in Belgium, the
Netherlands and a number of other mainland European countries, are
increasingly being required to offer more structured courses at the
expense of playgroup-type activities.
A good model is provided by the Italian system of preschooling which
offers detailed guidelines about the sort of experiences kindergartens
should be offering their pupils.
Italy's new Orientamenti -- official guidelines -- emphasise six areas
of experience: ''body and movement, speech and words'', ''space, order
and measurement'', ''time and nature'', ''messages, forms and media''
and ''self and others''.
The intention is to provide the best possible preparation for the more
formal learning programmes which begin in the primary school. The
popularity of preschooling in Italy means that over 90% of the
six-year-olds starting primary school there will have attended nursery
school for at least one year.
In Denmark, where 76% of three-year-olds and 81% of four-year-olds
attend nursery school, improvements are being made to the training
courses for nursery school teachers. Students now have to complete a
three-and-a-half year specialised nursery school teaching programme,
covering all aspects of child development, before taking up a career in
nursery education.
The German government is seeking to expand kindergarten education by
promising, from next year, a legal guarantee of kindergarten places for
all children between the ages of three and six.
New kindergartens are being opened to meet the expected demand for
places, particularly in the western part of the country, where the
number of children attending kindergarten has traditionally been lower
than in the former Communist states of Eastern Germany.
Local education authorities, which are struggling to meet the targets
set by the German government, say the quality of preschool places is as
important as the quantity, and that there is a danger that the urgency
of the government's reforms will force class-sizes upwards and the
quality of preschool education will suffer.
In Britain, where more three and four-year-olds are enrolled in
playgroups than in nursery schools, the Government is also looking at
ways of improving pre-school provision. In Scotland, the latest plan
involves providing the parents of some three but mainly four year-olds
with vouchers worth #1100 which can be exchanged for pre-school
services.
Local authorities, playgroups in the voluntary sector, and private
nursery schools all have reservations about the Scottish Office's
proposals, which are out for consultation. But in the independent
nursery sector there is a belief that the scheme will lead to more
nursery school places and more choice for parents.
</TEXT>
