<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thistle chief stung by takeover talk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650382</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Chairman of Partick Thistle, Jim Oliver, vents his frustration over
the elusive consortium which is said to be interested in buying his club
but seems to be negotiating through the media, writes Ken Smith.
WHEN they were handing out tact, Jim Oliver was clearly at the end of
the queue and not paying attention.
The property developer, who has been chairman of Partick Thistle for
over five years, has had little in the way of a public profile -- which
is not surprising in a city where the sporting attention gazes
constantly at David Murray of Rangers and Fergus McCann of Celtic.
Now it is Oliver who is making the headlines as the media feeding
frenzy gnaws on MP George Galloway's announcement that a group of Asian
businessmen want to buy the Firhill club.
Oliver, increasingly exasperated at the lack of contact from any
businessman, speaks his mind, and says the board is not going to walk
away from Firhill simply to satisfy the wishes of ''some Indian with a
curry shop''.
As Charan Gill, the restaurateur mentioned as a possible bidder, has a
turnover many times that of Thistle itself, the remark was indeed crass.
To others it was simply racist. And coming from a club which has avoided
the sectarianism of Rangers and Celtic it was inept.
Yet like many ambitious people, Jim Oliver speaks his mind, seeing no
need to ponder over the nuances of every word. Almost all chairmen of
companies are the same; the difference being that most of them keep an
army of public relations personnel to ensure their thoughts are kept
safely away from the public.
Nor is Oliver apologetic. He says: ''As I understand it he is Indian,
and he owns a curry shop. If he is not an Indian with a curry shop then
I'll apologise.'' He sees nothing racist in that. He explains further,
although to some people he is simply digging a bigger hole: ''I don't
care whether they are Asian or one-eyed black lesbian saxophone players,
if they have the money we will talk to them. But the club is not for
sale.
''To my mind, the whole thing is a spoof. We can't take it
seriously.''
What exasperates Oliver more than anything is that George Galloway has
given press conferences and interviews about the possible bid, yet no
money, no offer, nothing concrete has been produced. Now the alleged
racist remarks of the chairman may become the smokescreen which allows
some of those involved to slip away, having caused unrest at the club,
without ever putting forward a tangible offer.
Looking at it from a business point of view, Oliver's anger is
understandable. Businessmen do not do business through the media, no
matter how much we would like them to. No-one has talked money to the
club, yet the impression was given that a deal was imminent. At a time
when the directors should be concentrating on the season just started,
their attention is diverted.
Even Charan Gill agrees that is not the way to do business and has
withdrawn from the consortium, casting doubts on when a bid, if ever,
will be made.
The Thistle bid, whether it is fact or fantasy, began with a telephone
call to Jim Oliver from Sunday newspaper columnist, and now Thistle fan,
Ron McKay.
Says Oliver: ''He was the guy who before the end of last season
predicted we would be relegation favourites for this season. I'd never
met him, and saw no reason to take his calls. But he insisted it was an
investment proposition. He said he had someone who wanted to invest in
Partick Thistle.
''OK, so I arranged to meet him and George Galloway at eleven o'clock
last Wednesday morning at my golf club, provided the meeting was treated
in confidence.
''Galloway said a group of Asian businessmen -- he couldn't tell me
who they were -- was interested in taking over the club. Incidentally,
it was Galloway who raised the race issue by referring to them
constantly as Asian businessmen.
''I told him it was not for sale. We are six years into a 10-year
programme. We took it from a decrepit club lying eighth in the first
division to a Premier League club run efficiently and profitably.
''So I said 'Fine. You do what you have to do, but as far as I'm
concerned this meeting did not take place.' I left at 11.45 and at 12.30
I was having lunch with my daughter when Ron McKay sits down and
whispers that the media had been on to George and he was trying to
discover how they found out.
''McKay said someone had talked and that he thought it must have been
one of the Asian businessmen. There then followed a series of press
releases.''
Mr Oliver is clearly a bitter man at the turn of events. From his
office he looks across to the new #2.5m stand. A further #1.5m was spent
refurbishing the existing stand, and another #1m has gone on new
floodlights and other improvements.
The club has remained in the Premier League when others like Dundee
United have not. There is a new manager in Murdo McLeod. It should be a
time to look ahead, not fend off media hype.
One point causing confusion is that Oliver says the club is not for
sale. He also says that, like any business, it is for sale if the price
is right. Confusing? Well, it's simple business practice. There is not a
business in the land, from the largest multinational to the corner shop,
which is not for sale if someone comes along with an irresistible offer.
That, though, is not the same as saying it's for sale.
In other words, there is no bargain basement at Firhill. Galloway says
Oliver would have accepted a cheque for #2.5m for control of the club.
No doubt Oliver was simply testing to see if there was any actual money
floating around to give the so-called takeover bid some credence.
As it is, Oliver and his four fellow directors have put in #2.5m into
the club in shares and loans since they took over in 1990. Any buyer
would have to recompense them, and convince the board that there was,
say, a further #2m to be made available to the manager to buy players.
Deputy chairman Brown McMaster is also scathing of the way the
approach has been made. ''It's like a stranger coming to your front door
and saying they are acting for someone who wants to buy your house, even
though it's not for sale, and then demanding that they see round it. You
wouldn't operate like that, so why should we?'' he says.
As Oliver emphasises: ''No businessman has telephoned me, faxed me,
written to me, or contacted me about any offer. Anybody who wanted to
take over this club would have to demonstrate that they could run it
properly, and by their dealings so far, I'd be sceptical about that.
''The danger is that with all this hot air the fans will think there
is all this money out there and we are turning it down. Remember, no
director takes a penny piece out of this club. It is altruism of the
highest order -- stupidity if you like. But we are not going to walk
away simply to satisfy the whim of George Galloway or others. There is
as much chance of that as of me flying out of that window.''
Jim Oliver seemed to have his feet firmly on the ground when he said
it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
