<DOCNO>GH950829-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kirkwood expects his men to atone against 'Well</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650383</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE United manager Billy Kirkwood heads into the Coca-Cola Cup
clash with Motherwell tonight with his team -- favourites for promotion
-- sitting second-bottom of the first division.
Kirkwood yesterday admitted: ''I knew it was going to be difficult for
us but I did not realise just how difficult.
''The good thing, however, about this game coming so quickly after the
defeat at Dunfermline is that it will allow the players the opportunity
to make up for their display at East End Park.
''I am trying to put together a new team here and this allows us to
see how we might fare in the premier division if we can make it back
there in the one season.''
Former Scotland midfielder Dave Bowman, red-carded at the weekend, is
out and will be dealt with by the Tannadice club. Kirkwood said: ''We
lose him straight away for this match, and then he could be out for five
more games if he gets just a couple of yellow cards. We cannot afford
players landing themselves in trouble on the field.''
Kirkwood will still be without David Hannah, while Maurice Malpas is a
doubt. But club skipper Christian Dailly, who began the season under
suspension, will return. Close-season signing Sandy Robertson is likely
to replace Bowman in the middle of the park.
Motherwell, too, have worries, with Chris McCart nursing a knock he
collected at Tynecastle and striker Tommy Coyne still unavailable.
Manager Alex McLeish warns: ''Dundee United are probably the toughest of
the unseeded teams. We must be aware of that when we travel to Tannadice
tomorrow.''
Going to Broadwood, Hibernian face a similarly dangerous journey. It
was just a year ago that they crashed 2-0 to Airdrie in the same
tournament.
Last night club skipper Gordon Hunter, who will return to action
tonight after suspension, recalled: ''We had won our first seven games
last season when we came to play Airdrie and we lost. To my mind they
are the most difficult cup opponents anyone can get from the first
division.
''The lads looked really good at Firhill on Saturday and we were
unlucky not to win the game. Basically, though, we were making chances
and that was something we never seemed able to do last year.''
Two more suspension victims, David Farrell and Willie Miller, are
still mising and Keith Wright's troublesome back injury could keep him
sidelined.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
