<DOCNO>GH950829-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Champagne for Tim</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE AND GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650384</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MASTER trainer Reg Akehurst executed a long-range plan to deliver a
memorable first triumph in the ''Amateurs' Derby'' for Tim McCarthy at
Epsom yesterday.
He repaid the leading point-to-point rider for his preparation of many
of the Akehurst stars at the McCarthy livery yard with the winning mount
on Proton in the Moet &amp; Chandon Silver Magnum.
The champagne was put on ice while they sweated out a stewards'
inquiry into a clash between the three protagonists 50 yards out.
But the corks were popping after Proton was confirmed the half-length
winner over Casual Water, whose Italian jockey Filipo Grasso-Caprioli
received a two-day ban (September 6 and 7) for careless riding, his
mount having pushed third-placed Flight Lieutenant on to Proton.
''Tim won on Proton for me last year and I have had this race in mind
for some time,'' admitted Akehurst. ''The horse will probably go for the
November Handicap now.''
McCarthy has won the Kim Muir on Fighting Words, and the Horse And
Hound Cup on Federal Trooper among his 130 successes in Arab racing,
point-to-points, and under rules.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why Brown must stay with Leighton as first choice. Goram needs more time to re-stake that claim</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650385</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND manager Craig Brown will name his squad of players today to
face Finland at Hampden in a game where victory will send the nation
into the European Championship Finals.
That game is next week and while Brown was still agonising over the
position of Rangers' goalkeeper Andy Goram last night I believe that the
Ibrox man should be left on the international sidelines.
Not for good -- but certainly until he finds himself free of the
strains that fighting back from injury and being asked to play in
Europe's top club tournament have brought him.
Brown named him last time around in good faith. Since then all of us
have gone through the soccer soap opera which surrounded Goram and his
decision to withdraw because he was not ''mentally attuned''.
Brown and the SFA accepted that explanation and now they must further
accept that Goram still may not be able to focus properly on a match
where, in any case, he would be second choice at best.
Brown has a No 1 at the moment in Jim Leighton and for the next two
competitive games the Hibs' veteran should be allowed to play and
cotninue a challenge for top spot next summer which can only benefit the
national side.
We do not have enough quality players available to allow Brown to slam
the door shut on the Rangers' star. Instead the team manager may have to
do some subtle horse-trading much in the manner of his most illustrious
predecessor, the late Jock Stein.
Stein would always allow some latitude for players he needed and often
left men out if their clubs had important games, knowing that when
Scotland needed the key men he would get them.
Something of that order may be necessary in the current situation. If
the goalkeeper still feels he would have problems then he should be left
alone until these problems have cleared. But he should not be dismissed
from the Scotland stage because some day Brown will need his talents.
Perhaps even next summer -- if we have qualified.
I don't think that the preparations for next week's crucial Hampden
match should be disrupted by any off-the-field bickerings and the best
way to do that would be to leave Goram out.
That would allow Brown and his chosen men to focus on the real issue
-- victory over the Finns. And Brown believes that given his usual core
of players that can be achieved.
He knows too that despite injuries still affecting some players he
would want -- notably Paul McStay and Duncan Ferguson -- others are
coming good at the right time.
Aberdeen striker Scott Booth who has made a stunning start to the
season will be named for the first time in almost a year. He will be
joined by John Spencer of Chelsea who was injured before the victory
over Greece.
The remainder of the squad will be on the usual lines. There won't be
shocks because there is little room for manoeuvre at this stage of the
qualifying process.
Brown insisted yesterday:''It will be a bigger than usual squad
because this is a bigger than usual game and I want to be covered in
case of injuries this week. But I'm confident that if we have our key
personnel available then we can get the required result.''
With or without his troubled goalkeeper he might have added...
</TEXT>
</DOC>
