<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Appeal to regulate new TV set-up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650389</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TELEVISION watchdogs today called on the Government to let them
regulate subscriber and pay-as-you-view systems, which they fear could
become a monopoly for Mr Rupert Murdoch's News International after the
digital broadcasting revolution.
The Independent Television Commission argued that it, not Oftel,
should be the regulatory body for conditional access systems, in the
expectation of 18 or more new channels before the end of the century.
Otherwise, the complexity of subscriber technology, which involves
encryption and a set-top black box, could lead to a race and eventual
monopoly for Mr Murdoch's companies, the ITC said.
News International owns News Datacom Ltd, providers of Britain's
existing conditional access system for satellite services, as well as
most of BSkyB, the company that provides programming for many of those
services.
The ITC said one company was likely to become dominant and so the
interests of broadcasters and viewers had to be safeguarded, although
investors should also reap the rewards of developing the system.
''The ITC would urge Government to reconsider its proposal to licence
conditional access for digital terrestrial services via Oftel under the
Telecommunications Act.
''Both the encryption and subscriber management aspects of conditional
access are issues which affect the availability, content, and diversity
of the subscription-funded programme services which are delivered to
viewers by broadcasters, and the terms upon which those services are
delivered,'' it said.
However, the ITC ''broadly welcomed'' the Government's May White Paper
liberalising media ownership for newspapers and television companies.
The proposals will allow newspaper proprietors with less than 20% of
the total circulation to own up to two ITV television channels, paving
the way for new cross-media ownership, although clipping the wings of
News International, owner of five national titles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bizarre pleas of odd travellers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERPLEXING pleas from air passengers, including one traveller who
asked for a seat away from the window because she was frightened of
bats, were disclosed by a holiday airline.
The year produced a bewildering number of bizarre queries, said the
customer services department at Air 2000.
These included:
* The elderly lady who wanted to take her canary aboard a jet to test
oxygen levels so that ''if he drops dead you will know to let us have
the masks''.
* A male passenger who asked to be seated away from his wife and,
preferably, next to a young, single woman passenger.
* The young couple who asked for separate seats because they would
need space to spread out since they were newly married.
* The woman who asked not to be given a window seat for her night
flight home as she was terrified of bats.
* An anti-smoker who wanted a special seat at the airport to which she
was flying so she could avoid any smokers in the arrival hall.
''We get hundreds of requests, some very routine, but occasionally we
receive more amusing ones,'' said Air 2000 marketing and commercial
director Bill Kirkwood.
''The heat always seems to make our customers more frisky than normal,
as well as more demanding.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bomb threat closes airports</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650391</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW YORK: All flights at New York city's three main airports were
suspended last night because of a bomb threat. Tracon, the Long Island
air traffic control centre that guides landings and take-offs for
Kennedy, La Guardia, and Newark airports, was evacuated.
A spokeswoman for the Port Authority, which operates the three
airports, said flights were halted at 5.42pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dancing and instruction on eight-day train journey</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RENEE SCHOOF</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650392</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Beijing
AN eight-day train journey from Warsaw ended tonight with music and
flowers for the 250 women who arrived for an international women's
meeting.
Children waited to greet the train with their gifts. The arriving
women, primarily from Eastern Europe and former Soviet republics, had
used their days aboard to make final preparations for the meeting -- and
have a little fun.
''It was more than I expected. It was really nice. We were dancing
every night until three in the morning,'' said Desma Kos, of Croatia,
while waiting to board a bus to her hotel.
The meeting brings together non-governmental groups that will try to
influence the UN World Conference on Women, which opens next week. The
buses took the women to Huairou, 30 miles north of Beijing, where the
meeting begins tomorrow.
While travelling the Trans-Siberian railway, the women received
training in how to take part in the NGO Forum, said Stacey Gilbert of
San Francisco, who works for the United Nations Development Programme
that organised the trip.
''I think they have a lot more confidence to face the issues and
really get what they want out of the conference,'' she said.
As she spoke, one of the Chinese men escorting the women to their
buses stepped up without a word, roughly grabbed her by the arm and
pulled  her away. She took it calmly, shouting back with a smile: ''Got
to go.''
Sakiko Fukuraka, one of the UN organisers on the trip, said the group
produced a declaration about women's role in conflict resolution en
route to Beijing.
''All these negotiating teams are made up of men -- no women,'' she
added. ''Women should be involved in peace negotiations.''
Vanessa Vadim, daughter of American actress Jane Fonda, described the
trip as ''incredible''.
''Everyone wanted to stay on,'' she said. ''We haven't finished our
work.'' -- AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish launch for charities alliance bid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR Party leaders are using Scotland as the launchpad for a major
effort to build a new partnership with the voluntary sector, starting at
a meeting in Edinburgh today.
The initiative, which will bring together representatives of charities
and local government and politics in Scotland, has the support of party
leader Tony Blair and Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson.
Heading the one-day conference will be Shadow Minister for Scottish
Affairs John McFall. He said it was fitting that the first steps in this
exercise in partnership should be taken in Scotland, which had a
tradition of community activity which went back generations.
Mr Alun Michael, who is Shadow Minister for the Voluntary Sector, said
the party would be setting out Labour's fresh vision of a partnership
between the voluntary sector and government, but he also promised to
spend most of the time listening.
''This is not a one-off meeting. We will take away the concerns and
suggestions that we hear, we will continue the dialogue at a more local
level and with specialist groups throughout the United Kingdom,'' he
said.
There also would be more detailed and structured discussions during
the coming year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>I will be back, says Jacobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650394</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Gary Jacobs, who gave WBC welterweight champion Pernell
Whitaker such a tough battle before losing on points in Atlantic City at
the weekend, blasted out yesterday: ''If Frank Bruno is good enough to
get four shots at a world title then surely I deserve another chance.''
Now on a family holiday in America, Jacobs vows he will be back to
chase his dream, and he is more than happy to leave his future in the
hands of Mickey Duff.
''I've got the best management team in the business, and you can take
it as certain I will be back,'' said Jacobs, who added: ''I just want to
enjoy my holiday and forget boxing for a couple of weeks. Mickey will be
working on another fight for me, and I'll let him worry about that.
Hopefully, it will be another world title shot.
''I deserve it. I won and successfully defended the European title
away from home to climb into the official No.1 challenger spot for the
world title -- nobody handed me anything on a plate. I've just taken the
world's best all the way and that must surely mean I can fight a bit,
too.''
Asked whether his best option now would be a meeting with Ireland's
WBO champion Eamonn Loughran, who retained his title at the weekend,
Jacobs, who has tended to dismiss WBO titles in the past, thought for a
moment.
''The Americans are beginning to recognise WBO championships more
these days, although they don't carry the same prestige as the others,''
he said. ''It could be Loughran, but whether he would want to fight me
is a different matter.''
* VINNIE Vecchione, who stepped into the ring to save his fighter
Peter McNeeley from Mike Tyson 89 seconds into their bout nine days ago,
will get his #119,000 share of the purse after all. The Nevada State
Athletic Commission found no proof that the manager acted illegally.
</TEXT>
