<HEADLINE>TWO WILD CARDS COMPLETE BERNARD GALLACHER'S LINE-UP FOR THE RYDER CUP QUEST. The men who carry hopes of Europe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650395</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Age 32. Born Glasgow. Majors: 0. Caps: 2 (1991-93).
Record: P8 W4 H2 L2.
Says he lost sleep over his play-off defeat to Steve Elkington in the
US PGA, but it did not stop him retaining German Open this weekend.
First win since same event last August. Europe's leading money-winner
for the past two seasons, Montgomerie is the world's highest-ranked
player without a major. Also beaten in a play-off for the US Open last
year. Partnered Nick Faldo last time and they lost only once in four
games.
38. Majors: 2 (1985-93 Masters). Caps: 7 (1981-83-85-87-89-91-93).
Record: P29 W13 H5 L11.
Has lifted at least one title every season since 1979 and has not
missed a half-way cut in Europe for over four years. Langer won his
third Volvo PGA Championship in May, but missed this month's US PGA with
back injury. Key figure in 1985 and 1987 wins, but missed the six-foot
putt in 1991 which gave America victory. Showed character with
tournament victory a week later.
42. Majors: 0. Caps: 7 (1981-83-85-87-89-91-93).
Record: P23 W4 H6 L13.
Forever to be remembered as the man who sank the putt in 1985 which
ended America's 28-year grip on the trophy. Overall cup record is poor,
but has been playing some of the best golf of his career this season,
winning Italian and Irish Opens. Goal is to top Order of Merit for first
time, but now second to Montgomerie after being pipped for German Open.
Had septic toe at last match, played only one game and had to withdraw
from singles.
38. Majors: 0. Caps: 1 (1993).
Record: P2 L2.
Lost Open championship play-off to John Daly last month after dramatic
finish. Duffed chip, then made 65-foot putt to tie. Former factory
worker and caddie w ho became first Italian to play in the match in
1993, but his debut ended in tears. Was one up with two to play against
Davis Love, but lost both holes and Love's point clinched American win.
Four runner-up finishes this season, but no win for over two years.
38. Majors: 5 (1979-84-88 Open, 1980-83 Masters). Caps: 7
(1979-83-85-87-89-91-93).
Record: P34 W19 H5 L10.
With Jose Maria Olazabal has formed most successful pairing in cup
history -- just two defeats in 15 games. Earned eighth cap with
brilliant end to 1994, but since 71st career win in Spanish Open in May
has suffered alarming slump, missing halfway cut in five of past six
tournaments. Hindered by bad back, too, he wants no repeat of 1993
match, where he asked to be left out of second-day fourballs.
29.
Majors: 0.
Caps: 1 (1991).
Record: P2 L2.
Quiet man of European golf. Made unhappiest of debuts four years ago.
Heavily beaten in foursomes, first partnered by Colin Montgomerie and
then by Nick Faldo, Gilford was the European left out of the singles
after injury to American Steve Pate. Earns second cap now following
superlative five-shot win in 1994 European Open. In spare time, looks
after herd of cattle on farm which he and his father own.
41. Majors: 0. Caps: 6 (1977-79-81-89-91-93).
Record: P22 W7 H1 L14.
Switched to broomhandle putter at Moroccan Open in March -- and
immediately won. He nearly abandoned it at Open, but perseverance paid
off with eighth-place finish. Fined for his behaviour at the 1979 match,
he is now chairman of the European tour's tournament committee. Declined
invitation to the US PGA championship two weeks ago, but clinched
seventh cap at the German Open. Did not win a point last time.
41. Majors: 0. Caps: 5 (1977-81-85-87-89).
Record: P13 W6 H1 L6.
Has not won an event since 1988 English Open, but second five times in
last two seasons. His runner-up finish in Czech Open, the last-but-one
qualifying event, earned him a recall.
''I still have to learn how to win again,'' he said at end of last
year. ''It's all a question of nerve, of controlling yourself when you
get into a winning position.'' Last game in cup was record 8 and 7
defeat at hands of Tom Kite.
28. Majors: 0. Caps: debut.
Becomes the second Swede to play in Ryder Cup, following Joakim
Haeggman last time.
Went to Arizona State University and played on same team as Phil
Mickelson, who now makes his cup debut, too.
Turned pro in 1990 and, in first full season, was part of winning
Swedish teams in Dunhill and World Cups.
Almost made Ryder Cup, too, but this time he did manage to hang on to
a place despite missing cut in final two qualifying events.
33. Majors: 0. Caps: debut.
Relieved to make Ryder Cup at last. Buckled in 1989 when on verge of
making team and pressure showed again at German Open when he played
final nine holes in 42, but stayed tenth in table. Changed to
broomhandle putter last year and this season grabbed first win since
1990 at Catalan Open, then added English Open after play-off with Colin
Montgomerie. Said in May he had no interest in the cup because the
pressure was destroying players.
38. Majors: 5 (1987-90-92 Open, 1989-90 Masters). Caps: 9
(1977-79-82-83-85-87-89-91-93).
Record: P36 W19 H4 L13.
Rejoined American tour this year, but after early success has had
disappointing season. Finished outside top 20 in all four majors and so
needed wild card invitation, as he did in 1985 and 1991. Mainly blames
putting problems for results and at US PGA this month abandoned
cross-handed method he had used for a year. If he hits form he will
stillbe player the Americans least want to face.
29. Majors: 1 (1994 Masters). Caps: 4 (1987-89-91-93).
Record: P20 W12 H2 L6.
Handed wild card for fourth time -- 1989 was only time he qualified.
Instant hit with Ballesteros when they paired on his debut. Underwent
toe surgery in January, but problem with his right foot returned with
growth of small tumour. Has limped all year and there are doubts whether
he can play two rounds a day at Oak Hill, but better recent form -- and
the parternship with Ballesteros -- saw him preferred to Ian Woosnam.
</TEXT>
