<DOCNO>GH950829-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Encouraging results from Synergy rape trials</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650397</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH trials of the composite hybrid rape Synergy have done
''encouragingly well'' for the second year running, according to Kerr
Walker, Aberdeen-based rape specialist with the Scottish Agricultural
College. He reported a yield advantage of more than 20% over other
varieties used as controls.
His advice is that farmers who are drilling several fields should
consider using Synergy for about 20% of the area. ''If you've just got
one field, then stick with a conventional variety,'' he added.
In Scottish Agronomy trials, Synergy yielded 25% higher than controls
-- Apex, Bristol, Envol, Express and Falcon. It was 0.85 tonnes a
hectare ahead of Commanche, the highest yielding commercially available
rape.
Felix Patton of supplier CPB Twyford said that in appropriate
circumstances Synergy should give at least a #50 a hectare gross margin
bonus after deducting extra seed and growing costs.
The top yielding Scottish Synergy crop this year has been eight
hectares grown by Mary Singleton at Scotston of Kirkside, St Cyrus, near
Montrose. The return was 4.7 tonnes a hectare, beating last year's Envol
by 1.2 tonnes a hectare. The autumn drilling this year will be just over
six hectares and the only management change being considered is an
increase in the amount of sulphur.
</TEXT>
