<DOCNO>GH950829-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Good sales should lift T&amp;N results at half-time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650398</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE bank holiday means this is a shorter week and most of the the
major companies reporting are concentrated on Thursday.
Tomorrow, though, does see the half-year figures from motor component
manufacturer T&amp;N and the market will be looking for a measure of
respectability after last year's late exceptional charge of #140m for
past asbestos business which virtually wiped out annual pre-tax profits.
T&amp;N's share price has started to emerge from the doldrums in recent
weeks and could strengthen further on the back of a solid performance.
Projections range from #66m to #75m for a consensus of #71.9m which
would compare with #61m for the first half of 1994.
Improved sales and margins across many of the company's 10 divisions
should underpin the results. T&amp;N is expected to stick to its restrictive
dividend policy for 1995. The group has forecast an interim of 3p and a
total of 6p is in prospect for the year against 10.85p last time.
On Thursday, aero-engine and industrial turbines manufacturer
Rolls-Royce is thought likely to announce an increase of possibly around
50% in first-half profits, boosted by heavy cost cutting over the past
two years. Market projections are for taxable profits to jump to between
#50m and #65m against #40m last time.
The interim dividend is expected to be held at 2p. The company has
warned of a dip in engine deliveries this year but investors are looking
to when the core new aircraft and engine spares market comes out of
recession.
Also on Thursday, hotels and betting group Ladbroke will be announcing
its interim figures with the market forecasting a range from #52m to
#60m for a consensus of #56.7m compared with #57.3m for the same period
of 1994. Strong interest will centre on the group's betting shops.
Last month, Ladbroke Racing blamed the National Lottery, and in
particular Instant scratch cards, for its decision to cut 200 jobs out
of a total of 650 at its London head office and other locations --
including nine at Grangemouth. No change is envisaged in the 2.4p
interim dividend.
Reckitt &amp; Colman (Thursday) will be providing details of its
first-half progress. The figures will be the first since the group sold
its mustard business to Unilever in May as part of its decision to
concentrate on household prducts.
A half-year figure ranging from #149m to #162m for a consensus of
#158.3m could be in prospect and an increase in the interim dividend
from 6.95p to up to 7.5p.
A good performance is expected from the Macfarlane Group of packaging
companies when it reveals half-time progress, again on Thursday.
At the annual general meeting in Glasgow in May the chairman, Lord
Macfarlane of Bearsden, said 1995 had started strongly with sales and
profits well ahead of the same period last year despite pressure on
margins.
He said he would be disappointed if the group failed to make a taxable
profit of #20m this year. Last year profits rose 28% to #16.3m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
