<DOCNO>GH950829-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two US banks in $10bn merger</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650399</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New York, Monday -- Banking giants Chase Manhattan Corporation and
Chemical Banking Corporation said today they would join in a $10bn
merger that will create the largest bank in the United States and one of
the biggest in the world.
The combination of Chemical, America's fourth-largest bank, and Chase
Manhattan, the sixth-largest, is the biggest ever in the banking
industry, which is undergoing a spate of mergers as companies look to
cut costs or expand into other business lines or new territories.
''This is a strategic merger, not the sale of a company,'' Chase
chairman and chief executive Thomas Labrecque said at a joint news
conference with Walter Shipley, Chemical's chairman and chief executive
officer.
Mr Shipley, 59, will become chairman and chief executive of the new
institution. Mr Labrecque, 56, will be president and chief operating
officer of the new company, which will retain the Chase name.
''We decided this was the best route for our shareholders, our
customers and our employees,'' Mr Labrecque added.
The two executives said that the combined company expects to see
double-digit earnings growth and achieve a return on equity of at least
18%.
The new company will have $297bn in assets and $20bn in shareholders'
equity, overtaking Citicorp as the biggest bank in the United States and
becoming the fourth largest in the world.
The new Chase, which will have operations in 39 states domestically
and 51 countries around the world, is expected to cut about 12,000 jobs
from a combined staff of about 75,000.
''We propose to utilise the natural turnover that takes place (in
personnel) to take care of layoffs,'' Mr Shipley said, noting that each
bank experiences about a 20% annual turnover in staff, especially among
lower paid workers.
The deal is expected to save the new institution about $1500m
annually, starting within three years, the banks said.
''It is accretive from Day One,'' Mr Labrecque said.
The boards of directors of the rival banks approved the merger
yesterday, and the deal is expected to be completed in the first quarter
of next year. Shareholder and regulatory approval is still needed.
The Federal Reserve and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency,
which would have to approve the merger, said they would have no comment
until a merger application is filed. A Securities and Exchange
Commission spokesman also would not comment on the merger.
Mr Shipley and Mr Labrecque said the financial services industry has
become so broad and so diverse that they did not expect any objections
to the deal on anti-trust grounds.
''We do not anticipate any significant anti-trust problems,'' Mr
Shipley said. -- Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
