<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Construction group places shares with institutions. Morrison seeks funds by going to the market</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG, ECONOMICS EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650400</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER bucking the recession in the UK building industry for the past
five years, Edinburgh-based Morrison Construction Group is coming to the
stock market, through a placing of shares with institutions.
The new capital raised will allow Morrison, controlled from Scotland
since a management buy-out in 1989, to accelerate a growth rate which is
already the envy of many rivals. Since the buy-out, shareholder' funds
have grown from #1m to #18.6m, on turnover now well above #200m and
pre-tax profits of #7.6m in the year to March.
Morrison is active in four sectors -- building and property
development, civil engineering, utility and energy, and housebuilding.
The group is moving progressively away from traditional competitive
tender work, adopting a creative approach to winning new business which,
in the past week, triggered a row over who will be asked to build the
new Inverness headquarters of the North of Scotland Water Authority.
A flotation prospectus is expected within two weeks. Impact day is set
for September 27. The sponsor is Noble Grossart; the broker, Natwest
Securities.
Morrison was founded in Tain in 1948 by Alexander Morrison, father of
the two current dominant shareholders, Fraser and Gordon Morrison. In
1974, a controlling 80% stake was sold to Consolidated African Selection
Trust.
The Morrison family stayed with the business as it passed through
various hands -- including BP for a year -- and ended up as part of the
Charter Consolidated empire. In 1989, Fraser Morrison, now chairman of
Highlands and Islands Enterprise, and his younger brother Gordon bought
back control and returned the group headquarters to Edinburgh.
The results achieved since have bucked the recessionary trend in the
rest of the industry. Even in 1993, when most construction groups were
deeply in the red, Morrison managed to turn in reduced pre-tax profits
of #3.3m.
The Morrison name is familiar on road, motorway and bridge contracts
across Scotland. The group is currently on its third M74 contract,
resolving, under sub-contract, a problem-ridden section let to two
Italian groups.
The dominant division, in both turnover and operating profit terms is
building and property development, where it is developing Strathclyde
Business Park in Lanarkshire and is about to start work, in
collaboration with Cala, on Exchange Plaza, the last link in Edinburgh's
new conference complex. Exchange Plaza has already been sold on to a
financial institution, before a stone has been laid.
In England, Morrison owned Chester City Football Club for a time, as
part of a complex deal to relocate the football and build a retail park
on Chester's old ground.
Morrison has a reputation for technical innovation. On one recent
contract -- a joint venture with a German partner -- an entire underpass
was prefabricated and jacked under a railway line in South Wales without
having to halt the trains.
In the energy and utilities sector Morrison is working in partnership
with British Gas and the English water companies. The division deploys
about 200 two-person teams on around 75,000 separate jobs each year,
right across England.
Housebuilding, on the other hand, is restricted to Scotland, and is
increasingly focused on low-cost, social housing. It sold 344 units last
year and has been consistently profitable. Morrison also operates nine
quarries across Scotland.
The group has a small but growing overseas presence. It was working in
Kuwait five days after the war ended and is still working there.
Morrison also has exposure in Azerbaijan, Berlin and St Petersburg.
It is also bidding for work under the Government's private finance
initiative. But it is Morrison's creative approach to winning new work,
through its network of 27 business development teams across the country,
which differentiates it most from many of its rivals.
Around 50% of all its work comes from this approach, which eschews the
traditional ''here's the tender document give us the lowest price''
method.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
