<DOCNO>GH950829-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Renault doubles its profits</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650401</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris, Monday -- French carmaker Renault today reported that its
profits excluding exceptional items more than doubled in the first half
of 1995 on a surge in operating income fuelled by a rise in French car
sales.
Renault's six-month net attributable profit of Fr1755m barely exceeded
its 1994 first-half profit of Fr1753m but the 1994 figure included more
than Fr1000m of onet-time gains. They included proceeds from the sale
last year of a building and of shares in Volvo AB following the collapse
of Renault's proposed link-up with the Swedish group.
Renault's operating income surged to Fr1515m in the first six months
of the year from Fr688m as its car and commercial vehicle businesses
swung back into the black.
The results will be welcomed both by the Government, which plans to
complete the privatisation of Renault begun last year, and by investors
who have seen shares they bought at Fr165 slide steadily to close at
Fr147 today, down 6.5 on the day.
The Government recently said it would sell control of Renault, in
which it retains 53%.
The improved half-year results reflect a 7.7% rise in French car sales
in the first half of the year, propelled by a state rebate programme
that expired on June 30. Renault's sales rose 7.1% to Fr96.21bn in the
first half.
</TEXT>
