<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Andras Schiff, Usher Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650403</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALFRED BRENDEL -- like, in Edinburgh, the late Hans Gal -- has been
known to deplore performances of Schubert's great B-flat major piano
sonata that enormously enlarge the first movement by including the
composer's designated exposition repeat.
Andras Schiff thus enlarged it -- or, to put it another way, performed
it complete -- in the last of his late-night Schubert recitals on
Sunday, and the music could only be said to benefit. As in all fine
performances of Schubert's largest works, you were made to feel you had
travelled an immense distance in the 15 or so minutes the movement took
to perform. But you also recognised that the pianist trusted Schubert
enough to let him set his own pace and to fill the amount of space he
needed.
The unhurried unrolling of the opening theme, and the mysterious trill
in the bass that serves as its pendant, had in any case made plain that
this was to be the most spacious of performances. And as a result, by
the time the first movement finally reached its destination, the
landscape opened out even more broadly on a slow movement offering new
worlds of experience.
The speed was not so slow as to be trudging, but it was not so fast as
to sound impatient. Moreover, it led to a scherzo that was suitably
capricious and mercurial -- proof that Schiff plays Schubert fast when
the occasion demands -- and a finale whose swift changes of mood were
keenly controlled without blurring on the Bosendorfer piano which,
throughout these recitals, has served as Schiff's, and Schubert's, ideal
voice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650404</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Inspiration, it seems, is in the eye of the beholder. Choreographer
Pina Bausch once caught sight of a field of flowers, closely guarded by
Alsatian dogs. The sudden contrast between the breathtaking beauty and
calm of the flowers, the stark ferocity of the dogs, lodged in her
imagination. And out of that recollected image she subsequently
developed Nelken, a powerful piece of dance-theatre that sets the
dreams, desires and hopes of youth against an abrasive reality fraught
with manifestations of our deepest fears. Highly acclaimed wherever it
has been performed, Nelken (it means carnations) opens at the Playhouse
in Edinburgh on Thursday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legacy is an open book</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUTH WISHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL, DIARY</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650405</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* FIRST there were spells with the Fringe and Assembly Theatre, then
working on the first Book Festival with Jenny Brown in 1983 and again
from 1986 to 1991 before taking over as director herself. All in all,
says Shona Munro, terrifying both of us with the thought, she's been
involved in the Festival in some guise for around 20 years.
Which is the principal reason she's announced that this will be her
last bookfest before she moves on to pastures new and not quite yet
determined.
She takes with her some cracking memories of the biennial Charlotte
Square extravaganzas, she says. And often the real high spots were gigs
that looked too esoteric on paper to capture the popular imagination.
''I remember worrying about scheduling a session with three female
poets in the Spiegeltent, for instance. But the mix of Wendy Cope, Liz
Lochhead, and Eintou Pearl Springer was just a joy. So too was the event
with Christabel Bielenberg and Jung Chang two years ago. People
sometimes talk about the Book Festival not being literary, but that's a
dangerous word. We're not, and never have been, about high art or high
fiction or high anything. We're about reminding people that books are
part of everyday life and books are fun.''
That benign propaganda begins in the children's tent with the
deliberate juxtaposition of books and silly balloons, making all the
right connections with fledgling readers.
''And for that matter with writers. I always like to think that some
of the kids who come in here go on to become authors as well.''
Working on seven out of the eight Book Festivals hasn't dimmed her
evangelical zeal: ''I still get a great kick out of seeing people
queueing up every day till we open at 10. And about the fact that we get
five or six thousand people through the door every day. I think we offer
unique opportunities for people to meet favourite authors and find out
that they're actually real people. Of course a lot of people in the
business arrive here with their own agenda, but our bottom line is that
we make books accessible.''
Now that this year's two-week bookathon is over, and the Speigeltent,
alas, is folded away, the hunt goes on in earnest for Shona's successor.
Anyone who thinks the job a glamorous swan with the stars of the
publishing firmament need not apply. As Shona points out, it's a
happening which has no safety net. Every penny has to be raised and one
bad year could kill it off. So what does the outgoing director consider
the prime qualities for the right candidate?
''You could call it a skills mix. The ability to deal with big authors
and TV crews and a working knowledge of how to unblock the toilets!''
* FOR many years the Festival organisers and the local politicians
were wont to wrangle over how relevant the annual event was to the
natives. The collective angst often resulted in an unhappy piece of
tokenism which hit the budget without delivering anything resembling
real involvement. Now a much more fruitful partnership is being built,
not least in the field of dance.
Two separate events this last fortnight convinced me that the policy
has now hit the right set of tracks. The first was the use of
schoolchildren by the Miami City Ballet company in their version of
Nutcracker. The auditions for this event were oversubscribed, but
Lothian region reports that over the run some 90 children got the
opportunity to dance with one of the world's premier dance companies
with over 50 schools involved. And watching this particularly
child-centred Balanchine production you knew all these kids had been
given an experience with which they would almost certainly bore their
grandchildren.
A week later subtropical temperatures did nothing to dampen the
enthusiasm of another group of youngsters strutting their stuff in a
Show and Share in the gym of Broughton High School. For the second year
running ScottishPower funded four projects with the Mark Morris Dance
Group involving activities as varied as summer schools for secondary
pupils and workshops, with the company involving special needs groups
and senior citizens. The huge bonus of being able to use the Morris
dancers (sic) is that company's infectious enthusiasm which had quite
clearly infected their latest part-timers.
Add in a Festival masterclass with Scottish Ballet and former New York
City Ballet star Violette Verdy, pilot music workshops in schools, and a
similar outreach programme with TAG theatre company and you get the kind
of cross-fertilisation which leads to a much healthier relationship
between the citizenry and the annual arts extravaganza which has grown,
Topsy style, in its midst.
And, as the Festival has no doubt figured out for itself, it doesn't
hurt to start growing your own audiences.
* SO how to provide rehearsal space for Ruckblick featuring an
ensemble with several pianos and a harpsichord about their person. Think
laterally. And fix them up, as associate Festival director James Waters
did, with a gig in a piano shop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Now he's seriously hilarious. Sean Hughes, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650406</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE'S long purveyed a sort of winsome, floppy-fringed adolescent
daftness, leading to his adoption as hot-boy laff-totty to a generation
of female undergraduates. But now Sean's grown up and become tougher,
angrier, and more serious, while remaining every bit as hilarious.
During his two-night stand Sean demonstrated his complete mastery of the
stand-up's art.
Chiefly, he took his audience to places they weren't sure they wanted
to go, exploring drug-induced paranoia and self-delusion; male
self-deception; our wilful abandonment of familial obligation. In
establishing that men are truly scum-like simpletons and women are
weird, he crafted awe-inspring amounts of laughter. More than two nights
next Fringe, please, Sean.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Klub, Calton Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650407</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIX friends. A single mum, a bulimic, a TV soap star who's miserable
-- this is Generation ''?'', where some have jobs, others don't and
there's a sense of being Generation Lost, Generation Betrayed,
Generation Unnecessary. There's only one place where it feels right, one
place where they can be happy -- the Klub.
Ignore the beginning which casts a shadow of moody posey-ness over
this production by Frantic Theatre. Once the piece is up and running --
there's a lot of fast, clever movement in Klub -- it takes on an
engaging humanity, full of humour yet tinged with the real despair of
feeling the world doesn't want to know about you, your hopes or your
problems. I went to this because it fitted a time slot on my schedule. I
came away vastly impressed and smiling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kiuston Halle, French Institute</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650408</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEWSPAPER as a raw material was carried to its apogee by David Mach in
his 1999 Tramway Paper Parthenon installation where he piled, placed,
and folded several tons of newsprint into massive but immaculate
pillars. After that, it's downhill all the way.
Thus Kiuston Halle, a dancer turned photographer, can't really compete
with her yellowing newspaper cartwheels and big cross bisecting the
French Institute's elegant first-floor gallery. Her curved wall pieces
with their thin film of faint photographs of lobster pots, broken
sculptures or hands stuck across the sheets like large open books or
folio volumes are better, but this show in one of Edinburgh's most
beautiful spaces is really not up to its previous high standards. Till
September 20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>John James, Acoustic Music Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650409</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
''A TRIBUTE to the guitar greats -- and Bert Weedon,'' promises John
James. And so it proves. Django Rheinhardt, Chet Atkins, Scotty Moore,
Merle Travis, and Doc Watson all appear in spirit. Bert Weedon, too (''I
like that string''). The Rev Gary Davis, who unlike James the Guitar
wasn't Welsh but was --     exaggeratedly casual shrug -- ''OK'', has
his style slowly dissected and explained to make it look effortless.
Then speeded up to sound impossible.
On top of this, James is, in the nicest possible way, nuts. Sandwiched
between Atkins and Rheinhardt, comes a potted history of inventions and
political correctness rolled into one, wherein his between-line drawn
breaths at least give you a fighting chance of working out one pun
before he hits you with the next.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New Towns, Royal Fine Art Commission</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650410</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Fine Art Commission advises government on the visual impact
and design quality of buildings and roads. As arbiters of quality it
often sees fit to reject projects as not up to the mark. Fair enough.
But this appalling exhibition, which totally lacks direction and basic
information as well as being visually illiterate, makes one reassess
their role. If this is the best the Fine Art Commission can do, God help
us.
Architects will find many reasons for complaint -- but the public will
despair at this jumble of badly displayed photos of Cumbernauld, East
Kilbride, Glenrothes, Irvine, and Livingston which lack labels and
dates, never mind explanation as to the then real vision involved.
Poor Miss Elizabeth Mitchell, who hammered in the first peg in 1948 or
Gillespie Kidd and Coia building such wonderful churches in the 1960s.
If they could see this dog's breakfast of a show, they would weep.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Highland Fling, Diverse Attractions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIELLE NAGLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650411</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNDER-EIGHTS are dancing in the aisles throughout this trans-Scotland
hunt for stolen haggises.
The Happy Gang, alias Beth, Spatz and Mr P, have found a formula that
works and only, for adult eyes, lacks a little polish. They are bright,
cheerful, and far from patronising, giving plenty of chances for the
audience to help them round up the missing animals with the haggis call.
And for the (unfortunate) chaperones, there are plenty of sidelong
nudges and some excellent singing, as well as the knowledge that the
infant beside them is utterly absorbed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DEFENDER OF THE CITADEL</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUSSELL EDMUNDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650412</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ULSTER Unionist Party leader James Molyneaux is a far tougher and more
passionate advocate of his cause than his deceptively mild-mannered
nature would suggest.
Like all politicians in Ulster he has lived in constant fear of the
assassin's bullet -- in October 1982 he survived two attempts on his
life in one day by the Irish National Liberation Army when he was
elected to the Northern Ireland Assembly.
Molyneaux, a courageous and persistent debater, has never been afraid
to criticise even those on his own side of the ''Irish argument'' if he
feels they are falling short of the Unionist principles which he has
promoted with such conviction, commitment, and fervour.
He has been criticised by some sections of his party for his handling
of the Unionist cause both before and after the announcement of the IRA
ceasefire a year ago. In March he faced a stalking-horse challenge for
the UUP leadership.
He was returned as party leader but the challenger, university student
Lee Reynolds, shook him by snatching one-fifth of the vote -- a clear
sign of unease within the party.
The party's failure in June to win the North Down by-election, which
was caused by the death of Sir James Kilfedder, added to the question
marks around Molyneaux. Independent Unionist Robert McCartney won easily
on a platform criticising weak Unionist leadership in the post-ceasefire
period.
Ulster Unionists were said to have a ''special relationship'' with the
Government and Molyneaux the ear of the Prime Minister. But despite
saving the Government in a number of crucial votes he was unable to halt
the march of the Government's Northern Ireland policy, which Unionists
claim is far too ''green'' for their liking.
He saw his role as that of a general with an army ''that is not making
anything much in terms of territorial gains but has the satisfaction of
repulsing all attacks on the citadel''.
He was vigorously opposed to the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement, remaining
a believer in the idea of devolving power to Ulster, believing that this
could provide the basis for reconciliation and goodwill between the
nationalist and Unionist communities.
Molyneaux was ''appalled'' by the 1972 decision to abolish Stormont
and impose direct rule. A few years later he proposed the step-by-step
restoration of Stormont's powers, starting with self-administration.
In 1977 the links with Ian Paisley began to be cut, first over
Paisley's alleged connections with the paramilitaries. Molyneaux also
opposed the extreme Loyalists' strike of that year.
Soon after this he began to show his irritation with the British
Government. He refused Thatcher's invitation to a conference on Northern
Ireland local government in 1979 and boycotted a constitutional
conference the following year.
Then he attacked as a ''monstrosity'' the Thatcher-Garret FitzGerald
intergovernmental council of 1981. Molyneaux's party leadership came
under threat at this time, because of the successes of Paisley's
Democratic Unionists. But Molyneaux clung on.
As far back as 1983 Molyneaux was criticising SDLP leader John Hume
for ''grubbing around the back streets of Belfast'' to meet Sinn Fein
president Gerry Adams. He also denounced the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement
as a ''sell-out''.
As a telling and risky protest against the agreement, he and 14 other
Unionists resigned from the Commons and fought by-elections. He and all
but one other recaptured their seats. And in a further protest against
the agreement he led an illegal march through Belfast and was ''hopping
mad'' when a well-wisher paid his fine to stop him going to jail.
Under his leadership the Ulster Unionists broke their traditional
links with the Conservatives and during the Thatcher and Major regimes
Molyneaux and his colleagues sat on the Opposition benches.
He was highly sceptical of the Downing Street declaration, of
December, 1993, describing it as a ''tortuously-worded statement with
many contradictions''.
Two months later, after numerous demands by Sinn Fein for
''clarification'' of the declaration, Molyneaux claimed it was a
failure, a message he was prepared to deliver ''loud and clear'' despite
protestations to the contrary from Dublin and Whitehall.
But he was not dismissive about the IRA ceasefire of September, 1994,
although he remained cool about the possibility of all-party talks
which, he said, ''accentuate differences instead of reconciling them''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
