<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Horticulture a vital career, says Minister</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650414</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Office agriculture Minister the Earl of Lindsay recalled
yesterday how his early training as a landscape architect cut little ice
with his bank manager. Fresh from studying in America he found it
difficult to raise the finance to support his first tentative forays
into his chosen profession.
A lot had happened since then, he said, and caring for the environment
was a tremendous area for young people to be trained in, confident that
there were many circumstances in which their skills could be brought to
bear.
Lord Lindsay was speaking at the Royal Botanic Garden, Edinburgh, at
the launch of a new career leaflet for the horticulture industry
produced by ATB Landbase and the Scottish Joint Horticultural Committee.
The Minister pointed out that local authorities were now deeply
interested in the horticultural aspects of almost any planning
application. ''They want to know what trees you are going to plant and
how you are going to plant them,'' he said. The whole question of
management of the environment had become an intensely important subject.
''It has to be looked after very carefully.''
Man's re-arrangement of the environment went far beyond domestic
gardening or public parks, he added. Recent visits had taken him to
Aberfeldy and to the Black Isle where the striking landscapes were
almost entirely ''man-finished''. Farming practice and woodland
management had helped create those landscapes which people were now most
anxious to preserve.
At a different level, he said, landscaping and horticultural skills
had been used to great effect on parts of the M74 and the A9 to make it
look as if these features ''belonged'' where they were. The Meggat
reservoir, in the Borders, was another example of outstanding
landscaping effort.
Dougal Philip, chairman of the joint horticultural committee, spoke of
the need for the horticulture industry to attract young people of
quality. The temporary loss of the traditional apprecticeship had been
followed by an influx of unwilling entrants on YTS schemes, he said.
''We must try to separate horticulture as a career from gardening as a
hobby. Career horticulturists provide a service to society, supplying
plants or advice to the general public or enhancing and maintaining the
environment around us. We need the right calibre of men and women to
choose a career in horticulture.''
Besides the obvious horticulture skills, candidates who were keen to
progress in the industry had to be able to develop their management and
team building, financial awareness and marketing abilities, he said.
The horticulture industry is estimated to have an output worth #70m a
year in terms of plants produced in Scotland and sold in nurseries and
garden centres. It has more than 10,000 employees but is experiencing a
shortage of young recruits. Courses are provided at five centres
throughout Scotland a levels ranging from certificate to HND or BSc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Soprano supreme. Galina Gorchakova, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650415</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUSSIAN soprano Galina Gorchakova not only turned up yesterday, she
proceeded to tear apart her Queen's Hall audience. By the time she
reached her second encore -- when she unleashed her incredible laser
beam of a soprano voice on Puccini's Vissi d'Arte -- there were a lot of
tears trickling down faces (including this one).
Clearly, criticism of Gorchakova's performance yesterday would be a
criminal offence. The raven-haired beauty from Siberia was taken ill at
her earlier Festival appearances with the Kirov Opera, and had to
withdraw. She had bronchitis, and, until the weekend, it was touch and
go whether she would be fit for her celebrity recital yesterday.
The bronchitis is not quite out of the way -- when she stopped to
cough periodically during the concert yesterday, it was quite evident
that she still has a thick throat. But, she reportedly said to the
Festival directors: ''Nothing is going to stop me singing for this
audience.''
And nothing did, in a programme of little-known but mostly gorgeous
Romantic Russian songs, where she was accompanied by the formidable
Larissa Gergieva. Gorchakova was, it's probably fair to say, nursing her
voice a tad, singing at a bit less than full throttle in music by, among
others, Glazunov, Gretchaninov and Rubinstein -- the songs by the last
were superb -- and her intonation was not always dead centre or up to
par.
But there was enough cream in the Gorchakova voice to caress the
lyrics and the tone (especially in a wonderful set of songs by Arensky
which ranged from wistful to ardent). And when she did hit the upper
level of her range, especially those unbelievable top notes, she never
held back and the sound just pinned you to your seat. The intensity in
the near-capacity house was almost tangible. Bronchitis or whatever,
Gorchakova's is one of the truly great voices, and the lady herself is a
star.
* Sponsored by Bank of Scotland
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Folk Songs of North-east Scotland, ScottishPower Gallery, Festival Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650416</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S travelling families made a crucial contribution to the folk
song revival by passing on their wealth of songs to collectors, and on
Sunday representatives of three of those families made an absorbing and
thoroughly entertaining contribution to this concert series.
Stanley Robertson and Elizabeth Stewart, from Aberdeenshire, and
Sheila Stewart of the famous Blairgowrie Stewarts contrast as much in
character as singing styles. Compared to Robertson's harmlessly
garrulous, windmill-armed delivery (including a lengthy but brilliantly
constructed Laird O' Drum), Elizabeth Stewart was almost mouse-like, her
husky voice and lovely crisp diction all the more effective for
employing simplicity on the potentially melodramatic In London Town.
Sheila Stewart's fearless, free-flowing singing and devil-may-care
presence ensured that I Wonder What's the Matter Wi' A' The Men, for all
its Perthshire patois, crossed all language barriers before our host,
Andy Hunter, in fine voice himself, led a rollicking Beefcan Close in
tribute to the great travelling song source Jeannie Robertson, whose
prefab latterly was, he said, Aberdeen's other university.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ruckblick, St Bernard's Church</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650417</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCHUBERT and Dvorak are the Festival's big themes this year, but the
smaller ones, as so often, have been proving no less interesting. A
discreet emphasis on modern European instrumental music, for instance
has yielded nothing but good things including on Saturday a complete
concert of Kurtag.
Seventy next year, Gyorgi Kurtag has only recently begun to be
mentioned in the same breath as Bartok and Ligeti as a Hungarian
composer to reckon with. Yet wherever his music has been heard it has
held audiences enthralled, as the performance of Ruckblick clearly did
at St Bernard's Church (which, incidentally is establishing itself as a
welcoming, comfortable venue, with admirably warm acoustics).
Subtitled Homage to Stockhausen, and featuring two of Stockhausen's
offspring as performers, Ruckblick (or ''Backward Glance'') is a collage
of what Kurtag likes to call musical ''games'' assembled around his
memories of his own music and that of Stockhausen, the premiere of whose
Gruppen he attended in 1958. Much of Kurtag's music being vocal, it
reappears here in instrumental guise, its original lyricism intact, but
presented in fascinating new colours.
Yet, though consisting of some 50 short movements, Ruckblick is not at
all patchy in effect. These are in no sense sound bites, but a
mesmerising extended interweaving of piano pieces, memorials, fragments,
scherzos, and so forth into a sort of private sketch-book.
Thanks to the virtuosity of the playing, however, the effect was not
at all private but very definitely public. Markus Stockhausen proved a
dazzling trumpeter, Majella Stockhausen a gifted pianist. In company
with Peter Riegelbauer a dramatic double bassist, and Marcus Creed,
another fine pianist, they contrived to bring the prism-like timbres of
the music to vibrant life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A front-line success story</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650418</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alexander Linklater with chapter and verse on how the Book Festival
confounded the trade's prophets of doom as its popularity soared.
SPEAKING at the Book Festival a week ago two major publishers, Liz
Calder and Robert Gottlieb, agreed that in both Britain and America the
past 10 years have been disastrous for the book trade. The publishing
world, we are told, is in crisis. In Britain a breakdown of the Net Book
Agreement is threatening small presses. The spectre of VAT still looms.
It is hopeless trying to compete with the cultural mass markets of
cinema and pop music. There is a fiction slump.
But if these are the anxieties which lie behind the scenes, there is
almost no reflection of them on the front-line. The Book Festival this
year has been a phenomenal success. Compared to 1993, ticket sales have
risen by 27%, and book sales by 13%. An average of four to five thousand
people have attended daily with an estimated total of 78,000 filling up
some 400 events, of which 113 sold out.
Shona Munro, the festival's director, describes herself as ''tired but
happy''. It is her final year in charge and the legacy she leaves is
further evidence that books are, and must remain, a major feature in
Edinburgh during the Festival. To her sponsors she has proved the
commercial validity of their support, and to commentators the importance
of maintaining an essential catholicity of taste.
For it has undoubtedly been the variety of events at the Book Festival
which has given it vitality. Munro speaks of the necessity of finding
''something for everyone,'' and of bringing books to people who don't
normally read much. So there has been a range of music and comedy and
different ways of confronting writers with their audiences.
Among the normal readings and lectures certain themes have given
structure to the abundance of activity. At first the ''Six of the Best''
series -- in which authors spoke about a handful of books which have
influenced them -- seemed like it might become a forum for trite
generalisation. But this apparently glib formula turned out to be
surprisingly creative. Not only did it elicit some of the most unguarded
expressions of passion from the speakers, but it proved to be an
extremely efficient form of character analysis.
Roy Hattersley, for example, turned out to have utterly conservative
tastes. He revaled a Eurosceptic attitude to literature, having read few
non-English language authors and you could have taken his selection of
classics off a Higher exam paper. Astonishingly erudite, on the other
hand, was fantasy writer Terry Pratchett, who had clearly worked his way
through second-hand book shops at incredible speed and without any
respect for established attitudes.
Presiding in judgment over literature as a whole were the speakers at
a selection of regular lectures. Among others David Daiches, Rose
Tremain, Janice Galloway, and Marina Warner formed a cornerstone of
debate as to the kind of issues which make reading a serious business.
They balanced out the populist side of the festival which has
successfully targeted families and schools.
Children, readers of the future, more than just blended into the
literary scene at Charlotte Square. You didn't have to be a fan of
Kiddie-Lit to recognise the energy and sense of community that their
presence introduced to the general atmosphere. If there is any doubt
that they belong alongside the highbrow events of a book festival then
it is worth noting the words of Yehuda Amichai, perhaps the greatest
writer to read his work in Edinburgh this year:
When I reach the peak of my
visions,
I find myself with everyday
people
Who have children and
work, family cares,
Household chores. These are
my visions.
Amichai's reading represented the peak of the festival's aspirations.
His wise, affirmative commentaries on the political and spiritual
prerogatives for human survival were drawn out of a poetry that tunnels
deep into an experience of exile and war. Backed up by Amichai, Gitta
Sereny's gruelling revelations of Nazi darkness in her discussion of
Albert Speer, and Eric Lomax's struggle to comprehend his wartime
experience of torture at the hands of the Japanese, the festival
continued a tradition of tackling the difficult subjects.
There has also been a healthy dose of controversy. In the first week
Michael Dobbs attacked the BBC for twisting around the adaptation of his
book, Final Cut, to suit their own political ends. Then a few days later
David Sylvester let iconoclasm overcome him and skewered several sacred
cows of the art world, including Lucian Freud and Frank Auerbach.
But this was quickly matched by the inimitable Steven Berkoff who
lashed out at critics, theatrical establishments, and directors with
equal ferocity. Richard Eyre had to appear in front of an audience half
of whom had just heard Berkoff reduce him to the status of an artistic
John Major.
Poetry this year was stronger than it has ever been. Promoters Apples
and Snakes brought the first evidence of a growing performance scene.
Fast and energetic and physical, people like Lemn Sissay and Bertram
Besigye do not rely on the written word to make their impact. But those
who do came across even more clearly in the heightened atmosphere.
Brendan Kennelly, Paul Durcan, W N Herbert, Simon Armitage, James Berry,
and Sheena Blackhall demonstrated how popular serious poetry can become.
However, where the festival fell down heavily was in a lack of
widespread international participation. Four years ago the Neil Gunn
Centenary Conference brought together writers from all around the globe
to discuss vital issues of cultural cross-reference. For three days it
was possible to come into contact with the concerns which drive writers
everywhere. The debates covered nationalism, censorship, immigration,
imagination, and political unrest from Northern Ireland to Yugoslavia.
They lay at the centre of the 1991 festival and gave it shape.
This year the absence of such a forum meant that despite the variety
and energy of events there was little chance of the Book Festival
increasing its reputation abroad.
The advantages of having this kind of international hard core would
extend beyond just its immediate intellectual interest. More writers
would want to travel to Edinburgh merely to attend. The Book Festival
would become more prominent next to the film, music and theatre
festivals. And there would be much less chance of a repetition of this
year's disaster, when Germaine Greer dropped out just because Harold
Bloom couldn't come.
Shona Munro's biggest disappointment was that she couldn't come by the
kind of financial support that would make it possible to create a
regular conference of the 1991 kind. It would require enormous backing.
But what she has proved is that the Book Festival has a base of popular
support which would justify further expansion.
People often talk about the Edinburgh Book Festival as the biggest in
the world. You have to quibble over the difference between a trade fair
and a festival, and whether ''biggest'' means ''most important'' or not.
But there is little doubt that, given the extra support which would make
a serious accumulation of world writers possible, it could become the
most prestigious anywhere. It is something to be fervently hoped for.
It has undoubtedly been the variety of events at the Book Festival
which has given it vitality
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ensemble Intercontemporain, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650419</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRACK French troops from the Ministry of Culture, with their president
-- the supreme musical tactician of the 20th century -- invaded the
Edinburgh Festival last night and caused a storm. Pierre Boulez and his
outstanding virtuoso performance group, the Ensemble Intercontemporain,
flew in for a single festival date yesterday and laid down the musical
law.
Others do it, some do it well, but nobody -- nobody -- can clarify the
music of the Second Viennese School of composers -- Schoenberg, Berg,
and Webern -- like Boulez, the master of lucidity, and this superb group
of musicians. Boulez, simply, lifts the veil, aerates the music, and
lets it speak its message.
We really shouldn't be surprised: after all, some of this music is
more than 80 years old. But when you think of the sheer mince that many
performers and groups have made of it over the decades (and still do),
then what Pierre Boulez achieves is still vital, still seminal. Yes, his
is an intellectual approach; but that never stands in the way of the
dynamism of the music.
To Webern's Concerto for Nine Instruments he brought not only a
heightened expressivity, but dramatic propulsion. Comprehensively, in
the slow movement, he charted the gradual wind down towards silence. And
never, in the finale, has the snappiness and the wit of the music been
so apparent. Wit in Webern? Mais oui.
The clouds and mysteries dissolved before this outfit, intensely
atmospheric in Webern's Five Pieces, heartbreakingly melancholic in
Berg's Four Pieces for Clarinet and Piano. And they also brought with
them a powerhouse of a mezzo soprano, Nadine Denize, who gave gleaming
and operatically-scaled performances of Mahler's Lieder eines Fahrenden
Gesellen (in Schoenberg's stunning arrangement for chamber ensemble) and
The Song of the Wood Dove from Gurrelieder.
But, in an evening of blistering music-making, the French wizards
saved the best till last, in a sensational, ferociously exciting and
rivetingly articulate account of Schoenberg's Chamber Symphony No 1 that
confirmed the work as a masterpiece and the ensemble as a contemporary
group sans pareil. Brilliant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jezebel, Cafe Royal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650420</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROLIFIC playwright John Cargill Thompson wants to set the record
straight about the Biblical figure of Jezebel. I'm sure he's got a point
when he says that the woman whose name has become synonymous with
harlotry was not the degenerate that male-written history has us
believe. But, several millennia after the event, it's hard to work up
much outrage over the injustice.
The monologue is performed by an elegant Porlyn Rhoden who, despite
her crisp delivery and lively energy, does not place enough trust in
Cargill Thompson's script to make the most of the humour of the early
scenes. That coupled with the density of historical fact, make it more
an educative experience than a dramatic one.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scott Capurro, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650421</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN seeking to establish why gay men fail to learn how to date in their
teens, thus restricting the range and nature of their relationships
later in life, Perrier-nominated charmer Scott Capurro deploys his full
armoury of acid put-downs and explicit coyness. He is impishly funny.
Scott also emphasises many truths. For instance, that gay men understand
straight women better than straight men. That we all, gay or straight,
most fear being left alone -- especially with Lena Horne or a
pre-operative trans-sexual. Whether you're homo or hetero, for
revelatory laffo make a date with Scott at the earliest opportunity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>All that Glitters, Netherbow Arts Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650422</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS latest musical by Edinburgh's First Base Theatre really can't
decide what it is up to.
Ostensibly a play about a 70s revival band -- and therefore an excuse
to jam through a load of Gary Glitter, Suzi Quatro and David Bowie
numbers -- it has been lumbered with a poorly constructed and not
especially relevant tale of marital strife between a teacher (bass and
Quatro vocals) and her policeman husband (drums).
You could make allowances for this, the leaden acting and the flagging
pace, if the music was up to much, but as a band, the four performers
demonstrate little feeling for the wild hedonism for their chosen genre.
And not celebrating it, neither are they ironic nor funny about it,
leaving the whole thing in an odd no-man's land that makes you wonder
what made them do it in the first place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yarnspinners, Quaker Meeting House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIELLE NAGLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650423</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
''ONCE upon a time there was a cold, grey land. And into it crept the
faery folk to bring the song of life to its hills.'' That is just what
Kaleidoscope Theatre does. Yarnspinners, an original fairy-tale, tells
of the quest by the factory for the secret of the faery thread which
will not perish.
Exquisite movement combines with music and excellent lighting to weave
a web of magic over audiences, keeping them in their seats motionless
throughout the performance. It is only a programme note which reveals
that half the company suffers from Down's syndrome.
This production needs no sympathy vote however. It should simply be
applauded as quite entrancing theatre, and one of the Fringe's unique
experiences.
Run now ended
</TEXT>
</DOC>
