<DOCNO>GH950829-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>John Shuttleworth, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650424</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Comedy
REMARKABLY unremarkable, John Shuttleworth is south Yorkshire's master
of middle-aged mundanity. John's life is his art, and his life is his
Y-reg Austin Ambassador; occasional weekend trips to carveries in rural
Derbyshire; his wife, Mary, and his teenage son, Darren, an employee of
Victoria Wine. John also enjoys keeping an eye on reservoir-levels,
checking out holdall prices in shopping arcades, and scaring gangs of
ominous youths away from his carport at night.
One of John's perky songs asks a question: How To Be Happy In A Sad,
Sad World? The answer? Accept that age does not automatically bring
wisdom and be wary of telling every stranger about your new porcelain
bathroom-splashback. Aye, the Shuttleworthian path of enlightenment is
seriously, strangely funny.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A Lot Of People Ask Me, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650425</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A STUMPY, formidable presence on British stages for over a century,
Dame Sybille Thorndyke has lived a life of much drama. Her spitefulness,
her prodigious alcohol-intake and, above all, her stout leatherette
handbag have served her well in battles against such adversaries as
Bertolt Brecht, Sir John Gieldgud, Adolf Hitler, Judy Garland, and
Margaret Thatcher.
Her energetically-shouted memoirs detail all these incidents, plus
many lesser-known ones involving midgets, bared bottoms, and bodily
fluids. NB: It is rumoured that Dame Sybille is related to the roguish
Sean Cullen, of Canadian pranksters Corky and the Juice Pigs, but
frankly I can't believe it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>So You Think You're Funny, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650426</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNLIKE this year's Perrier judges, the panel of experts at Sunday
night's final of the annual So You Think You're Funny competition for
stand-up newcomers arrived at a verdict with which no-one could quibble.
Motor-mouthed Lancastrian absurdist Lee Mack deservedly joined a
distinguished roster of past SYTYF winners, alongside Phil Kay, Rhona
Cameron and Dylan Moran. Another Scottish contender emerged, too, in the
gangling form of runner-up Joe Heenan. My sole cavil was with third
place for dizzy blonde Geordie beautician Avril Robson; Lucy Porter was
far sharper.
Earlier rounds of the competition had been marred by widespread theft.
One contestant saw nothing wrong in impersonating recent Perrier winner
Lee Evans, using lots of his material, too, while in another heat five
out of the eight contenders appropriated bits of tried-and-trusted
material crafted by other, established comics.
Sunday night's finalists all succeeded by their own efforts. Indeed,
it won't be long before Lee Mack is up there with Sunday's host, Eddie
Izzard. Hopefully, the Gilded Balloon's current nightly Best of SYTYF
show will showcase the young Mr Mack alongside his illustrious
forebears.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mary Stuart, A Reign Revisited, Moray House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976650427</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Theatre
THE packed houses are testament to the zealous efforts of the Royal
Stuarts Scottish Performers Guild in drumming up audiences, proving that
their PR stunt of strutting around town in period dress has paid off.
The costumes, lavish recreations of sixteenth-century Scottish attire,
somewhat steal the show and are a real tourist pleaser.
Not so pleasing to the native ear is the group's insistence at
performing in their own tongue. Mary, Queen of Scots, undoubtedly had a
pretty strange accent, with French inflections, but it's somewhat
startling to hear her pant about Lord Darnley in a Californian drawl. It
seems bizarre that a group so committed to historical re-enactment
should overlook such an obvious aspect.
However the play, scripted by Chip Clark, is carefully and
convincingly rooted in authentic detail and commendably manages to offer
a fresh perspective on a well-documented life by having three women
playing Mary simultaneously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Barrymore goes down the road to destruction</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACLEOD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650428</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OF all the ebullient hosts of light entertainment -- and there are
some emetic ones about -- there is perhaps none so likeable, or so
highly regarded, as Michael Barrymore. Host of such shows as Strike it
Lucky, Barrymore's love for people, and delight in the company of the
most obscure, is manifest.
Barrymore never patronises his guests. He exudes regard and affection
for them, even as they are the butts of his comedy. He is ordinary,
jovial, unpretentious, supremely natural. In his recent battle with the
bottle, accordingly, Barrymore has had vast reserves of sympathy behind
him.
Over the past 10 days, however, Michael Barrymore has needed it. On a
Friday night in a London pub -- dramatically removing his wedding ring
-- the entertainer reportedly declared to a crowd of delighted
homosexuals that he was, himself, gay. Meanwhile a former aide of
Barrymore's, John Davis, had boasted of past sexual encounters. The
cheaper press, throughout the summer, had relayed tittle-tattle of the
comedian boozing in assorted homosexual haunts.
The weekend was scarcely done when it was confirmed that the Barrymore
marriage was over. Michael and Cheryl would be leading ''their own
personal lives''; his wife of 19 years, however, would remain his
business manager. And, just as the papers now dug delightedly through
the remains -- Barrymore's visits to a sanitorium, various
well-publicised drinking episodes, his workaholic lifestyle, his
estranged mother -- the star decided, finally and publicly, to end all
doubt.
He appeared in the small hours, on a London radio show -- a gay show;
a gay host -- and confirmed all rumours. ''I am gay,'' said Michael
Barrymore, and declared it was ''the best thing I've ever done'' to come
out. He had concealed his homosexuality for the sake of his career, said
the comedian, but -- despite various protestations of regard for his
wife -- he insisted, ''I wanted to take control of my life and think
about me for five minutes.''
So beloved is the star, and so assured is his success in TV ratings,
that this episode is unlikely to do any damage at all to Barrymore's
popular reputation. But it raises certain disturbing questions that are
worth addressing.
In the first place, what does Barrymore mean by love? He says he has
loved his wife from the day they first met; that they love each other
still; that he will love her till the end. But he has left her and,
worse, humiliated her, in the most grotesque and distressing fashion.
Cheryl Barrymore is manifestly heartbroken; so too, is Barrymore's poor
and elderly mother, who has not heard from nor seen her son for five
years.
Does Barrymore declare his undying affection for her too? Well, words
are free, and words are cheap. This is the modern disease: a reduction
of love to attitude, emotion, and so much sentiment. Real love is
ethical and real love treats people in a loving way. Real love is always
outwardly expressed, even when our hearts are far from it.
Further, Barrymore's spectacular declaration forces our attention, yet
again, to homosexuality. The gay lobby can scarcely believe their luck.
A new star has joined their ranks and not a stereotypical flounce, like
Larry Grayson; not a barbed lounge-lizard, like Noel Coward; not such a
glorious pansy as Julian Clary; not even such a manifest lump of evil as
the late Derek Jarman, but a popular, straight-acting, wholesome family
entertainer. And the gay lobby will make the most of it.
The natural spin of course, is that Barrymore has ''discovered
himself,'' decided to stop living a lie and so on, ad nauseum. How valid
is this? Wrong, and wrong on every central point, for it is a view
founded in fallacy.
First: homosexuality is a lifestyle, not a condition into which we are
born as we are born black or white or Jewish. The concept of an
exclusively homosexual ''orientation'' is, in fact, most modern, and
examples in pre-twentieth century history are hard to find. The reality
is that Barrymore is not a homosexual, but is a man at present troubled
with homosexual feelings, and now driven to resolve them by assuming
homosexual identity.
Second: the homosexual life is unnatural, dangerous, and evil. It is a
lifestyle remarkable in its practice -- as has been borne out by study
upon study -- for promiscuity, instability, neurosis, substance-abuse,
and suicide, untold depths of degradation and misery and self-loathing.
It is a way in which men, physically and psychologically, are simply not
equipped to live. It may seem a very easy way at present to Michael
Barrymore -- easier, perhaps than addressing the ills of his marriage,
or the wider roots of his alcoholism, or his need for fame and adulation
-- but it will end, in the next world if not in this, in his utter
destruction.
Third: why in our age, do we so prize honesty over truth? In our art,
in our culture, in our cinema -- courtesy of Kelman, Bacon, Lynch, and
all their kind, we esteem meticulous realism, even if it be obscene,
horrific, demonic, depraved, profoundly and permanently pessimistic.
Michael Barrymore, and I, and you, all have a disease. That disease is
called sin. It is an innate warping of our nature, a blinding of our
faculties, a built-in bias that pulls us all to the egotistical, the
violent, the proud, and the wrong.
Families, society, civilisation itself are human institutions evolved
to address this problem, to engender emotional restraint and self
discipline, enforced by sore sanctions. But in our personal lives we
need all to be aware of our capacity for wickedness and for
self-destruction. Are Barrymore's eyes really open to what he has done?
And is he really aware of the consequences of the step he has taken?
Honesty has its place. We all have problems, conflicts, terrible
fears, and temptations; we all have sexual drives. We are not to ignore
these, to pretend they do not exist. But we have to control them and, if
necessary, deny them.
Those who struggle with forbidden desires, those forced to address,
indeed, homosexual urges, and who are persuaded that expression of these
is absolutely and in all circumstances wrong -- folk have little place
for them today. I know of such. The sophisticated world would laugh at
them. Few friends they have to trust. The very church itself, decadent
and un-Christianlike as it has become, would recoil from them. But
theirs, in the end, is lasting fame and glory. Theirs is the Kingdom of
Heaven.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650429</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN what might be his gravest miscalculation yet Gary Hart, man of
gaffes and self-destructing Democrat, is contemplating one more bid for
the American Senate. He is the former politician whose two attempts to
win the Presidency were felled by that oldest of man's follies,
woman-trouble. But today Hart judges that the electorate is not only
more broad-minded than 12 and eight years ago, it is also suffering from
scandal-fatigue.
Where, one wonders, has he been hiding? Even exiled to the dull vistas
of an industrial lawyer's office, he must be aware of America's
accelerating lurch to the right. The country may be scandal-tired but
that is not at all the same as being scandal-tolerant, and already the
Republicans are rattling and rolling out the skeletons in his closet.
In 1984 Hart had turned a dazzling smile towards that desk in the Oval
Office only to have it severely blemished by his wife's disclosure that
their marriage had twice reached breaking point, and anyway she detested
politics and the prospect of incumbency in the White House. Four years
later, again out in front as the Democratic candidate in the
presidential race, Hart curiously instigated his own downfall by
taunting the press into a cat-and-mouse chase which ended with their
discovery of him in the arms of a ditzy blondette called Donna Rice.
Other than the angst and lust of middle life (Rice was almost 20 years
Hart's junior), what compelled him to behave so disastrously? Contempt
for prying journalism and the moral rectitude demanded of public figures
was part of it. But was Hart also inveterately unreliable? After all,
this was a man who had earlier been devious about his age, and shifty,
too, about the fact that he was born not Hart but Hartpence.
Still, reinvention has always been the stuff of American ambition and
today here he is, aged 58, telling the Denver Post that he wants to win
back his old Colorado seat (now occupied by a Republican), by waging a
campaign about issues, not sleaze. Such high-mindedness may count for
nothing, however, because during his years in obscurity Colorado has
changed greatly from the days when Hart knew it as a liberal state. Last
March one of its senators, Ben Nighthorse Campbell, turned his back on
the Democrats to become a Republican, realising that Colorado is now so
conservative in outlook and demands any Democrat was going to have a
tough time winning in next year's election race.
It seems certain, then, that many voters would be reluctant to root
for a candidate once accused of adultery. Even now Colorado's Republican
Party chairman is reminding people of that photograph of Donna Rice
perched erotically on Gary Hart's lap. ''It will be on every billboard
in this state,'' the chairman threatens. ''We will see to that.''
So, well in advance of the 1996 presidential campaign, dirty tricks
are on the boil, raising the temperature of scrutiny on all candidates,
not least of whom is the President himself. Last time round Bill Clinton
may have defied those who were out to ruin him for his past marital
infidelity. Against the odds he managed to regain the women's vote
because of his commitment to abortion, equality, and social harmony.
But his hampered progress and personal indecision on domestic matters
have left many with feelings of betrayal. As a result those politicians
who exploit others' sins of the flesh, no matter how ancient, may
effectively control the electorate's mood.
''A politician,'' mused the wife of a former American President,
''should be born a foundling and remain a bachelor.'' Beneath her
patient and adoring gaze Lady Bird Johnson managed to disguise any
scorching resentment about LBJ's recurring peccadilloes. But an
unmarried President would be unthinkable in the States. More than ever,
America is fragmenting into a society where family stability seems
irreparably damaged by serial divorce and, at national level, this is
contributing to a profound sense of failure.
In this situation the country's First Citizen must have a First
Partner, a surrogate royal to initiate good deeds and show the world,
via visiting heads of state, that for all its loud-mouthed aggression
and disintegrating standards America still aspires to wholesome values
and sophisticated chitchat over presidential dinners.
But extreme demands for virtue in high places may cause politicians to
end up with no private life at all. Meanwhile should Gary Hart indeed
run for the Senate we can be sure that dubious investigators will spend
next year dragging out those old, incriminating snapshots which allow
the rest of us a moralistic flourish as we leer down Donna Rice's
cleavage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Speak up in the interests of Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish business community was a prime source of recruits to the
No camp last time Scotland got into an inconclusive lather over home
rule. Now a significant segment of that same business community appears
to have a devolution crisis all of its own making.
Lex Gold is quitting his post as director of CBI Scotland after just
18 months, the third director to depart in quick succession since the
organisation was robbed, through his premature death, of John Davidson's
high-profile presence and tireless appetite for lobbying.
Sure-footed and articulate, Gold, together with outgoing CBI Scotland
chairman John Ward, has done much to rehabilitate the employers'
organisation's waning influence north of the Border, after a lacklustre
interregnum. But his swift departure, coinciding as it does with the end
of Ward's fixed term, threatens to plunge the organisation back into a
period on the far margins of influence.
Part of the problem is that the CBI is a UK organisation, run from the
infamous Centrepoint tower block on London's Tottenham Court Road, with
centralist assumptions to match those which would not be misplaced in
the most myopically metropolitan mandarin. Although its departing
director-general Howard Davies was much too shrewd and quick-witted to
give the game away in public -- some of us still relish his storming
toast to Caledonia which quite put Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown's
Immortal Memory in the shade at this year's Strathclyde region Burns
Supper -- Davies has not managed to resolve the implications of the fact
that, in the Confederation (sic!) of British Industry, too, Scotland is
different.
Gold was, in effect, expected by the wider Scottish community to play
the Howard Davies role within Scotland. That he did, with the same
tireless enthusiasm of a John Davidson. But, in the eyes of the
Centrepoint bureaucracy, Gold was on little more than #30,000.
He could probably afford to do the job as a loss leader, thanks to a
healthy severance package after a long career in the Civil Service and,
latterly, with Scottish Enterprise. But, as CBI Scotland starts the
search for a successor, you know what they say about peanuts and
monkeys.
There is, however, a deeper point to all of this than grubby salary
differentials. If business organisations cannot resolve the issue of
Scotland's distinctiveness in the way they manage their own affairs, it
is not surprising that they bolt below the parapet every time anyone
tries to engage them in dialogue over the wider constitutional debate.
That failure of the Scottish business community to participate in a
sustained way in debating the home rule issue is symptomatic of a wider
malaise.
At its extremes, there is a latent and debilitating schizophrenia.
Scottish business leaders eagerly promote their Scottishness as a
marketing edge on the one hand -- and stand on the Murrayfield terraces
at each home international belting out Flower o' Scotland with the best
of them -- but, depressingly, some go on to threaten wholesale
relocation of their operations south of the Border, if as much as a
toothless equivalent of a toon cooncil is proposed to sit on Calton
Hill.
Some otherwise highly intelligent men -- Scottish business is probably
even more male dominated at the very top than its English equivalent --
betray a stunning ignorance of even the bare fundamentals of the
constitutional debate. Indeed, as a rule of thumb, there seems more
informed awareness the further down the tree you go, into the small
business community.
Last week there was just a hint that the malaise may be crumbling at
the edges. Scotland's Chambers of Commerce issued a challenge to the
political parties to improve the level of representation business
currently enjoys with Government north of the Border. There was a
particular challenge to Labour, coinciding with plans for a new survey
of members' attitudes to devolution, to give business its rightful place
in the process.
Of course the Chambers of Commerce are jockeying for influence in a
crowded market-place, where more and more representative bodies, from
the Institute of Directors to the Forum of Private Business, seek to
grow their membership lists representing this or that section of the
Scottish business community.
Inevitably organisational self advancement is every bit as much at
play here as any desire to get a surer hand on the levers of power. But
the Scottish Chambers' willingness to embark on meaningful political
debate is at least a start.
If Scottish business wants to be treated seriously in this process it
cannot come to the table with any preconceived partisan prejudices. If
it wants representation as the money making voice of the Tory Party the
adventure will assuredly fail.
It is time that Scottish business made its constructive voice more
clearly heard on devolution and a host of other issues. For too long,
there has been an assumption that these concerns can be dealt with
through the informal networking process -- in black tie, across endless
dinner tables -- which so dominates the winter evenings of so many in
the business community.
I have long thought that a country's economic success is probably in
inverse proportion to the number of formal dinners its business elite
attends. The same is possibly true of its ability to influence the
political process.
If business wants a clearer representative voice in the way this
country is heading we need, from it, a more mature consideration of the
issues and an open-minded willingness to become involved, without prior
prejudice, in shaping outcomes. The CBI could help by recognising that,
within its own structure, Scotland is not just another regional office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What a difference a day makes in path to glory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650431</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE battle for self-determination is hotting up. First, the Diary is
in receipt of the programme for the SNP's sixty-first annual national
conference -- at Perth, just for a change -- complete with traditional
tri-lingual greeting from national convener Eck Salmond (''Ower the lest
echtein munth, the SNP haes focht five sindrie election campaigns . .
.'') and a full menu of radical proposals designed to bring independence
that little bit nearer.
Even among Nationalists, however, the paths of glory are not ever
smooth. Campbeltown branch lobs in the motion, ''Recognising that many
party members cannot attend an annual conference from Wednesday to
Saturday and to ensure that future conferences are more representative
of the total membership, it is agreed that future annual conferences be
held on a Friday, Saturday, and Sunday.''
Up pops Lochaber branch, plainly staunch Sabbatarians to a patriot:
''Amendment a) Delete 'Friday, Saturday and Sunday' and insert
'Thursday, Friday and Saturday'.
What a difference a day makes. Or as the old Billy Connolly song had
it, ''And will ye start the revolution on a Saturday, for ah huv to work
through the week . . .''
Bowled over
ITEM two, designed to launch the fight-back against neo-colonialist
curs everywhere and perhaps even launch a fringe event of its very own,
arrives as a small gift from our old friends at the Scottish Republican
Socialist Party. A T-shirt, no less, complete with eloquent motto and
wee saltire. ''I Failed the English Cricket Test'', it asserts. This is
very true, and ideal for bewildering tourists from around the world.
Given that the Diary has also passed the Pepsi Challenge, the Guinness
Test, the Mutton Pie Quiz, and the Polyunsaturated Fats Poser, we are
pleased to report the thing appears to fit. What we have failed thus far
to find is the little label on the shirt that says ''Made in Scotland''.
Must be there somewhere.
Twice the fun
WHAT larks. An item in the Scotsman, a newspaper, has lots of fun with
the fact that its very own film writer Brian Pendreigh, in covering a
Steve Martin press conference, predicted someone, somewhere, would
deploy the line ''Hollywood came to Edinburgh yesterday''.
Sure enough, we did, to the evident amusement of an Edinburgh nom de
plume named ''Boswell''. ''Step backward,'' he says, ''the Herald, still
proving that 'quality' is easier said than done.''
It is not, of course, for us to point out that the Scotsman enjoyed
its fabulously funny tale so much it printed two versions of it on the
very same day, once in the broadsheet section of the paper and again in
its unmissable Festival supplement.
Never mind the quality, boys and girls, feel the width -- or is that
''gulf''?
Big ideas
SPEAKING of width, we were terrifically pleased to note from a recent
advertisement that Cellulitex Ltd of Edinburgh are doing well. It seems
the company, dealing in the latest techniques for removing ugly
cellulite ''instantly, painlessly, and non-invasively'', have
opportunities in all areas for ''consultants''.
Is there any real point in adding that the demon flab-fighters are a
''rapidly expanding'' company?
Barking mad
THE Isle of Lewis, CalMac's splendid new ferry, is recommended to us
as the only way to travel -- if you're a dog. Harassed parents report
that there is more space for canines on board the all-new (save for the
menus) boat than there is for bairns. Accommodation for dugs is
described as spacious, nay luxurious, but that for the little darlings
somewhat less so. This either tells us something very important about
Lewis, about CalMac, or about the sort of weans who cross the watter
under maximum security.
Meanwhile, we hear that the boat itself, though very pretty to look
at, has encountered a little difficulty keeping to its schedule. This,
it is alleged, has more than a little to do with berthing arrangements,
described by one survivor as ''trying to fit a very big backside into a
very wee chair''.
Look back in anger
JANET Street-Porter's MacTaggart lecture at the Edinburgh
International Television Festival was as combative as one might have
expected, with the doyenne of ''yoof'' television lambasting this, that,
and the next thing beginning with ''M'' (middle-class, middle-brow,
middle-aged, male, and so forth) that came to mind. We are grateful,
then, to the trade paper Broadcast for recalling one of Street-Porter's
previous festival interventions. ''People who work in television,'' she
said, ''are all too old''.
That was in 1982, of course, when we were all a lot younger, Dame
Janet, still busy as ever, certainly not least. Who said middle-aged?
The last blast
WITH anniversaries of utterly insignificant sixties events all around
us -- a comment, we cannot help but feel, on just how fascinating and
creative the nineties have been -- we are glad to report that Dr Timothy
Leary continues to prove that all those funny drugs never did anyone any
harm ever.
The man who instructed us all to ''turn on, tune in, and drop out''
has just announced he is ''thrilled'' to be dying. Like, wow.
Afflicted with an entirely unfunny prostate cancer, the one-time
counter-culture guru and full-time career fruit-cake asserts that he has
''entered into the real challenge of how to live an empowered life . .
.'' by, er, dying.
This, we can't help but feel, may be to miss the point more than
somewhat, but it was ever thus with the Doc. For your information, he
adds that there is a ''real possibility'' he will take LSD again before
he dies but hasn't yet done so.
One logical explanation for his ravings is therefore ruled out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
