<DOCNO>GH950829-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quangos pursued</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650432</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Labour Party pursue quangos with all the zeal of the toffs
pursuing the luckless grouse and if the quangos that survive happen to
be the ones with Labour majorities that is proof of the rightness of
things.
They have their sights trained, once again, on the House of Lords --
the quango of all quangos. Only the fact that they would blow away
Labour peers and close forever the magic trail of honours lists,
knighthoods, and preferential treatment makes them hold their fire.
After all, where would ageing Socialists go?
All this smokescreen enables them to obscure the fact that they daily
live to defend the most undemocratic decision taken by the most
perfidious quango of them all, the signatories of the Treaty of Union.
The people had no say in the matter; indeed women had no say in
anything until over 200 years later.
The Campaign for a Scottish Assembly, at the moment deciding the shape
of the puppet parliament for Scotland, is itself a quango, unelected,
but speaking in the name of the people. Conceived in the minds of a
lordly quango 258 years ago, Scotland's entrapment is about to be
ratified by a non-elected quango of the proletariat.
Nina MacAulay,
9 Cnoc Glas,
Drumbeg,
Sutherland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>To increase gospel's impact</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Macleod writes a disturbing melange of well-argued historical
analysis and xenophobic prejudice (August 26). If the Reformation's most
striking effect was to release people from their chains, then John
Macleod has done a good job of shackling himself anew.
The Renaissance and the Reformation indeed challenged the religious
view that life weas a mystery best left unquestioned, and the results
were a freeing of philosophy, politics, science, and medicine. But to
ponder over the collapse of the ''sons of light'' (Presbyterians) in the
face of the ''sons of darkness'' (Roman Catholicism, Europe, the
National Lottery) is to undervalue the wisdom of God.
The point about the reformed Church is that it should be always
reforming, always setting the world free. So let's spend less time being
mesmerised by the horror stories of the past, and recognise instead our
own failures in the present. Jesus Christ is the same yesterday, today,
and for ever -- but nothing else is.
Ecumenism, I suspect, is close to synonymous in John Macleod's mind
with the ''new paganism''. But a true endeavour for understanding among
the Churches, recognising clearly what still divides us, and repenting
sincerely for all the dark periods in our histories, can only increase
the impact of the gospel on our largely unchurched society.
In those terms, why should not Reformed Scots be happy to applaud the
joy of Roman Catholic brothers and sisters over Thomas Winning's red
hat?
Rev John R Smith,
82 Lanfine Road,
Paisley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650434</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANY of John Macleod's observations are accurate and informing (August
24). Traditional Presbyterianism has lost its hold on Scottish society
and we are indeed heading backwards as well as forwards into Europe-wide
corruption. greed, and superstition.
But he provides no answers, preferring to bemoan long irrelevant
schisms and failings in our supposed national church. What are we all
meant to do? Go to Presbyterian churches which have lost their function
as places of genuine worship?
Most of them are utterly dead: we know that. The historical failure of
Presbyterianism for generations stems from a lack of relevance as well
as from a lack of love and power, qualities of God which cannot be
recaptured easily by any church.
We have seen very recently from the cultic antics of the Church of
England in Sheffield, no doubt copied elsewhere, that it's not enough to
try desperately to be relevant.
The answer lies in Christian churches and individuals, Protestant,
Catholic, Non-conformist, who welcome the Holy Spirit and with Him. His
power and love which can meet the needs of everyone in our despairing
country.
Are we not all floating about unanchored, looking for Something? True
Christianity and its Triune God is hard to find but found by those
churches and individuals who take the time and trouble required.
Dr Archie Roy,
8 Crown Road North,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650435</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Macleod displays a depressingly high level of historical
illiteracy in his claim that ''it was largely the Reformation that made
Scotland a nation state''. Whether he likes to admit it or not, it is
undoubted fact that the medieval Scottish Catholic Church was a key
element in the ultimately successful struggle for Scottish independence
in the late thirteenth and early fourteenth centuries under Wallace and
Bruce.
Ian O Bayne,
8 Clarence Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
