<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish business is consulted</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650437</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was with both interest and a sense of disbelief that I read your
report covering the Scottish Chambers of Commerce assertion that
business in Scotland was not adequately represented in either local or
national government (August 21), and that as the ''premier
representatives of the business community'' they should be co-opted on
to local authority sub-committees and LEC boards.
I would challenge the notion that Scottish business is not presently
consulted. The Federation of Small Businesses has, for instance,
recently met with the new Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, at his
request, I might add. This follows a good working relationship with Ian
Lang.
We have also met in recent months George Kynoch, Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton, George Robertson, Helen Liddell, Jim Wallace, Henry
McLeish, and Alex Salmond.
These people cover a cross-section of political opinion in Scotland
and we value all opinions no matter the political flavour as I am
assured they value ours. We also work closely with the Scottish Tourist
Board, STUC, Cosla, Scottish Enterprise, and local authorities. In most
cases we are invited into the consultation exercise. All of this gives
the lie to the Chambers' claim that business is not represented.
The Chambers once again raise the hoary old chestnut of compulsory
business registration, with the Chambers being the organisation to run
it. Compulsory business registration, or Statutory Chambers as it is
often known, is a barrier to free enterprise and must never be allowed
to come into force.
In reality it actually means that if you wish to run a business you
would have to register with a local registry which, if it was the
Chamber, would be in a position to pick and choose what business could
be registered, a very clear case of vested interest.
If the Scottish Chambers are so keen to influence political opinion
perhaps they would do well to support some of the current issues. Rail
privatisation, for example, as even the local Lochaber Chamber could not
elicit help from the Scottish Chamber. They might also tackle
differences in business rates valuations between Scotland and England.
Stewart Farmer,
Strathclyde Regional Chairman, Federation of Small Businesses,
17 Chisholm Avenue,
Bishopton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Caught out on colonialism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650438</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is ironic that Sandy Lindsay should choose to use as evidence of
Scotland's colonial status the game of cricket, which is one area where
Scotland can now claim to be genuinely independent (August 24).
Cricket is played in Scotland (and elsewhere) by thousands of
Scotsmen, and there are countless other Scots who take an interest as
spectators, readers, listeners, or viewers.
Mr Lindsay would be a brave and arguably a foolish man if he were to
attempt to impose his prejudices on the inhabitants of, for example,
Freuchie.
Chris Carruthers,
Chairman,
Scottish Cricket Union,
Caledonia House,
South Gyle, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>After Molyneaux</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650439</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sudden resignation of Mr James Molyneaux from the leadership of
the Ulster Unionist Party was fully in the character of that stubborn
and secretive man. The party must now find a replacement who will
reconcile its persistent internal differences, or at least reduce them
to manageable proportions in the difficult times ahead. It is clear that
the UUP will have difficulty finding another man like James Molyneaux:
what is not clear is whether it wants another man like him. That is not
to disparage the retiring leader. He has done many remarkable things in
his long years in office, not least the support he gave to the
eventually doomed Government of Mr James Callaghan.
Nevertheless, Mr Molyneaux's style has irritated some of his
supporters. His conditional support for Mr Major's efforts on Northern
Ireland, and indeed Mr Major's Government, was tactical and designed to
maintain influence on Government thinking, but his critics point to what
is seen as the British Government's excessively ''green'' tinge on these
matters. The loss of the North Down by-election did not help.  If the
UUP believe that Mr Molyneaux's policies have failed they would be
foolish to elect to the leadership a man who would give them more of the
same. Yet of the probable candidates for the post the one believed to be
annointed by Mr Molyneaux is the colourless William Ross, who is on the
most sceptical wing of the party on the subject of the Downing Street
Declaration. Mr Ross neatly illustrates another dilemma for the UUP,
which is that the most popular leaders with the general public are not
best regarded within the party.
A recent poll showed Ken Maginnis to be by far the most popular UUP
MP. He was followed by David Trimble who, absurdly but actually by
deepest calculation, believes that he is too young at 50 to stand, and
then by the Rev Martin Smyth whose position as Grand Master of the
Orange Lodge may, or may not, be an advantage. The UUP is split
basically between those who wish to progress cautiously with the current
exploration of peace and those who insist that it is fruitless. Of the
former Mr Maginnis and Mr Taylor are the most acceptable but there are
other nuances here. Mr Molyneaux hints mischievously that the Tory
Government may not last its term; Mr Major's worries may be about to
multiply.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650440</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is one thing for your TV reviewer, Ian Bell (August 19) and Sandy
Lindsay (Letters, August 23) to tell us of their dislike of cricket, a
view evidently not shared by their many compatriots who play or follow
the game, but quite another for them to express their racism.
Astonishingly, Mr Lindsay claims that Ian Bell's ignorant xenophobia
showed ''deep insight into the mentality of the English''. What on earth
is that mentality? Who indeed are the ''English''? Substitute for
''English'' any of ''Scots'', ''Jews'', ''blacks'', ''Irish'',
''Serbians'', or countless other adjecives and you see something of the
danger of this sort of crude stereotyping.
I must admit that I like cricket. But I loathe racism, wherever it
comes from and however much it dresses itself up with cant about ''our
colonial status'', even more.
Andrew Anderson,
179 Granton Road,
Edinburgh
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650441</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is not the tedium of cricket which annoys me but the
ever-repetitive tedious criticism of the game. Cricket is a game of two
codes, the traditional three (now four) day and Test Match (five day)
contest. That arena is for the purists -- not to be confused with the
bustling limited-over contest. Certainly no tedium or boredom arises in
these contests -- only a definite result.
Cricket as played in Scotland generally relates to limited overs.
While admittedly not a show-stopper, it is probably the most
participant-involved summer team game played.
It can also boast a broad spread of multi-racial players, surely an
opportunity not to be discounted in promoting goodwill and harmony among
all our citizens.
Long may the ebb and flow of summer's pleasant game continue. As with
our Scottish summer, the season is all too short.
Councillor Allan C Steele,
Chair, Community and Leisure,
East Renfrewshire Authority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650442</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LARGE number of Scots, including those like myself who support the
SNP, greatly enjoy watching cricket (August 23).
As the English cricket commentators and supporters are generally much
more impartial and intelligent than their yobbish footballing
counterparts, many of us actually wish the England cricket team well.
Ben Wood,
2 John Street
Portobello, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Civil justice debate</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650443</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUST, fair, speedy, understandable, certain, and responsive to the
needs of the people who use it. These are the qualities of an ideal
civil justice system identified by Lord Woolf in his green paper Access
to Justice. He has highlighted a number of faults in the English system,
but you do not have to search very hard to find the same flaws here.
According to Lord Woolf, civil justice is too slow, too complicated, too
expensive, and the outcome of cases too uncertain. Cases are run by the
competing sides and court rules are either ignored or not enforced.
Assuming that you can afford to venture inside the door of the court at
all, litigation is all too often a contest between unequal foes -- rich
and powerful vested interests ranged against someone struggling to meet
the cost of a legal aid contribution.
The diagnosis of Lord Woolf, and the remedies he proposes for the
sickly patient, would have found great favour with Lord Morton of Shuna.
Before his untimely death, and along with Lord Gill, Lord Morton did
much to focus attention on the flaws of the Scottish system and what
could be done to give it a sharp kick into the next century. Some
improvements have already been made. Lord Penrose is dispatching
complicated cases at an impressive rate in the commercial court; lessons
for ordinary cases can certainly be learned from that. There is also
little doubt that Lord Cullen, who is conducting a Woolf-type exercise
in the Court of Session, albeit on a smaller scale and tighter
timetable, will benefit from the exercise south of the Border. He will
have to address himself to many of the issues tackled by Lord Woolf, the
crucial one being whether we should give the court much greater control
over the way cases are conducted. This would mean a radical change from
the present arrangement where judges are passive spectators largely
unable to influence events and circumvent delay. His guiding principle
should be that the court system must be run for the benefit and
convenience of the public who use it rather than for lawyers. Scotland
needs a speedy, economical, reliable, and just system of civil justice
and the current debate as to how we achieve it is welcome, if overdue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650444</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR report about the Government plan to send young offenders to the
Military Corrective Training Centre at Colchester was shallow (August
25). Had your reporter spent 10 minutes doing some research he would
have found there is much to commend in the work of the MCTC.
Soldiers who return to their units from Colchester do so fitter,
smarter, better trained, and often with the problems which caused them
to offend in the first place successfully dealt with. Above all, the
system helps them to regain their self-respect.
Many of those sent to Colchester are discharged into civilian life.
The training they receive is appropriate to a future as a civilian. Such
treatment is entirely relevant to the problems of dealing with young
offenders.
By dismissing the idea in such a trivial way and calling in aid Labour
politicians, the Prison Officers' Association, the Council for Civil
Liberties, and the rest of the politically correct for their instant
reaction, your reporter does nothing for your claim to be a serious and
reputable paper.
Finally the report contains the usual ration of cliches. The term
''glasshouse'' would not be recognised by many of today's young
soldiers. It refers to military prisons, the last of which was closed
more than 30 years ago.
Equally the use of the term ''boot camp'' is just as irrelevant. Boot
Camp is an American term, synonymous with bullying, brutality, and the
sadistic treatment of young people, none of which should or does form
part of the Government's plans for the treatment of young offenders.
If you are to be a newspaper dedicated to criticism of the Government,
at least you should do it on the basis of facts.
Michael Ashmore,
Cocklaw, Elsrickle,
Biggar.
</TEXT>
