<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New education framework</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650445</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Over the next few days the heads of our secondary schools will receive
three copies of a weighty, 4in-thick volume which sets out the draft
frameworks for the courses their fifth and sixth-year pupils will follow
from 1998 onwards. That will wipe the smile from their faces, should
they drift into a fleeting daydream of recent happy times in the Algarve
or Florida. It would be wrong, however, to over-react to this latest
publication, daunting though it may appear at first sight. This is not a
time for jerking the knee or bellyaching about more bumph from the
Scottish Office. This tome represents a commendable attempt to solve the
many problems in the upper secondary school arising from the fact that
the present Highers are unsuitable for many of the increasing numbers of
youngsters staying on beyond 16. It sets out the framework for the way
short units of learning and courses -- both academic and vocational --
should be organised as we head to the millennium. It is intended for
heads and the principal teachers of departments. It is a consultation
document, a critically important point which is underscored by the fact
that seminars will shortly be organised throughout the country to
encourage feedback from department heads and their counterparts in
further education colleges.
The Scottish Office has already shown that it will listen, first in
its response to the criticisms of the original Howie report, most
recently in agreeing to a one-year delay in the implementation of Higher
Still to take account of the work involved in writing new courses. Now,
even the names for the awards themselves and the levels at which they
will be made are up for grabs, in consultative terms.
The documentation released yesterday proposes the release of more time
for the teaching of courses, shorter final examinations, and greater
emphasis on pupil assessments made by teachers. Higher Still is about
giving all pupils the opportunity to achieve as much as they can across
a broad range of subjects. It does not have all the answers, especially
in relation to sixth year, but it is a genuine attempt at offering fair,
attainable, and meaningful targets for the increasingly disparate group
of fifth and sixth-year pupils. The profession should respond,
positively and responsibly.
</TEXT>
