<HEADLINE>Set up for a new age</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TONY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650447</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TONY ARMSTRONG meets a man who enjoys life in the slow lane
THE young man has dark curly hair, earrings, and a weather-beaten
face. As his horse crops the grass of a lay-by he carries out some minor
maintenance on the immaculate canvas-covered caravan while the kettle
bubbles, suspended from a tripod over the open wood fire.
Glen Wilson may look every inch a Romany but he is, in fact, the son
of Joe Wilson, Labour Euro-MP for North Wales. While his father tramps
the corridors of power in Brussels, 31-year-old Glen has chosen another
route, currently plodding along the lanes of Scotland looking at the
world between the ears of his horse Kes.
It is a world moulded to the pace and needs of a quietly creative
individual who left school as a dyslexic 16-year-old, worked in a
garage, ran his own furniture-stripping business and finally decided to
head off in the gypsy caravan he had built when his marriage ended two
years ago.
For the past 18 months he has been based near the Berwickshire village
of Gordon, living winter and summer in the caravan and working in a tree
nursery where his ordered mind and rapid mastery of Latin variety names
quickly impressed his boss. He was heading south towards Shropshire to
see his son who is eight, and then probably into Wales.
His progress started with a gentle four or five miles a day while Kes,
sleek and a little tubby on pasture grass, got used to daily life
between the shafts and builtup his muscle power. When he was ''run in''
there were good days of up to 20 miles. But the key factor in deciding
when to call a halt to the day's trek is finding good grazing and water.
Mostly Glen is camping on some grassy verge but sometimes he is
invited into a field. ''There are times when you are treated like
royalty by farmers or landowners who are really interested and
welcoming. Other times people don't want to know. Mostly it is assumed
that I am a true Romany and I don't say otherwise.''
The seeds of Glen's present lifestyle were planted when he made
friends with gypsies as a child during conventional family caravan
holidays at Portmadoc in Caernarvonshire. ''They've left the place where
they used to camp,'' says Glen. ''Most of them are in council houses now
but I learnt a lot from them and I still go to visit.''
Glen acquired his first gypsy caravan in his twenties after graduating
from a traditional two-wheel horsedrawn cart and tent, and then set to
work on his present vehicle, completely rebuilding it around the
salvaged metalwork and wheels of an old one. The result is an authentic
gypsy caravan, immaculately painted in maroon and cream and topped with
a hooped green canvas cover.
Glen's home has a floor space 9ft by 5ft with cupboards, iron
wood-burning stove, seats and a single bed that pulls out to make a
double. Lighting is by paraffin lamp and candles and ''kitchen''
equipment includes a shining metal kettle, bucket, two bowls and two
pans and a few plates and cups.
There is, of course, no double glazing or insulation to combat the
Borders winter. But Glen says: ''It is roasting hot even in January.
People regularly ask me over to their houses thinking I am having a hard
time, but I often find their homes cold.''
Glen cooks inside in winter and on a fire outside in the summer. In
this simple and compact environment traditional gypsy couples raise
large families. ''People don't realise how little time was actually
spent in the caravan,'' says Glen. ''The kids slept in a tent or
underneath the caravan. Most of the time the outside world was their
living room.''
On the road Glen is surrounded by an animal menagerie. In addition to
Kes -- who was trained by an old gypsy friend in Telford -- a cage
beside the driver's seat contains a yellow canary. At the back in
another cage are two white ferrets called Little Sally and Sexy Susie.
In a coop beneath the caravan is a cockerel called Lionel and two hens
which will produce eggs along the way. The collection is rounded off by
a Lurcher bitch called Daisy.
Of the months that stretch ahead Glen says: ''It takes a few days to
get settled into a pattern and after that your priorities become finding
good water and grazing for the horse, and firewood for cooking. I take
some tinned food with me and Daisy does some hunting for both of us. For
money, I'm using a bit that I saved up during the winter and top it up
by doing casual work along the way. I don't rely on the DSS.''
The image may be one of plodding peacefully along but Glen says the
driving can be stressful. ''Main roads are actually OK because there is
plenty of room and visibility and Kes is 100% safe in traffic, but small
country lanes can be a nightmare. You have to think three steps ahead
because you can't see round the corners. Oncoming cars or others coming
up fast behind don't expect to meet something moving so slowly and I've
had a few near misses. It may seem idyllic but a horse isn't like a car.
It has its own reactions and you can't reach out and switch off the
ignition.''
Glen's resourcefulness and manual dexterity probably have their roots
in the dyslexia that saw him leave school with a reading age of seven.
His mother June explains: ''Although he reads pretty well now, he
realised early that he would have to get by without some areas of
conventional learning.
''His school was very good and helped him develop in his own way. If
he had been forced to conform it could have destroyed him. As it is he
has developed as his own person and is at peace with himself and very
skilled and determined. His father and I are happy that he is content
with his life.''
</TEXT>
