<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP agenda aims to draw up battle lines for election</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE,SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650448</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish National Party will today outline the agenda for next
month's national conference which it hopes will prepare the party for
the challenge of the next General Election.
The policy vice-convener, Mr Alex Neil, said the debates would firm up
policies on the SNP's distinctive economic and social aims, adding that
he was confident the challenge to his own post by Perth and Kinross MP
Roseanna Cunningham would not cloud the issues.
''We plan to give the lie to the Unionist argument that Scotland isn't
paying its way, to show how our industrial policy will bring new jobs,
and to outline how our dynamic budget and repatriation of oil revenues
will reduce unemployement,'' he said.
Among the ideas outlined in the agenda motions will be a plan to make
Scotland the ''Science and Innovation Capital of Europe'', and a paper
written by Mr Neil and MEP Winnie Ewing on a strategic vision for the
future of Europe and Scotland's place in it.
''We aim to prove that the kailyard Scots are in the Unionist parties
now,'' he said. ''We are the internationalists now.''
The party is going through a stiffening of central control and
narrowing of its agenda in readiness for the detail being scrutinised
during election hustings, as it was at the by-election.
This may sound rather like an outbreak of Blair-type moderation in the
party, but as one source put it: ''If we come across as crass, or
nonsensical, or threatening, we can't capitalise on the by-election
success.''
</TEXT>
