<HEADLINE>Take the time to be a credit to yourself</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SUE TRANTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TRAINING AND DEVELOPMENT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650449</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Voluntary community service encourages young people's independence,
helps others, and can boost career prospects, reports Sue Tranter.
YOUNG people who want to live away from home for a while, but need
some financial backing, can help the community, themselves, and their
careers by becoming part of a volunteer scheme.
Community Service Volunteers has been running for 30 years and has 60
offices across Britain, six of them in Scotland. On average, around 300
young Scots take advantage of the service annually, taking part for a
minimum of four months in projects dealing with the disadvantaged,
either in a group situation or on a one-to-one basis.
Volunteers are all given projects in another part of the country, free
accommodation, and a small living allowance which helps finance their
immediate needs.
With three students chasing every two university places, it's more
likely than ever that an increasing number will choose to take a year
out from their studies while they have a break, or decide on which
course they wish to commit.
Some will take fill-in jobs or even go abroad. But a spell as a
Community Service Volunteer is particularly attractive to those with a
career in education or some kind of social work in mind.
Helen McLachlan recently returned from a six-month stay in a small
English village near Basingstoke where she lived with a housebound
victim of multiple sclerosis.
''It was a lovely place surrounded by countryside and obviously
somewhere I would never have visited without CVS.'' she says.
Helen, from Dumbarton, finished her sixth year at Our Lady and St
Patrick's last year and chose to take a year off before going to
university.
''I found out about it at a careers fair and went along to the Glasgow
office. At first I wanted to work with special needs children, but I
wasn't particularly bothered when it was suggested I would be better at
working with someone one-to-one.''
''The lady I helped couldn't manage to get out on her own, and before
I got there the only assistance she had was someone who came in first
thing and in the evening. If she wanted to go anywhere she had to be put
in her car at 7am.''
Volunteers like Helen get an allowance of #50 a week for food and
spending money as well as free accommodation. No qualifications are
needed to join. According to Anne MacEwan, external relations officer
for Scotland, ''Whether it is a desire to work with the homeless, with
children who have learning difficulties, to help people with
disabilities to live independently or just to move away from home with
some financial security, CSV provides more opportunities for more
gap-year students than any other organisation.''
''We have between 8000 to 9000 projects needing helpers,'' she adds.
''Our doors are always open and we can always find work for more.
Placement depends on the person's skills, ambitions and abilities.
Students who have already done a degree also find CVS valuable as a way
to get experience, while others find it gives them the experience they
need to get onto a social work course.''
Despite the perception that volunteers are more likely to be female,
Anne adds that this is not the case, and the spread between boys and
girls is much more even.
There is an age cut-off at 35 while the maximum term for a volunteer
is 12 months. However, the first month is considered a trial period when
it is possible for a change of mind, and if a job came up demanding
immediate acceptance then obviously that would be accommodated.
While leaving Scotland might be an attraction to some volunteers, Anne
is quick to reassure others that they won't feel isolated.
''Local get-togethers are organised for volunteers and they meet one
another during their work,'' she says.
Vivienne Saber is 17 and currently working at a disability resource
centre in Paisley. She came to Scotland from her home in Westminster,
London, five months ago and will be spending another month here before
going to college in York.
''I decided to become a volunteer because I thought it would be an
ideal way to leave home and get more independence without being totally
on my own,'' she says. ''I also thought it would be a way to meet people
and give myself more confidence.'' Fortunately her expectations seem to
have been fulfilled, and she has enjoyed her time here.
''I had never been to Glasgow before and though I was offered a
specific placing in London if I had wanted it, I decided it was better
to go for something quickly so I said I really didn't mind where I was
sent.''
Clearly a flexible attitude and an enthusiasm to try out something new
rather then kicking your heels for a few months make the ideal attitude
for any volunteer.
* For more information contact CVS on 0141 204 1681.
</TEXT>
