<HEADLINE>Civil justice has its day in court</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650450</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bruce McKain, Law Correspondent, examines the case for reforming
Scotland's antiquated system of civil justice
AT long last the system of civil justice in Scotland, so long
overshadowed by crime, is getting the attention it deserves.
For understandable reasons, crime has hogged the headlines and grabbed
the imagination of the public and politicians. That is no doubt why we
have had more than a dozen pieces of legislation affecting criminal
justice in Scotland since the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1975, in
itself a major reform.
Civil justice -- dealing with divorce, road accidents, medical
negligence, and challenging the decisions of central and local
government -- has far more direct effect than crime on most of our
lives. While it has not exactly been ignored, it has been the poor
relation, with patchwork reforms dictated by recurring crises.
Contrast the situation in England, where the Lord Chancellor's review
body on civil justice reported in 1988 and Lord Woolf has recommended a
major overhaul of the system to tackle the problems of cost and delay.
The two-day conference currently being held in Aberdeen by Citizen's
Advice Scotland is the latest welcome sign that the attention gap
between civil and criminal law is now being addressed.
While the views of bodies such as CAB and the Scottish Consumer
Council are welcome, and indeed crucial to the debate, perhaps the most
encouraging sign is the clarion cry for change emanating from within the
top ranks of the legal profession itself.
The consensus seems to be that the current system is too slow, too
expensive, and too mystifying to the public who use it.
It is certainly possible for a reasonably intelligent person to sit in
on a Court of Session hearing for a considerable amount of time with
only a glimmering of comprehension.
Frequently, delay is not the fault of those who administer the system
but rather of lawyers whose clients' interests are not necessarily
served by a speedy resolution of the dispute.
In November last year the late Lord Morton of Shuna issued a blast in
a speech in the House of Lords: ''I am proud to have been appointed a
Senator of the College of Justice, but I regret that the court's
procedures have become wholly out of date. It is no pleasure to me to
have to suggest that on this issue England and Wales are so far ahead of
Scotland.''
He conceded that there had been radical reform of sheriff court
procedures to enable sheriffs to have much more control over cases and
the speed at which they proceeded through the court.
Lord Morton called for the same hands-on approach by Judges in the
Court of Session, our supreme civil court which sets out to be the jewel
in the crown of the system.
In his view the public quite rightly saw as a complete nonsense a
system where no matter how ineptly, slowly, and expensively a case was
being conducted, a judge remained a passive prisoner of the procedure,
there only as a referee to see that the fight was conducted cleanly
according to the rules.
He also demanded a ''cards-on-the table'' approach to get rid of what
he called justice by ambush by ensuring the fullest possible disclosure
of evidence by both sides at the earliest possible stage.
A few months later the cudgels were taken up by Lord Gill, at that
time the newest judge on the Scottish Bench. He condemned the
complacency which had allowed the basic structure of civil litigation in
Scotland to remain the same since 1825, faithfully applying the
tradition of nearly 200 years.
Lord Gill conceded that the Scottish system of complicated written
pleadings, taking many months to draft, might be intellectually
satisfying, but it was also time-consuming, expensive, and long past its
sell-by date.
He contrasted proceedings at the Copyright Tribunal, where it is
apparently normal to proceed straight to a hearing on cases involving
millions of pounds without complex procedural rigmarole.
Then, in May this year, Lord Hope, the Lord President, set up the
Cullen Committee to conduct a review to see how procedure in the Court
of Session could be speeded up and simplified and a greater degree of
Lord Morton-style judicial control exercised over cases.
The points raised by Lords Morton and Gill will be addressed by the
Cullen Committee, but according to research conducted for The Herald's
law page by Scottish lawyer Mike Dailly, the solutions are by no means
straightforward.
Following up Lord Morton's suggestion of the superiority of the
English system, Dailly discovered that in England it took 176 weeks
between issuing a writ and commencing or disposal of a case in the
Queen's Bench Division.
In other words, someone suing in a civil action must wait, on average,
three years for justice. This compared with a nine-month period in the
Court of Session for a case to go to proof.
In England in a personal injuries action in the High Court or County
Court, the two sides must exchange witness statements within 10 weeks of
pleadings being finalised -- in other words a cards-on-the-table
approach.
But when Mike Dailly asked the Law Society in England what effect this
had on the speed and cost of justice, the reply was that there was no
evidence it resulted in cases being settled earlier.
Concern was also expressed that it added to the costs of a case at the
early stage since that was when all the statements had to be prepared.
This detracted from the savings that could be made later from a case
being settled out of court.
So, while no-one denies the imperfections of the Scottish system, or
the attractions of the Morton/Gill ideas for reform, it is obvious that
there is no quick fix if we are to have a system of civil justice fit
for the next century.
The report of the Cullen Committee will help, but the case for a
complete civil justice review seems overwhelming, particularly if there
is to be a radical departure from our present adversarial system.
As Lord Gill put it: ''My retirement date will be 2017. If I am still
around by then I will be greatly disappointed if the system of civil
justice remotely resembles the present model.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
