<DOCID>GH950829-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Oor Wullie, Wee Willie, and one who likes cowboy pictures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650451</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILLIAM is a sturdy name. According to one keen derivation, it means a
helmet of resolution. Stout stuff is William. In print it looks shapely.
But like some other monikers, it is often not allowed to say what it
wants to say. As Mark Twain pointed out, names are not always what they
seem.'' For an example, he added: ''The common Welsh name Bzjxxllwcp is
pronounced Jackson.''
The trouble with William is worse. Seldom is it allowed to be a name
at all. Diminutive versions are preferred. One way or another about
seven changes can be rung. William is not so much a handle to a jug as
an adjustable spanner. Also, it gets slanged. And some people use it to
talk dirty. Sometimes it is just a joke.
Yet rhymers have been moved to poesy by the word's poetic qualities.
Even its bitty variety has prompted their muse:
Father calls me William,
Sister calls me Will,
Mother calls me Willie,
But the fellers call me Bill.
Less lightsome treatment has fallen upon the name. The chairman, name
of Wakeham, of the Press Complaints Commission wants to keep it out of
the newspapers. Without asking the other Wm's in the world, this Wakeham
recommends a decent obscurity for the name when it comes attached to a
princeling of the royal household.
He quoth: ''Prince William is not an institution, nor a soap star, nor
a football hero.''
Right enough, a schoolboy who is not every night on television and
doesn't kick a ball has not much obvious news value in him, especially
as a seven-letter name is a brute to fit into a headline.
To be fair (not easy), royals of assorted flavours have done much to
make William sweet. They have made a rich assortment. Kingly Williams
have been variously the Bastard, the Red, the Wise, the Silent, and the
Lion, not to forget battling Billy.
Emperor among these crowned ones was William IX, of Aquitaine, who put
the name to his output of filthy songs.
Dirtying the word has been a part of the abuse it has taken. Willy
began as a piece of schoolboy slang -- probably including Eton where
prince what'shisname is going -- but has since declined to a code work
guaranteed to put any grown-up audience in kinks.
Into knots it has sent even the most scholarly dictionaries as they
seek to illustrate the usage. For a context one tome quotes: ''The
gallant soldier boys are afflicted with syph, darling (their willies rot
away).''
Genteel willies mean a fit of nerves, while william-nilliam has been
used humorously (it says in this book) as a ponderous form of
willy-nilly. American slang employed william to describe a dollar bill.
Slang in English has taken weird forms of which the weirdest was
Willie, Willie -- wicked, wicked. At the start of this century it seems
to have been a street shout to jeer at a middle-aged woman talking to a
young man or toy boy. Somehow the voice of Alma Cogan seems to drift
over that quaint outburst.
Despite Oor Wullie and Wee Willie who ran about in his nichtgown,
William got made heavy with years. It became an old man's name. The
poets did that. Robert Southey, a rhymer of the royal court, heaped age
on the name and Lewis Carroll topped it off:
''You are old, Father William,'' the young man said.
''And your hair has become very white;
''And yet you incessantly stand on your head --
''Do you think at your age, it is right?''
''In my youth,'' Father William replied to his son,
''I feared it might injure the brain,
''But now that I'm perfectly sure I have none,
''Why, I do it again and again.''
Weary Williamness, however, springs mainly from the creation of an
unwashed, untidy, unbiddable magazine character called William Brown.
''I just don't WANT to behave like a civilised yuman bein'. I'd rather
be a savage any day,'' he was wont to utter.
This William preferred worms to girls whom he believed were the
scrubbed guardian angels of boring adult civilisation. ''They're soppy
an' batty and stuck-up an' stupid,'' he said. Even what passed for his
jokes were anti-social. Here's one.
''Which of our grand national buildings have you seen?'' said Mr
Cranthorpe-Cranborough.
''I've never been to the races,'' said William sadly. If he had a
redeeming weakness it was liking cowboy pictures.
But it wasn't William Brown's fault that he became enduringly
destructive. At first he was known only to readers of a weekly paper
called (yes!) Happy Mag. His invention was at the hands of a
schoolteacher named Richmal Crompton who hoped to make money from him so
she could concentrate on writing serious novels.
When the magazine's proprietors made a book of her first William Brown
stories, they called the collection Just William. That was in l922. It
was the first of hundreds of books about him; well, nearly 40 of them.
They were enough to see off William as a serious name. It has been just
so-so ever since.
This Wakeham chap may be right after all. The princeling at school
needs all the protection he can get from the papers. Enough for him to
take is what he's called. The parents are to blame, of course.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000121</DOCNO>
