<HEADLINE>Leading cartoonists pay tribute to Giles</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>OBITUARY</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650452</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOP cartoonists paid tribute yesterday to Carl Giles, the creator of
some of the most celebrated cartoons of the century, who has died at his
home in Suffolk.
The brolly-wielding grandmother and the cadaverous teacher Chalky
became nationwide favourites.
The Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh were fans and often requested
originals of his cartoons.
Giles worked for the Daily and Sunday Express. He began drawing for
Lord Beaverbrook's papers in 1943 and provided a look at life in Britain
for 50 years.
Stanley McMurtry, Mac of the Daily Mail, said: ''Giles was a great
influence on me although the humour is different now, more political.
''What Giles showed was gentle warmth and tremendous detail in his
drawings. I rang him up a few weeks ago to get him to come to the pub
but he wouldn't. He said he would make a comeback but I think it was
wishful thinking. He was a great character.''
Matt of the Daily Telegraph admired Giles's eye for background with
great technique.
He said: ''He was up there with the giants. In politics you have Bell,
Garland, and Vicky, and for large, humourous cartoons he and Jak of the
Standard and Mac of the Mail are the best.
''I'm a lot younger but as a kid I was given Giles annuals and they
were marvellous.''
Sir Nicholas Lloyd, editor of the Daily Express, said: ''Giles was
unique. The draughtsmanship of his cartoons and his wonderful sense of
fun were legendary.
''He was a cartoonist of the people and much loved by everyone, not
only Express readers.''
The wheelchair-bound artist, whose humorous portrayals of the Second
World War in the Daily Express made him into a national institution,
died on Sunday after several months of ill health.
He had never fully recovered from the death of his wife, Joan, last
Christmas.
</TEXT>
