<HEADLINE>Better-dressed children</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I COULDN'T agree more with Jack McLean (for once) with his mention of
hodden grey suits and old schoolwear.
I'll never forget when my mother took me to the Social Security.
My father died of pneumonia due to the muddy water in the trenches in
the First World War. She was given a coarse, hodden-grey worsted dress
big enough to fit a 14-year-old (I was only five) and big boots.
When I wore them to the primary school, the children laughed at me and
I came home crying.
Today's children are richly dressed.
Athene Burns
9 Inverbervie
North Barr,
Barr, Erskine.
</TEXT>
