<HEADLINE>Man of cultures in the health vein</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TRAINING AND DEVELOPMENT,MY JOB</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650454</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Eric Kennedy meets a microbiologist and put his career under the
microscope
BLOOD donors, it turns out, are not the only people who help humanity:
for there are laboratories up and down the country which constantly use
blood and serum in the cultivation of micro-organisms for diagnostic
purposes.
The blood, says Dr John Cameron of E &amp; O Laboratories Ltd, comes from
horses and sheep and goes to diagnostic microbiology labs throughout
Britain and Europe.
Before you ask, the horses and sheep don't get a cup of tea and a
biscuit but they are allowed a little extra grass and hay.
John Cameron, himself a microbiologist, feels the job is worthwhile.
''Cultivation and identification of harmful micro-organisms is often
the first stage in treatment of infectious diseases,'' he says. ''Our
laboratories provide blood, media and sera which are essential in this
process. It's a job whose benefits can clearly be seen.''
Being particularly interested in science, he entered Glasgow
University Faculty of Science in 1986, having left the city's Holyrood
Secondary with passes in Higher Chemistry, Biology, Physics and English,
and a Sixth Year Studies Certificate in Biology.
He became extremely interested, however, in microbiology and
concentrated on topics such as genetic approaches to bacterial
virulence, virology, medical microbiology, and vaccine development. None
of these presented him with any particular academic problems: perhaps
because by this time he was caught up in his studies.
He also spent a summer vacation working in the Central Veterinary
Laboratory, run by the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, in
Weybridge, Surrey.
That sort of activity does one's CV no harm.
He graduated B.Sc. (Hons) in microbiology in 1990, then went to
Edinburgh University to do a Ph.D. He graduated in July this year,
having spent a year and a half working as a molecular biologist while
writing his thesis.
He immediately started work with E and O in Bonnybridge, which, due to
company expansion, was offering its first full-time research and
development post. He also takes care of technical services, dealing with
inquiries from labs when, for example, they are having trouble growing
certain organisms, or have problems working with serum.
Is it an enjoyable job? ''Yes,'' he says firmly, ''There is always
something different to be done and we are kept very busy.
''And while we deal with a lot of telephone inquiries every day, I
also attend conferences and exhibitions at which I get across to people
what the company does.
''As I have said, it is a worthwhile job due to its involvement in
public health, and I feel I have chosen a particularly rewarding
career.''
</TEXT>
