<HEADLINE>Treatment for rheumatoid arthritis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650455</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE write with great concern regarding Dr Elizabeth Scott's article
(August 24) and her comments on sulphasalazine.
First, the headline with reference to the subsequent article is
incorrect since sulphasalazine is not a ''cure'' for rheumatoid
arthritis.
Secondly, rheumatoid arthritis cannot be dismisse as ''a bit of
pain''. It is a major disease causing severe joint pain, stiffness, and
swelling and an inability to carry out normal activities of daily living
such as writing, dressing, feeding, walking, toileting, and bathing.
Untreated rheumatoid arthritis causes irreversible joint destruction.
Thirdly, while sulphasalazine may cause a fall in the white cell count
this is rare and reversible. Changes in the blood count can be detected
by monitoring. This is always explained to the patient and to the
general practitioner prior to starting therapy.
The only point with which we are in agreement with Dr Scott is that
ultimately it is the informed patient who makes the decision to take the
treatment. It is undoubtedly the duty of the prescribing doctor to
explain the risks and benefits of treatment but also to recognise the
disability associated with untreated progress of the disease. We would
all like to have entirely risk-free treatments but these are not yet
available.
We would wish patients to understand that stopping treatment with
drugs such as sulphasalazine in controlled rheumatoid arthritis will
result in a deterioration in their disease over a period of weeks to
months.
We suggest that an alternative explanation for the fact that patients
chose to take drugs such as sulphasalazine is that they have weighed up
the risks, benefits, and the impact of the disease after receiving
adequate explanation on all three counts from informed practitioners.
It is unfortunate that Dr Scott appears to have focused on only one
part of the risk/benefit equation.
Dr Pitkeithley, Dr Fraser, Dr Marshall, Dr Murphy, Dr McGill, Dr
Larkin, Dr Porter, Dr Madhok, Dr Capell, and Dr Zoma,
On behalf of the West of Scotland Rheumatology Group, Centre for
Rheumatic Diseases,
Royal Infirmary, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
