<HEADLINE>Scottish timeshares under the hammer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650456</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HUNDREDS of bargain-hunters are expected to take part this week in
Scotland's first timeshare holiday auction.
Interest in the sale has been so intense that the catalogue has been
reprinted twice and a second auction is to be held early next year.
About 200 weeks at 13 of the 17 Scottish timeshare resorts will come
under the hammer at the Royal Scot Hotel in Edinburgh on Thursday.
Although most of the catalogue requests have come from Scots, many of
those interested are English and some inquiries have come from the
Continent.
Skiing weeks at Aviemore, Open Golf dates at Kilconquhar, close to St
Andrews, and Christmas weeks at several centres are among the lots on
sale. Most of the deals entitle people to stays at timeshare resorts
abroad.
A school holiday fortnight at Kenmore, Perthshire, where the
attractions include salmon fishing, golf, sailing, and water sports, is
expected to raise more than #20,000. However, the list also includes
attractive weeks which could be available for around #2000, and there
are 35 with either no lowest price set or reserves of less than #1000.
Mr Alasdair Seale, managing director of Trinity Factors, Edinburgh,
the auction's organisers, said yesterday: ''We were getting dozens of
calls a day with catalogue requests and we ended up having 800 copies
done. There is certainly potential for some bargains.''
He added: ''We already have registrations for our next timeshare
auction, next March.''
</TEXT>
