<HEADLINE>After the resignation of James Molyneaux, Russell Edmunds looks at the front-runners for the leadership of the Ulster Unionists. Battle for the future of Unionism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUSSELL EDMUNDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was the briefest of resignation notes. Just two paragraphs
signalling the end of James Molyneaux's 16-year leadership of the Ulster
Unionist Party.
Suddenly, as Northern Ireland recalls the first anniversary of the IRA
ceasefire, his departure places a new uncertainty over the province's
political future.
The resignation of Molyneaux, who was 75 on Sunday, has been the
subject of intense speculation since the British and Irish Governments
published their agreed proposals for the future of Ulster last spring.
Many Unionists were angry that the trust placed by Molyneaux in his
personal friendship with John Major was not reflected, as they saw it,
in the Government's ''joint framework documents'' with Dublin.
These proposals promised a political settlement which would give the
Irish Government a greater input into Northern Ireland's future than
that agreed in 1985 by Margaret Thatcher. In that year Molyneaux had
come under attack for pinning too much faith in Thatcher. Assurances he
had given to Unionists appeared to backfire when she agreed to give
Dublin a strong consultative say in Ulster.
His resignation took Belfast by surprise, especially since he had
conveyed the impression recently that he would continue until next year.
Instead he chose to step down on his birthday, confiding in only a
handful of his closest party colleagues and issuing a terse statement
saying he had taken his decision to enable a successor to be chosen in
time to prepare for the next General Election, which ''could come
earlier than would have appeared six months ago''.
He added: ''Might I make it absolutely clear that I have no intention
of making any further comment on my decision.'' The succinctness was
typical of a man of few words and the lowest of political profiles.
Unlike other leaders in the cauldron of Irish politics, he was a master
of understatement, preferring to avoid the television studios and to
shun the headlines.
''Where Northern Ireland is concerned, I do not believe in high-wire
politics,'' he once said, and that was his guiding principle in recent
years even though Unionist supporters sometimes despaired at his
unwillingness to play a more prominent role, in contrast to the loud and
verbose tactics of the rival Democratic Unionist Party leader, Ian
Paisley.
Molyneaux believed in working behind the scenes at Westminster,
quietly trying to persuade successive governments to maintain Northern
Ireland's constitutional position within the UK and to reject the
advances of the Irish Government and Ulster nationalists. In the end,
even his closest party colleagues lost faith in his strategy. As they
sought a more strident approach to defending the Union, so their message
to Molyneaux was that it was time for him to go.
Throughout his career as leader, Molyneaux was constantly looking over
his shoulder at Paisley. Somehow, until recently, he had managed to
subdue the thunder of the Free Presbyterian leader who had emerged in
the early 1970s with his new Democratic Unionist Party. One by one,
Ulster Unionist leaders had fallen in the face of Paisley's fiery
Protestant rhetoric, each of them condemned for allegedly selling-out
the Unionist cause.
Molyneaux, with his impeccable Orange Order connections, built a trust
among grassroots Protestants that even Paisley could not dent. When
asked privately how he had managed to keep the right-wing politics of
Paisley in check, he replied wryly: ''Simple, I out-right him.'' By that
he meant that he could appear just as fundamentally Protestant as
Paisley, by marching proudly at the head of Protestant parades,
unveiling Orange banners, and generally conveying a conservative
Unionist message to the faithful.
In the end that was not enough as Paisley raged last year that he was
a ''Judas Iscariot'', a reference to his apparent closeness to John
Major, and the Unionist party grew weary and wary of his assurances
about the Government's intentions towards Ulster.
Molyneaux's resignation adds confusion to the quest for a lasting
political settlement. Friday marks the first anniversary of the IRA
ceasefire but there remains no sign of inter-party talks involving Sinn
Fein. Neither of the two main Unionist parties is prepared to
countenance such dialogue, although Molyneaux's party might if the IRA
were to agree to decommission its terrorist arsenal.
Molyneaux's departure puts Unionist strategy in limbo for a few more
weeks at least. A new leader is expected to be chosen by mid-September
but who that will be and what if any new approach he may propose is
unclear. Despite a year of peace, Unionists are in no mood for the kind
of political settlement involving Dublin which their nationalist
opponents have in mind. This summer brought bitter street clashes over
the re-routing of Protestant marches away from Catholic areas and
grassroots Unionist opinion is deeply suspicious of what it sees as
unwarranted concessions to Sinn Fein over the peace process and the rise
in political confidence of the Irish nationalists.
Four of Molyneaux's colleagues at Westminster have emerged as
front-runners for the leadership. They are the party's high-profile
security spokesman, Ken Maginnis, 57, MP for Fermanagh and South Tyrone;
the Chief Whip, William Ross, 59, East Londonderry MP; Orange Order
leader, the Rev Martin Smyth, 64, who is MP for South Belfast; and John
Taylor, 57, MP for Strangford.
A weekend opinion poll conducted by an Irish Sunday newspaper put
Maginnis as the most popular and Ross as a virtual also-ran even before
the race begins. Significantly, the second most popular Unionist figure
was David Trimble, the sternly articulate MP for Armagh, who says he is
not a candidate for the leadership. Trimble, a university law lecturer,
has gained support for his forthright defence of Unionist principles in
television debates and for his tough stand this summer in support of
Protestant parades.
Taylor, a former minister in the old Stormont government, and
Maginnis, are particularly disliked by hardline Paisleyites. Both men
have accused Paisley of damaging Unionist interests with his firebrand
international image. Ross and Smyth have followed a more conventional
political road, rarely, if ever, making statements that might disturb
the party faithful.
But now the battle for the future of Ulster Unionism is joined, all
the contenders know their best chance is not to rock the party boat. An
uncompromising message in defence of the Union and a determination to
withstand the mounting pressures of Irish nationalism -- when the Ulster
Unionist Party's 900 delegates meet to select the new leader next month,
that is what they will want to hear, no matter how strongly London or
Dublin, John Hume or Gerry Adams may wish it to be otherwise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
