<HEADLINE>Zadar drags itself out of crater</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650458</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As the mortar shells land once more in Sarajevo, ripping the city and
its people apart, Tom Gallagher relates how one Croatian city is trying
to patch up the scars of war
A SENSE of euphoria still hangs over the coast city of Zadar, capital
of Old Dalmatia, almost a month after the Croatian army managed to
retake high ground to the east as it occupied the Krajina region.
On the evening I arrived in town, cars with the Croatian flag
extending from rear windows were a common sight as they rattled across
town. Soldiers in fatigues were being feted in cafes. But at least no
guns were being fired in the air: that would only have been to emphasise
similarities with the despised Serbian foe.
However, in 1990 militants from Franjo Tudjman's party had smashed up
Serb businesses in the town in response to the sabre-rattling of Krajina
Serbs intent on pulling out of Croatia. Unlike the other towns on the
Dalmatian coast, Zadar warmed to Tudjman's brand of intransigent
nationalism and voted solidly for his HDZ party in 1990 and thereafter.
Memories still festered of occupation by Italy between the two wars
which culminated in savage Allied bombing raids in 1942-43.
In 1991 Zadar was bombed from the sea and land and sporadically
shelled. Ana, a student at the local university, recalled days on end
without water or electricity in which many of the 130,000 population
crammed into underground cellars. She was still bitter that Serb gunners
had aimed their most withering fire at the city's churches, the oldest
one, St Donat's, being associated with the Irish saint who had
re-implanted Christianity along this stretch of the eastern Adriatic.
Zadar connects north Dalmatia and Zagreb, the Croatian capital, with
the rest of the Croatian coast as far south as Dubrovnik. If Croatia is
seen as two sides of a triangle, reaching eastwards into central Europe
and southwards down the Adriatic coast, the town is placed at a most
vulnerable point. If it had fallen to Serb forces, Croatia would have
been effectively partitioned and Belgrade would have achieved the
coveted access to the sea which land-locked Serbia lacks.
Croatia's difficult geography almost meant that its rebirth as a state
was stillborn. But the local defenders of Zadar held their ground and
showed that the Yugoslav army and Serb militia were not as mighty as
London, Paris, and Washington have always assumed.
Sand-bagged churches and public buildings still bear the scars of war
but inland the devastation is far more systematic. For almost 15 miles
up to the destroyed Maslenica bridge few houses have escaped shell
damage and hundreds have been pounded to rubble. Those that have been
dynamited from within are likely to have belonged to Serbs, the subject
of revenge attacks by embittered Croats.
Cars and lorries crawl across the 825ft pontoon bridge erected in
July, 1993, after Croatia had retaken the hinterland behind Zadar. Many
had predicted that the fragile ceasefire which had come into being in
1992 would collapse as a result of Croat efforts to restore what is
still the only road link between south and north Croatia. However, a few
days later the Croat President met with Serbia's President Milosevic
which rekindled rumours that both might do a deal by partitioning Bosnia
between them.
Today these rumours are once again on many lips.
Whatever the endgame for Bosnia proves to be, plans are already afoot
to blast a motorway through the mountains above Zadar to halve the
journey time from Zagreb to the Croatian coast, thereby reviving the
touristic fortunes of the area. Already there is a glimmer of hope: on
the offshore islands of Pasman and Ugjian the foreign yachting
fraternity have started to return. These islands are only a short ferry
trip from Zadar but they might be another world away, the war having
failed to shatter their calm.
Zadar's inhabitants are patching up their historic quarter in the hope
that the Corinthian columns and Romanesque churches visible from the
islands will tempt visitors across. Today the only big-spending
foreigners belong to the UN protection force.
* Tom Gallagher is a lecturer in the Department of Peace Studies,
University of Bradford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Code to avoid can of serpents</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART LAMONT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stewart Lamont believes 'clergy codes' could be the first step by
churches to fend off compensation claims from those abused by errant
ministers.
THERE I was drinking tea, sitting next to an attractive young divorcee
on her white leather couch . . . a couple of days later, on Sunday, I
was standing in a local pub in my dog collar less than an hour after
stepping out of the pulpit. All this in the same week as I returned
after 11pm from visiting a member of my flock.
Is this the confession you have all been waiting for? Will the
Presbytery of Glasgow soon be defrocking the errant minister of Kinning
Park? The charge: breaking three of the ''commandments'' which were
issued by the Bishop of Oxford's working party to keep Anglican clergy
on the straight and narrow.
Well, not quite. I have a defence, Moderator. On the first occasion
there was no other seat in the living room, apart from the one occupied
by another lady who is going to be matron of honour at the forthcoming
wedding. So by having a chaperone present, I hopefully escape censure.
The second occasion was a family baptism in which the godmother (and
aunt of the baby) was using the pub of which she is manager for a
private christening party and many of those present were, like her,
members of my congregation. OK, Moderator?
Oh, and the third occasion I had arranged to visit this family after
an evening meeting and it went on rather long. Is that me off the hook?
The reason I have cited these three examples is that it is all too
easy to see how doing a normal week's work as a clergyman can create
situations in which the ''clergy code'' is breached. All three examples
mentioned are true and they all occurred as recently as last week. All
three situations are specific instances to which the Oxford group allude
in its clergy code.
Sitting on settees with single ladies is out. Visiting same after 9pm
or being seen taking alcoholic drink while on duty are all warned
against. Rightly so. But whether the guidelines -- and that is all they
are -- are necessary will surely be questioned.
Most clergymen would be expected to use common sense in doing their
duty. In today's world, with stories of sex abuse and harassment
abounding, it is surely doubly necessary to be as innocent as doves and
as wise as serpents. The latter bit consists of not just being innocent
but being seen to be innocent (or rather not giving anyone the
opportunity to imagine you are guilty).
It is all too obvious that the situations in which impropriety arises,
or is alleged to have occurred, are no longer as rare as they once were.
The recent and much-publicised case of the Dean of Lincoln (cleared of
wrongdoing after a late-evening visit to a lady verger became a cause of
scandalous accusations) was swiftly followed by the can of serpents
opened when the ''rave'' vicar in Sheffield, the Rev Chris Brain, was
exposed as a sexual abuser and suspended.
There have been a number of stories in the past year linking Roman
Catholic priests with sexual abuse, and a Kirk minister is currently
serving a prison sentence for the same crime.
In one sense they are part of a wider picture in which moral weakness
seems more common in society and in the professions than it once was.
The professional bodies are, therefore, being forced to spell out
professional standards which were once taken for granted.
The Kirk's Board of Ministry presented a code of professional conduct
to the last General Assembly within its report. Less specific than the
Oxford group's guidelines, it dealt, among other things, with the need
to observe confidentiality and sexual propriety in pastoral
relationships; being circumspect in handling money; and not making false
claims to qualifications.
Rather neatly, it fell into 10 sections -- allowing it to be described
as ''commandments'', but it has yet to have the force of law in the
Kirk.
It is in the same position as the Bishop of Oxford's report -- it is a
guide. Churches like the Roman Catholic church have a much more specific
system of moral code for clergy in canon law which covers matters such
as whether a priest may sport a moustache. But when it comes to the kind
of thing which got the Dean of Lincoln into trouble it relies on common
sense.
Father Tom Connelly, the media spokesman for the Roman Catholic church
in Scotland, sums up the advice given to trainee priests as being ''use
caution, common sense, and discretion. That covers things like calling
at houses in the late evening or visiting one house rather too often.''
He applies the same advice to the more open form of face-to-face
confession which is available in some Catholic churches but which does
not seem to have caught on in Scotland.
However, no matter how commonsensical the guidelines of Anglican,
Catholic, and Presbyterian churches may be, the signs are that these
churches will be forced into turning them into commandments and making
them mandatory.
There are two reasons for this. The first reflects modern concern for
''rights'' in the area of employment. This is strengthened on the one
hand by the need to protect against unfair dismissal and on the other to
be able to have legislation by which the bad apple can be plucked from
the barrel.
The second -- and much more significant -- reason was revealed by the
Archdeacon of Sheffield, the Venerable Stephen Lowe, the man who
suspended the rave vicar. The Oxford guidelines were not relevant to the
case of Mr Brain who, the Archdeacon said, would not have acknowledged
that he was misbehaving. However, he added: ''Maybe we need to look at
the idea here a lot more carefully. It's been around in America a lot
longer because they have the risk of being sued.''
The possibility of such lawsuits becoming more commonplace in Britain
is an increasing one. For instance, a woman abused by a clergyman could
sue his employer, his diocese or Presbytery.
That could be a very costly and difficult situation. Dioceses and
presbyteries would need to be insured against such an eventuality.
However, if they could show that they had guidelines which disallowed
certain forms of conduct, when a clergyman breached these he would
become personally liable for his conduct and they would not be held to
be liable as his employer.
In other words, the issuing of guidelines could be the first step for
churches to protect themselves against those who want compensation for
the failure of the churches to protect them from abuse.
It's a crazy situation in which common sense goes out the window while
insurance men and lawyers come in the front door.
Sitting on the white leather couch, will I be insured for damages if I
spill my tea and leave a stain -- or will the stain turn out to be on my
character?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000129</DOCNO>
