<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prelim exams set to disappear.   Blueprint for secondary reform puts emphasis on internal assessment of courses.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN,EDUCATION CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRELIM examinations for fifth and sixth-year pupils are likely to
disappear under the Government's blueprint for reforming upper secondary
schooling.
Most secondaries currently set prelims in December and January to
check the progress pupils have made before their Higher exams, and to
use as ammunition if a school wishes to appeal on behalf of those who
fail to achieve their expected grades.
But in a consultation document issued yesterday which describes how
subjects are to be organised and assessed under the Higher Still
programme, prelims are described as ''time-consuming''.
Under the reform, courses which will last 160 hours will be externally
assessed by the new qualifications body to be formed by the merger of
the Scottish Examination Board and Scotvec, which is responsible for
vocational education.
Courses will be divided into units, normally of 40 hours' duration,
which will be internally assessed by teachers in school.
Chief inspector of schools Mr Ron Tuck, a leading light in the Higher
Still development, said yesterday there were many benefits in internal
assessment.
In an effort to placate teachers who are expressing concern about the
amount of assessment in the five-14 programme and in Standard Grade, he
said: ''It will not dominate the lives of students, or dominate
teaching.''
Both he and the senior chief inspector of schools, Mr Nisbet
Gallacher, hoped the assessment of units could be simplified when
teachers were gauging whether pupils had met the targets they were set.
They hoped the teacher assessments thoughout courses would ''reduce or
eliminate'' the need for prelim exams.
The disappearance of prelims would also free more time for teaching,
particularly in the fifth year where the present Higher has come under
attack as a ''two-term dash'' to the exam period.
Yesterday's document makes it clear that external exams could be
shortened because of the enhanced role of internal assessment. The SEB
has already proposed shortening the exam diet to allow more time for the
longer Higher Still courses.
The key part of the document says good performance throughout a
course, verified by unit assessments, may overturn a poor performance in
the externally-assessed final exam.
This will happen if a school's overall estimates for the pupils
presented are generally consistent with actual results. The level of
award given to a pupil who has done less well than expected in the final
exam ''will be automatically improved, prior to the issue of results''.
In a further acknowledgement of the need to safeguard the best
interests of pupils, a ''safety net'' is to be provided for the new
Advanced Higher, which will replace the Certificate of Sixth-Year
Studies. The Advanced Higher will be a two-year course lasting 320 hours
in each subject intended to prepare pupils for higher education.
However, there had been criticism of the proposals because they
encouraged able pupils to by-pass the Higher exam at the end of fifth
year in the expectation that they would pass the final exam after the
two-year programme.
Now pupils who fail the Advanced Higher may be awarded a compensatory
Higher on appeal if they have passed the assessment of the fifth-year
units at Higher level.
The Advanced Higher will be introduced in 1999, one year after the
implementation of Higher Still.
The reform is being introduced because the present system of Highers
is beyond the reach of a large percentage of the growing number of young
people staying on after 16.
Higher Still aims to put vocational education on an equal footing with
academic subjects and, with that in mind, Scotvec's National
Certificates, which build up to group awards, are being given a central
place in the framework.
*
</TEXT>
