<HEADLINE>Blood service accused of trying to 'gag' staff</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANAGEMENT at the National Blood Authority, recently affected by a
scandal over leaking blood bags, were accused yesterday of trying to gag
their staff over serious safety concerns.
Draft guidelines obtained by the Labour Party say staff who want to
raise cases of exceptional concern must exhaust all internal procedures
before contacting their MP or the media.
The guidelines, drawn up by the authority which is responsible for
managing the blood tranfusion service in England and Wales, warn that
failure to comply with instructions could result in disciplinary action.
The guidelines do not apply to the Scottish National Blood Transfusion
Service, which requires only that staff make clear they are speaking on
their own behalf rather than for the service.
A spokeswoman for the Scottish service said: ''We believe in openness,
subject to the normal constraints of patient or donor confidentiality
which apply throughout the health service. We have many staff,
particularly doctors, who have to speak publicly on professional
matters.''
Labour health spokeswoman Ms Tessa Jowell said it was ''outrageous''
for the NBA to try to prevent staff from raising matters of concern with
their elected representatives.
''The audacity of the NBA beggars belief. People have a basic right to
approach their MP with any concern at any time. It is not for the NBA to
decide when they can or can't do this,'' she said.
She said the NBA's stance was a matter of particular concern following
the incident earlier this year when Australian-made Tuta blood bags had
to be withdrawn after they were found to have faulty seals, exposing
them to the risk of infection.
An NBA spokeswoman said the guidelines were still being discussed with
National Blood Service unions. However, she claimed they were based on
practices and procedures used throughout the National Health Service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
