<HEADLINE>Lawyers to pay #11,000 for sacking</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Acas course on employers' duties will cost two lawyers #10,956 --
after they unfairly sacked a typist.
An industrial tribunal has labelled the lawyers' actions
''unreasonable, arbitrary, and unilateral''.
Mr Cornelius McAfee and Mr Richard Ackland, who trade as McAfee
Criminal Defence Lawyers, were ordered to pay compensation to Mrs Mary
Mullen, of Braehead Avenue, Kirkshaws, Coatbridge.
Mrs Mullen had been employed by the lawyers at their Coatbridge office
from August 1983 until she was forced to retire, aged 61, in February of
this year.
Problems started for the lawyers after Mr Ackland attended the Acas
course last autumn and discovered that employers should issue statements
of terms and conditions of employment to staff.
After discussions with Mr McAfee, who thought the retirement age for
women was 60, the lawyers inserted 60 in the employment contracts but,
when they learned Mrs Mullen was already that age, the contracts were
altered to 61.
The tribunal noted: ''Everything was fine until Mr Ackland went to the
Acas course. On his return, it was like the blind leading the blind.''
In declaring Mrs Mullen was unfairly dismissed, the tribunal said:
''The respondents unilaterally sought to insert a term into the
applicant's contract of employment that would have required her to
retire within three months of their notification of it.
''They took no proper steps to ascertain that she consented to such a
change. There was no prior consultation.''
The respondents had acted in an unreasonable, arbitrary, and
unilateral manner which fell foul of any standards of fairness towards
an employee.
''The imposition of a retiral age of 61 was not a sufficient reason
for dismissing the applicant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
