<HEADLINE>Small towns must wait for by-pass schemes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW roads to relieve congested small towns must wait until core
network improvements are complete, Scottish Transport Minister Lord
James Douglas-Hamilton said yesterday in a move to divert criticism over
by-pass delays.
In a letter to the British Roads Federation, the Minister admitted
that funding was a ''major issue'' behind the postponement of many new
routes. However, he said a recent survey by the pressure group was wrong
to suggest that the concerns of communities over traffic volume had been
disregarded.
BRF reported last week that nearly two thirds of Scotland's by-pass
schemes now are delayed, predicting that at current completion rates, it
will take 35 years to finish the current tranche of new roads.
However, the Minister said: ''Although the financial constraints that
we are under mean that many construction schemes are being deferred,
significant improvements are being made in many other areas.''
These involved Route Action Plans and ''traffic calming'' measures,
which used one-way systems, efficient traffic lighting, and roundabouts
as quicker and cheaper alternatives to by-passes.
He added that his department's priority was ''to concentrate the
majority of funds on the strategic network to ensure a core of
first-class routes for the strategic commercial traffic of vital
importance to the country's economy.''
However, while welcoming the Minister's interest in his group's
report, BRF campaign co-ordinator Andrew Pharaoh said the letter offered
little comfort to areas waiting by-passes.
</TEXT>
