<HEADLINE>The child abuse trap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH WESTCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Suspicions of child sexual abuse can lead to misery and injustice: Dr
Elizabeth Westcott discusses the anguish of a parent unable to prove his
innocence
CHILD sexual abuse is our greatest social taboo. For far too long, our
society has found the practice so deeply repulsive, that we have
unwittingly protected the perpetrators by our inability to acknowledge
and expose what they do.
Now we are developing methods of seeking them out and punishing them,
but progress down this path is proving extremely difficult. Child sexual
abuse cannot be approached objectively. The word ''abuse'' itself is a
moral category.
There is some evidence to suggest that social workers, in the Ayrshire
case and other instances, are struggling with this lack of objectivity.
Their role demands they make moral judgments on the character of
guardians, during the thousands of investigations into family situations
undertaken each year.
The principal officer of childcare at Strathclyde Regional Council,
Greg Gallagher, believes the difficulty lies in the deep layers of
secrecy shrouding the issue, and the fact that child sexual abuse has
only been a recognised category in Scotland since 1989: ''Because it's
such a new area we can't always get it right, but there's a dilemma: we
have adult survivors telling us they tried to speak out and no-one heard
them,'' he says.
According to Sue Amphlett, spokesperson for the support group PAIN
(Parents Against Injustice) families under investigation find the
experience intensely traumatic. Not knowing how the system works, or how
to get access to the relevant information, these families are
disempowered by the bureaucratic machine. Changes must be made, she
says, to recognise and help the victims of what she calls ''system
abuse''.
Dr David Thorpe, author of Evaluating Child Protection goes even
further in his appraisal of the British child protection system. He
believes intervention is currently based on an inadequate subjective
framework and calls for a ''radical reconceptualisation of the
apparatus''.
One victim of ''system abuse'' is Stuart White, who shares a house in
Glasgow with his de facto partner June Kenny, her two children from a
previous marriage and their daughter Laura. Two years ago he was accused
of sexually molesting his daughter, and despite the complete absence of
evidence he remains under investigation. The process, he says, has
destroyed his life.
On one Friday evening in November 1993, June went to collect Laura
from her nursery. To her surprise, she was summoned to the principal's
office where she was confronted by the principal, a social worker and a
policewoman. She was told an allegation of abuse had been made against
Stuart, and that all three children might be removed from her care if
she did not co-operate in accompanying the officer to the police
station. Although the alleged disclosure occurred in the morning and an
interview had taken place, neither parent was informed till almost five
hours later.
June was told by the social worker that a medical examination would
settle the matter, so everyone trooped off to Yorkhill Hospital, where a
doctor took vaginal swabs from Laura. He said there were no signs of
sexual abuse and he wouldn't need to see her again.
Later, June phoned Stuart from her mother's, to let him know what had
happened. The police had visited already, looking for him. The police
told June, in front of her mother: ''We know Mr White did it, because it
happens in the nicest of families.''
Not long after June's phone call, the police arrived on Stuart's
doorstep, wanting to interview him: ''They pushed their way into the
house and told me Laura had made a verbal statement of abuse, but they
wouldn't tell me what. Who do I sue? I asked. They left, saying they
would be seeing me,'' said Stuart.
The medical examination did not settle the matter; in fact it was only
the beginning of a two-year struggle to get information from the
relevant authorities -- including what Laura allegedly said. Unknown to
Stuart and June, the case went to the Children's Reporter, whose
considerable powers include bringing a case to court on the balance of
probability.
It was discussed at three case conferences, only two of which they
were informed about and even then were not permitted to attend, but had
to wait outside (''like naughty children,'' says June). Nor were they
given summaries of the case conferences, which is a legal requirement.
''Social workers would not give me any information whatsoever, not
even guidelines to procedures,'' says Stuart.
''The medical examination would have been the end of the matter if it
had been in their favour; social workers need two pieces of binding
information, the medical and the original allegation, before it can be
taken to court.''
Stuart and June guessed that the recurring inflammation, similar to
nappy rash, which Laura suffered from, probably triggered the original
allegation. They took her to a specialist, who told them it was ''sore
bottom syndrome'' caused by anal bacteria. When Stuart was finally
notified by letter from a social worker as to what words Laura actually
used, this is what the letter said: ''That my bottom is sore, that Daddy
made it sore, made it sore inside too and her daddy kissed it better.''
According to Stuart, at the time the allegation was made Laura could
hardly put together a three-word sentence. This was later verified by a
speech therapist who said that while she could not make a statement as
to how the child spoke a year ago, she found it highly unlikely that a
child with Laura's speech difficulties should have made such a full
disclosure. So what did Laura say? Did she nod in response to suggestive
questioning? Could she have said something easily misinterpreted by an
employee who was eager to read between the lines?
''What upsets me,'' says Stuart, ''is the complete refusal by the
authorities to even consider that the case was possibly unfounded.''
After Stuart and June became aware of the involvement of the
Children's Reporter, they had to wait for four months before being sent
a brief letter stating: ''I have decided to take no futher action.''
Once again, they hoped this would end the investigation.
However, they discovered that the third case conference had placed
Laura on the Child Protection register, which effectively means that if
any harm befalls Laura which can't be accounted for, she may be taken
and placed in care. They were also denied access to the social worker's
file on the case, for which Stuart had applied, because the case remains
under police investigation.
Stuart feels that from the outset the authorities have treated him as
guilty. The fact he has not been proven innocent not only keeps him
awake at night, it drives him to continue writing letters (well over 300
by now) and filing complaints against both social workers and the
police.
''Nothing can be done to get the police to cross-examine the person
who made the allegation. There's no professional body of social workers
to complain to -- they can say what they like,'' says Stuart.
''The police have said that nothing is proved against me and the
Children's Reporter dropped the case -- why? There wasn't even a
hearing. And yet my daughter is on the at-risk register. At every turn
of the key what I had to say has been ignored.''
Spokesperson for PAIN Sue Amphlett says that Stuart's frustration and
anger is typical of what families under investigation have to endure.
''People become physically and mentally ill or suicidal, their lives
are permanently altered by the investigative process without any
recognition of the trauma -- and then the majority of cases are thrown
back into the sea.
''Meanwhile, very well-meaning social workers are forced to live with
the fact that while they are identifying some kids as victims of abuse,
they are inadvertently harming others.''
PAIN's figures show that 80% of families under investigation don't
have access to relevant information. While social workers do not have
too much power, the balance of power is unequal.
''Advocacy needs to be provided for families, either funded by the
Government or local authorities,'' says Amphlett. ''There should be an
independent body for arbitration and complaints, under the auspices of a
family ombudsman.
''Children have rights, but it's dangerous to build up the rights of
the child without building up the rights of the family. We have got
ourselves into an investigative trap.''
Social workers have the unenviable task of wading through this
minefield, often attacked by both sides, in order to fulfil their
child-protection brief. Greg Gallagher says that while it is
understandable that parents feel aggrieved at being the subject of
investigation, there are few instances where social workers are
completely mistaken.
''Children speak obliquely but there's not always nothing going on.
Manipulation is the name of the game in relation to child sexual abuse.
''The evidence coming in from convicted abusers about the manipulation
they used in an effort to keep their crime undetected makes your hair
stand on end and I don't say that lightly,'' he says.
''My own feeling is that social workers try extremely hard not to go
half-baked into an investigation, and current procedures do demand that
we look closely. There's a lot of debate about who should be
investigating, psychiatrists or perhaps a special team, but at the
moment the social workers have the body of knowledge needed. To retrain
a special group would be a backward step.
''We are meant to be guardians of morality but as soon as we begin to
do that, restrictions are placed on us because folk find it
unpalatable.''
Stuart White now believes that because he and June are not married,
and he has maintained a separate address in England, he is being
discriminated against: a suspicion which Dr Thorpe's research into child
protection appears to confirm.
Dr Thorpe's British and Australian case studies demonstrate that
alternative families, with only one parent or a de facto arrangement,
are far more likely to be under investigation by child protection
authorities. The subjective norm of the ideal home and family, fed by
constant images, is deeply ingrained in all of us, social workers
included. When a family situation deviates from the norm, says Dr
Thorpe, it triggers a forensic gaze for evidence of abuse.
''It's impossible to regulate the power of social workers -- it goes
much, much deeper than that,'' he says. ''There needs to be a radical
reconceptualisation of the whole apparatus of intervention. Child
protection ideologies have to be rethought and workers need to be
retrained.''
There are two aspects to Dr Thorpe's review of child protection.
First, the word ''abuse'' must go. Currently it is used to mean
everything from the death of a child through to minor caregiver
shortcomings.
Secondly, there needs to be a specially trained team to deal with the
families where children are being deliberately and identifiably harmed,
as opposed to other kinds of social work which deals with children in
less than ideal conditions.
Lifting the lid on child sexual abuse is like opening Pandora's box:
inside is crammed with the complex, horrifying ghouls of our deepest
social malaise. As Stuart White ironically points out, while vindication
or any sense of proving his own innocence is dwindling into a forlorn
hope, somewhere a child is being sexually abused and nothing is being
done to stop it.
* All names in this article have been changed to protect the identity
of our sources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
