<HEADLINE>Lanark blue cheese sample in the clear, claims owner</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PIECE of Lanark blue cheese alleged to contain 5000 times the
permitted level of listeria monocytogenes was clear of the organisms
when re-tested, a court heard yesterday.
Many other allegedly heavily contaminated samples showed either no
sign of the organism or contained low levels which were not dangerous,
cheesemaker Humphrey Errington claimed.
Giving evidence on Day 11 of the case at Lanark Sheriff Court in which
Clydesdale District Council seeks an order to destroy #27,000 of Lanark
blue, Mr Errington produced certificates from three accredited
laboratories showing test results on cheese samples before they were
deep frozen on his farm at Walston Braehead, near Dunsyre, Lanarkshire.
These samples had been tested by Western General Hospital in Edinburgh
and Monklands Hospital in Airdrie and revealed what environmental health
officers described as ''unacceptable levels of listeria''.
However, Mr Errington said he doubted the accuracy of the hospital
tests and said that, on re-testing, listeria was not discovered.
A harmless strain of listeria was found in the composite sample --
cheese pieces taken from the inside of a number of cheeses and blended
together.
Mr Errington told the court that he could not believe the high levels
of listeria found by the Scottish Agricultural College in February.
The suspect cheese had by then been deep frozen on his farm. He took
many samples from the deep frozen batches and sent them for further
testing at different laboratories.
Mr Errington went on to produce more certificates from different test
centres, in Bellshill, Halifax, and Gloucestershire, all showing
significantly lower levels of listeria than those found by the SAC.
The court had previously heard that listeria could be reduced by as
much as 60% in cheese when it was deep frozen.
Mr Errington said that, in January, he took soundings from the trade
on the listeria problem in blue and other cheese.
He said the managing director of a wholesale company in London told
him he regularly checked for listeria.
That firm provides cheese to Heathrow Airport airlines, Harrods, and
leading hotels in London, such as the Ritz.
Mr Errington said: ''The MD told me he would inform the authorities
only if listeria levels were discovered to be in excess of 100,000 per
gramme -- and even then he would not necessarily withdraw it and notify
the manufacturer.''
Mr Errington said his whole dairy had been examined from top to bottom
for a source of listeria but nothing had been found.
The case continues.
</TEXT>
