<HEADLINE>Primp for a premiere</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STIRLING -- dubbed the dirtiest town in Scotland by snooker supremo
Ian Doyle -- is to get a special clean-up before the visit of Hollywood
star Mel Gibson for this Sunday's European premiere of the film
Braveheart.
Stirling District Council's cleansing division said yesterday it had
organised its own Operation Braveheart to make sure the town was as
clean as possible.
A special squad of 14 street cleaners will be on the beat from 9am on
Sunday until 1am Monday morning.
They will concentrate on the town centre and the route to be taken by
the stars from the MacRobert Arts Centre, where the film premiere will
take place, to Stirling Castle, where 700 guests will attend a lavish
post-premiere party.
Every piece of litter will be removed and all bins emptied.
Earlier this month, millionaire Doyle -- who lives near the arts
centre -- said parts of the town were an absolute disgrace and bosses at
Stirling District Council should be ''for the chop''.
Mr Doyle, manager of superstar Stephen Hendry, said some American
visitors had told him Stirling was the dirtiest town they had seen in
the whole of Scotland.
However, a council spokesman said yesterday: ''This spruce-up would
have happened regardless of what Mr Doyle said. We want the town to look
its best for its special day.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Owners get more time to repair 'A' list building</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OWNERS of Glasgow's historic Lion Chambers are being given six months
to come up with the #1.7m required to save the grade ''A'' listed
building.
The eight-storey reinforced concrete structure in Hope Street is now
covered in protective scaffolding following an incident in March when
pieces of the structure fell on to the pavement in Hope Street.
Consequently, a dangerous- building notice was served on the various
owners but, so far, it has not been complied with.
Instead, the owners sought permission to demolish the building because
of the prohibitive costs of reinstating its structural integrity.
A council sub-committee on development control refused permission in
view of the building's architectural and historic importance.
Indeed, Historic Scotland has stated that Lion Chambers -- designed by
Salmon and Gillespie and built between 1904 and 1907 -- is of European
significance and that it would be ''unthinkable'' to demolish it except
in the most dire emergency.
While the owners do not feel able to meet the financial burdens
involved in complying with the repair notice, they are willing to
negotiate its sale to a responsible third party.
Since discussions are taking place with the Glasgow Building
Preservation Trust with a view to the trust undertaking the required
works, the council's sub-committee on building control has extended the
repairs notice for six months.
Local councillor Bailie Alex Mosson said: ''We decided on a six-month
stay of execution for the repairs notice. That will allow the planning
department, in conjunction with the Glasgow Preservation Society, to
bring forward a financial package which will be used to repair the
property and deal with the outstanding defects, which are running at
more than #1m.
''It's one of the most prestigious buildings in the city. It's unique
in Scotland and nobody would like to see it demolished.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
