<HEADLINE>Aid agency to abandon 'killers' in Hutu camps</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Amsterdam
THE Dutch arm of the aid group Medecins sans Frontieres (Doctors
Without Borders) said today it would pull workers out of two camps for
Rwandan refugees because it believes they are being used as shelters by
the perpetrators of genocide.
Mr Jacques de Milliano, director of the Dutch section of MSF said nine
members would be withdrawn from Katale camp near Goma in Zaire while 13
would be pulled out from Ngara in Tanzania.
A total of 1500 local MSF workers would also cease operations.
''In refugee camps there are killers walking around making plans for
new attacks. We don't want to be part of that system,'' said de
Milliano.
A million Rwandans, mainly from the Hutu majority, fled to Zaire after
the July 1994 victory of Tutsi-led rebels. Tanzania has more than
700,000 refugees, mainly Hutus.
Many of them fear reprisals for last year's genocide in which
1,000,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were killed.
De Milliano added that eight expatriate members of the Belgian MSF
would also move out of a camp in Goma.
He stressed it would take some time, possibly months, for a controlled
withdrawal and handover of responsibility to UN refugee authorities.
But he conceded that the MSF had had misgivings about events in the
camps for some time.
Calling for prosecution of those responsible for genocide in Rwandan
camps, de Milliano said: ''The population (in the camps) has become a
kind of prisoner of its own leaders and humanitarian aid is fuelling
these systems of impunity.'' -- Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
