<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kashmir hostage in radio contact. India nears deal after breakthrough</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NELSON GRAVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Srinagar
THE Indian Government spoke directly today to one of the four
Westerners being held by guerrillas in Kashmir, the first such contact
in the eight-week hostage ordeal.
A spokesman for the government of Jammu and Kashmir state said the
radio conversation convinced authorities that Britons Keith Mangan and
Paul Wells, American Donald Hutchings, and German Dirk Hasert were all
unharmed.
''There was contact today,'' a senior police officer said. ''One of
the hostages has spoken to the government.''
An official said it was Hutchings who spoke on the radio but the
information could not be immediately confirmed.
It was hoped the direct contact marked an important step towards
solving the crisis.
Indian officials had demanded that Al-Faran militants holding the
hostages provide firm proof that all four were in good health before
reaching any final agreement.
A fifth hostage, Norwegian Hans Christian Ostroe, was found beheaded
in an isolated region of Kashmir on August 13, beside a note from
Al-Faran threatening to kill the others.
Last week Al-Faran provided photographs and a tape recording
indicating the men were well, but they were apparently dated from August
18.
That was two days before Indian officials and diplomats learned of
another apparent threat to the captives' lives.
The threat was believed to have been quickly dropped, and authorities
said they have since had verbal assurances of the hostages' well-being,
but wanted firmer proof before reaching a final agreement, a senior
official said.
Authorities have been negotiating with Al-Faran through unidentified
intermediaries and have sketched the outlines of a possible agreement in
which the hostages and a number of jailed separatists would be released.
Al-Faran, which was unknown before the abductions, has demanded that
15 militants including at least three members of Pakistan-based
Harkat-ul-Ansar be freed in exchange.
India has ruled out releasing hardcore militants it says would rejoin
a five-year-old separatist revolt in which police and hospitals say at
least 20,000 people have died.
Harkat-ul-Ansar, which along with most Kashmiri separatist groups has
condemned the abductions, denies any ties to Al-Faran.
India has said it will not agree to an open exchange of jailed
militants for the hostages, but has indicated that a certain number of
separatists could be released as part of the government's regular review
of the status of prisoners.
Officials said one of the sticking points that emerged in the talks at
the weekend was the militants' insistence that the jailed
Harkat-ul-Ansar members be released.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
