<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flying in a flap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW POPPLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976650475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANDREW POPPLE offers a cautionary tale for would-be globe trotters
THEY have all but forgotten it now, thank goodness, but one of the
most terrifying moments for our children -- and us, if truth be known --
happened at an airport check-in desk. We were travelling from New
Zealand to Australia, on a Friday afternoon. Not any old Friday, this
was New Year's Day. After a few days in Fremantle, on the West Coast, we
would be heading back home to Scotland, after a Christmas holiday Down
Under.
We got to the airport nice and early. All went swimmingly until the
clerk wanted our passports, to check we had entry visas. We knew the
Australian authorities were strict: no travel without the necessary
documents. The children have New Zealand passports, so they have
automatic right of entry. I had a ''valid duration of passport'' visa
and, therefore, so did my wife -- we had got them at the same time.
Wrong. My visa had been renewed for work reasons; hers had not. It had
timed out.
We were on as-cheap-as-you-can-get, no-changes fare, and the options
as presented to us were: stick together as a family and pay a fortune
for single fares back to the UK, or starting unpacking the bags there
and then to find my wife's things, so she could stay behind until she
could get a visa.
The next day that the consulate would be open was Tuesday --
''probably, but it might be Wednesday, it's a public holiday y'know''.
So there we were, discussing in front of a six and a four-year-old the
prospect of at least four days without Mum, who would have to sit around
for three of those days before she could start to sort it all out.
By now the queue behind us was forming, and we had to make decisions.
An appeal got us to an airline supervisor. Howls of: ''We won't go
without mummy'' helped. To cut a long story short, a series of
trans-Tasman phone calls and telexes got us ''exceptional permission''
to travel and argue the toss with the Australian authorities. With
minutes to spare, we were bundled onto the plane and away we went.
As the plane levelled out we looked at the copy telex we were
carrying: the permission was to go to Sydney; we were on our way to
Perth! Our only course of action was to front up and see what happened.
My wife was by now ready to burst, and my 'little joke' that the worst
they could do is put her in jail did not go down at all well.
Unfortunately our six-year-old heard me and shouted, horrified, for all
the plane to hear: ''Mummy's not going to prison, is she?'' It's a great
conversation stopper.
In the arrivals hall I knew we had been found out. The Tannoy was
calling rather insistently for me to go to information. I was handed an
official-looking envelope. In it was a note: re your hire car, its the
third on the left in the car park, the keys are under the mat.
Farce seemed to turn to tragedy as we hit immigration. The desk clerk
called across the immigration supervisor. This person had obviously had
no fun at all this New Year's Day and now saw her opportunity. My wife
was escorted, by armed heavies, to an interrogation room and we, the
rest of the family, were ushered away to wait in the main lobby. It was
late, and everything was closed. Even the toilets were being cleaned.
The children were tired, hungry, and worried and so was I.
Over an hour later, all had been resolved, and we were all allowed to
stay. Not without some hard negotiating, I gather. Rules are rules and
the fault was ours -- mine. But my wife's passport shows her title as
Doctor, and we had onward flights, credit cards and screaming kids. Not
the stuff of illegal immigrants, surely. However, her passport is now
stamped on every page with words to the effect ''tried it once, never
try it again''.
Aussie hospitality and weather soon banished those events to
pre-history. The children no longer cling to Mum as we front up at
airports, but I won't book so much as a fairground ride without checking
with her first.
So remember, everyone -- including the little one who wasn't with you
last year -- needs all the right travel documents, and if you make
assumptions, like me, you risk some uneasy moments and plenty of grey
hair. But the keys really were under the mat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UN admits failure in refugee crisis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nairobi
THE UN refugee agency today
admitted defeat after failing to get Rwandan refugees in Zaire to go
home voluntarily, raising the possibility that Zaire could resume
forcing them over the border.
Meanwhile, Rwandan Prime Minister Faustin Twagiramungu announced his
resignation as a senior Government official said he had been sacked.
Twagiramungu is a moderate Hutu politician who has been privately
critical of what he called Tutsi hardliners in the army and Government.
He was appointed in July 1994 after Rwanda's bloody civil war.
''The Prime Minister has been sacked,'' said Emmanuel Gasana, an aide
to President Pasteur Bizimungu.
Whatever the circumstances of his departure it is likely to strengthen
the determination of the million Hutu refugees in Zaire to stay put.
Zaire began forcibly expelling Rwandans from their huge camps nine
days ago, but stopped late last week after the UN High Commissioner for
Refugees agreed to restart a voluntary repatriation programme.
But only a few hundred of the vast Hutu refugee population have gone
home.
''It's a flop for very well known reasons,'' said UNHCR spokesman Joel
Boutroue.
''Extremists are still here in the camps and until that problem has
been addressed there will be very little voluntary repatriation.''
The failure of the UN effort presents a problem since Zaire has been
expected to demand ever faster repatriations before promising a
permanent halt to its own expulsions.
Zairian troops forced some 15,000 to return home. Another 173,000 fled
into the countryside, although 70,000 have since returned to the camps.
Zairian officials have become exasperated over the size of the 50-odd
camps, some of which house as many as 200,000 people. They are also
angry at the length of time the refugee crisis has gone on.
A land mine thought to have been planted by Hutu militants trying to
disrupt the departures exploded today, injuring two Zairian workers in a
UNHCR truck.
The land mine exploded as the refugee agency was preparing to take 117
people home. The driver and a passenger were injured as the truck was
leaving the Care Canada base in Goma.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kvaerner optimistic over #65m contract</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at Kvaerner Govan are likely to learn today whether or not the
yard on the Upper Clyde has secured a #65m contract to build a rocket
transporter for the world's first commercial sea-based satellite
launcher.
The Govan yard has been locked in battle with its sister yard in
Germany for the contract to build the transporter for the Sea Launch
programme.
The launch platform will be based in the Pacific Ocean and is expected
to be operational from the beginning of 1998.
Fears had been expressed by union officials at the Upper Clyde yard
that its German counterpart may have an unfair advantage because of a
perceived Government failure to provide adequate financial support.
However, Kvaerner yard convener, Mr David Cooper, said yesterday he
believed the Government's support had been positive, adding: ''We are
optimistic.''
The transporter will carry the rockets from Russia to the platform and
will in itself cost around #66m, although Kvaerner has remained silent
about the overall investment in the programme in which it has a 20%
stake. Other participants include Boeing, Energia of Russia (which makes
the world's biggest rockets), and a Ukrainian space company.
Earlier this month, management of the Norwegian shipbuilding and
engineering giant, which owns the Govan yard, revealed that the yard --
which employs 1300 -- had made a small loss in the past 12 months but
believed that it should break even by the end of this year.
Finance director Jan Magne Heggelund said that while there had been
increasing productivity, the levels were ''not yet acceptable''.
However, he softened the blow by adding that, in a European context,
Govan's productivity was acceptable, although this was not enough to
appease the Kvaerner group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Baseball bat attack on groom</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GROOM was suffering from amnesia last night, unable to remember his
wedding day, after being battered with a baseball bat at the reception.
His bride and the guests had been terrorised by a gang. Her #1000
wedding gown was splattered with Mr Dean Knight's blood as he collapsed
by her side.
Three other guests were injured when the gang of 15 invaded the
reception at the Grove Restaurant at Warsop in Sherwood Forest,
Nottinghamshire, at the weekend.
They were armed with baseball bats, pool cues, and a pistol that fired
ball-bearings. They demanded drinks and went berserk when refused.
The bride, 24-year-old Gillian Knight, was too upset to talk about the
attack. Brother-in-law Darren Knight, 19, said: ''Dean is very ill. He
has completely lost his memory and can't even remember getting married.
I saw them kicking him in the head when he lay on the floor.''
He added: ''One held his pistol at my neck and then put it to my head.
I thought he was going to shoot me dead.''
The bride's brother, Mr Anthony Radford, was also battered with a bat
and needed 27 stitches in a head wound.
Last night, police, who recovered a gun and other weapons, were
interviewing three men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eight years for man who killed his brother</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN who stabbed his brother through the heart was jailed for eight
years yesterday.
John Boyd, 22, plunged the knife four times into his older brother
Stephen, 24, during an argument.
Yesterday, as he was convicted of culpable homicide, it was revealed
that the crime had left him with deep psychological scars. His lawyer,
solicitor advocate Maurice Smyth, told the High Court in Glasgow that
acute post-traumatic stress disorder had been diagnosed by a
psychologist.
Boyd described to the doctor how he suffered nightmares and frequent
flashbacks of the night he killed his brother.
Mr Smyth said: ''The loss of his brother is irreversible,
unforgettable and, indeed, unforgiveable. He has been left with a
scalding, indelible memory of what happened that night.
''There is no respite from the pain or guilt of what he did.
''His position is crystallised in his own words to the police: 'I
didn't mean to do it'.''
Boyd, who was living in a Glasgow hostel at the time of the killing,
was originally charged with murdering Mr Stephen Boyd, of Prospecthill
Circus, Toryglen, Glasgow, in Elmbank Street, also Glasgow, on April 1.
Yesterday, however, the Lord Advocate, Lord Rodger, who was
prosecuting the case, reduced the charge to culpable homicide and Boyd
pleaded guilty.
The judge, Lord Marnoch, was asked to accept that Boyd had been
provoked.
The court heard how the tragedy was witnessed by Boyd's sister Paula
and his brother's girlfriend, Pamela Duke.
The brothers and Ms Duke had been in Glasgow for the night and were en
route to a fast-food restaurant where Paula Boyd worked when they
started to argue.
John Boyd, who had just come out of prison, wanted to go to a disco,
while his brothertold him for his own good not to go and to keep out of
trouble.
He resented being lectured and, when his brother started pointing his
finger and prodding him in the chest, a scuffle broke out and Boyd was
knocked unconscious by a blow to the temple.
When he came to, lying on the pavement with blood streaming from a
head wound, he was shocked to find himself abandoned by his brother.
Mr Smyth then told how Boyd went to the carry-out restaurant where his
sister was a chef, grabbed a knife, and stabbed his brother.
He then ran away in a panic and telephoned his mother in tears to tell
her what he had done. At the time, he didn't know he had killed his
brother.
Sentencing him to eight years, Lord Marnoch accepted he was filled
with remorse and bore in mind the provocation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Algiers hijacker linked to Paris bomb</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Algerian thought to have planned the Christmas hijacking of a
French airliner in Algiers has been identified as a suspect in last
month's bloody bombing of a Paris commuter train, a French newspaper
said today.
The report in Le Monde follows the discovery of a 55lb unexploded bomb
alongside the high-speed TGV railway line near Lyon.
Prime Minister Alain Juppe held a crisis meeting with the Interior and
Justice Ministers over security measures as a judicial probe was opened
into the failed attack.
Investigators said the gas canister bomb packed with nails bore
similarities with bombs used in two recent Paris attacks which killed
seven people and wounded 103.
Le Monde said a second suspect in the July 25 attack on a Paris
commuter train was identified by a witness from a large mole on his face
as an Algerian using the assumed name of Yahia Rihane, also known as
Krounfil -- Algerian slang for a mole.
Algerian secret services had told French police Krounfil organised the
Christmas hijacking and wanted to avenge the killing of the four Islamic
Armed Group (GIA) hijackers by French commandos who stormed the plane in
Marseilles, it said.
A first Algerian suspect for the bombing, Abdelkrim Deneche, is being
held in Sweden. A request for his extradition is pending.
Deneche has denied the charges saying he was in Stockholm at the time.
Sweden's public prosecutor Jan Danielsson said Deneche was still a
suspect in the Paris bombing but denied a report he also was accused of
the Paris killing of a Muslim cleric on July 11.
0 Justice sources said an Algerian Muslim fundamentalist named as
Boualem Guerroudj was sent to prison and was being probed by a
magistrate for forging documents. But there was no indication the arrest
was linked to the bombings.
* A Swiss group firebombed an empty TGV train earlier this month in
protest at France's plans to resume nuclear testing.-- Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Envoy 'was warned of kidnap dangers'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650481</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bogota
A BRITISH diplomat kidnapped in Colombia was bird-watching in a remote
area of the country despite a warning from his embassy of the dangers of
abduction and terrorist attack, officials said today.
Timothy Cowley, a staff sergeant and aide to the British embassy's
military attache, was kidnapped two weeks ago by suspected left-wing
rebels manning a makeshift barricade across a rural road in the Tolima
area southwest of the capital.
Police and military officials have said the 32-year-old diplomat was
on a bird-watching expedition.
British Ambassador Leycester Coltman told journalists today that in
recent weeks ''there was a small change in advice given to travellers''
because of an upsurge in violent activity.
The embassy's latest travel advisory for British citizens in Colombia,
issued about the same time Cowley set out on his trip, stresses that
''travel by air is preferable'' throughout Colombia and that ''road
travel should be by major routes only''.
''Violence and kidnapping have recently increased in Colombia,'' said
the warning. ''In all rural areas in particular there is a serious risk
of being caught up in terrorist attacks and opportunistic kidnapping.''
The advisory, which notes that a British resident had recently been
kidnapped and killed in Colombia, warns that foreigners are ''a tempting
target'' for criminals in Colombia -- including assailants who
specialise in using a voodoo-like powder known as Burundanga to subdue
their intended victims.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
