<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No trial for beauty queen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Miss Lebanon Ghada Turk will not face court martial for posing
in a photograph next to Miss Israel at the 1993 Miss World gala, a
military investigator said today.
The dark-haired beauty was charged last year with breaking laws that
bar contact with Israelis -- an offence punishable under military law by
three to 15 years jail since the two countries are still formally at
war.
However, investigating judge Riad Talee ruled that 22-year-old Miss
Turk will not be tried since she only became aware she was posing next
to Miss Israel Tamara Bourat at the 1993 Johannesburg pageant after the
photograph was taken.
''It did not become evident that the suspect went too far in her
relationship with Miss Israel or had done any deal with her that could
harm Lebanon's security or jeopardise its interests,'' Talee said.
Beirut newspapers last year front-paged the photograph of the two
beauty queens rubbing shoulders and smiling, and indignant captions
demanded an explanation.--Reuter.
0
</TEXT>
