<HEADLINE>Rumbling volcano holds island in suspense</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Salem
ROYAL Marines moved to the area of a rumbling volcano on this island
today to place remote sensing equipment, officials reported.
Scientists monitoring the volcano detected five small earthquakes
under the mountain overnight and five episodes of gas and ash venting.
This tiny British colony was in its sixth day of massive disruption,
with half its population displaced and few signs the situation would
change soon.
''We're in the worst possible scenario now, really,'' said Governor
Frank Savage. ''We've got everyone stuffed in the north end of the
island. We've got to watch sanitary conditions carefully.''
Several days of decreased seismic activity would be needed before the
evacuation order could be lifted, according to the scientific team. But
there were no signs of a let-up in volcanic activity.
Authorities ordered the evacuation of the southern half of the island
last Wednesday when scientists warned that the volatile volcano on
Chances Peak could erupt and said they could not assure six hours'
notice.
The population from the south have now moved to the less populated
north, where they remain crammed in public shelters and the homes of
family and friends. About 3000 people are believed to have left the
island.
The capital, Plymouth, remained closed but people were allowed to
return to their homes on a limited basis to tend animals or retrieve
supplies.
Islanders were relieved by the passage of Tropical Storm Iris, which
brought brisk winds and sporadic heavy rain but caused no damage to this
lush Caribbean island.
''It spared us, thank goodness,'' said Brigitte Lewis, a volunteer at
Radio Montserrat, the government radio station operating from a remote
location in the north of the island.
The island's small airport reopened today after being closed for a day
because of the storm.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
