<HEADLINE>Briton denies child sex link in Philippines</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BRITISH travel agent accused of promoting child prostitution in the
Philippines denied the charge today, saying all he was interested in was
a ''safe family holiday''.
Michael Clarke, 48, from Eastbourne, Sussex, pleaded not guilty at a
preliminary hearing at a court in the town of Olongapo, north of Manila.
He is charged with trying to ''promote, facilitate child prostitution
by advertising sex tours'', according to court documents.
The law under which he was charged carries a maximum penalty of 40
years in prison.
Clarke, who appeared in the ramshackle court in a pinstripe suit with
a bow tie and red pocket handkerchief, told Judge Leopoldo Calderon he
could not afford either a lawyer or to put up bail.
The judge said he would appoint a lawyer for Clarke and would study an
application for his 40,000 peso (#987) bail to be halved.
Clarke, who has been in detention since June, was escorted into court
by two Immigration Bureau officials.
Asked by reporters before the hearing if he was guilty, Clarke
replied: ''Not guilty, sir, 100 percent. It was a complete set-up. Hook,
line, and sinker, it was a set-up.''
Clarke said he was a businessman and had only been interested in ''a
safe family holiday here''.
''Do I look like a pervert?'' he asked.
Clarke, whose case has been featured in a British current affairs
television programme, earlier claimed he had been set up by a Christian
cult.
Philippine President Fidel Ramos has ordered a crackdown on foreign
paedophile syndicates exploiting Filipino children.
Prostitution is widespread in this south-east Asian nation.
Clarke, who is next due to in court on September 27, told reporters he
had run out of money and was raising funds to buy cigarettes in
detention by cutting hair for 15 pesos (37p) per head.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
