<DOCNO>GH950829-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bombay shelves Rushdie book</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE release of Salman Rushdie's new novel has been put off in Bombay
amid fears that it could enrage the city's powerful Hindu fundamentalist
group.
One of the characters in The Moor's Last Sigh, set in Bombay, is
apparently said to be a caricature of Bal Thackeray, leader of the Shiv
Sena party that is known for using strong-armed tactics in dealing with
its critics.
Rushdie was born in the city.
''The situation in Bombay is volatile. Keeping in mind the controversy
regarding Rushdie's previous book, The Satanic Verses, we've decided to
play safe,'' said a spokesman for the book's Indian distributors.
It was published by Jonathan Cape in Britain and was released in other
Indian cities, including New Delhi, two weeks ago.
Rushdie has been living in hiding since 1989 when Iran's Ayatollah
Khomeni declared The Satanic Verses blasphemous and ordered his
death.--AP
</TEXT>
