<HEADLINE>Overhaul urged for civil justice. Citizens Advice says current set-up is failing to provide modern, reliable court system.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN,LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S system of civil justice is in need of a radical overhaul so
that it can deal with the real problems faced by ordinary people, it was
claimed yesterday.
Citizens Advice Scotland says the present set-up is failing to provide
what the country needs -- a modern, reliable, simple court system.
The shortcomings of civil justice in Scotland will be addressed at the
annual conference of Citizens Advice Scotland, the Scottish association
of Citizens Advice Bureaux, which opens in Aberdeen today.
Among the speakers will be Court of Session Judge, Lord Gill, who
earlier this year called for a comprehensive review of civil justice in
Scotland in which the public must have a proper voice.
The two-day conference -- Citizens and Access to the Law: Truth,
Fairness, and Cost -- also comes against the background of a major
review of civil justice in the Court of Session, Scotland's supreme
civil court, announced by Lord Hope, the Lord President.
That would not affect how civil business is conducted in the sheriff
court.
Citizens Advice Bureaux deal with nearly three quarters of a million
inquiries from the public every year, and CABx say that, increasingly,
their experience is that the civil justice system is unable to cope with
the problems of ordinary people.
The main complaints against the system are its high cost, uncertainty
of the outcome of cases, an over-emphasis on legal argument rather than
realistic solutions, the old-fashioned, intimidating atmosphere of
courts, and long and unreasonable delays.
Mr Martyn Evans, chief executive officer of Citizens Advice Scotland,
said yesterday: ''The CAB services across Scotland see thousands of
people every day -- talking through, addressing, and tackling their
various and often complicated problems.
''We need a modern, reliable, simple court system. I regret to say
that, at the moment, we do not have one.
''I hope our conference can make a contribution to changing our system
for the better by establishing a dialogue between interested parties. We
hope to put the general public's interests and concerns first and
foremost in the civil justice system in Scotland.''
The concerns of Citizens Advice Scotland echo those expressed in a
powerful speech delivered by Lord Gill earlier this year when he
described our system of civil procedure as a ''contemporary relic of a
vanished age which is ill-serving the ligitant''.
Lord Gill argued that the usual piecemeal approach to reform must be
replaced by a comprehensive review of civil justice in which the public
should have a proper voice.
He added: ''The public are entitled to an efficient and well-funded
system of civil justice. Our civil system is to be admired only to the
extent that it serves their needs. The present system is failing the
litigant.
''The priority is the institution of a comprehensive civil justice
review in which every aspect of the status quo is open to question.''
Lord Gill urged the judiciary and legal profession to promote reform
before public dissatisfaction and resentment forced the issue.
Following Lord Gill's speech and similar criticisms by the late Lord
Morton of Shuna, Lord Hope announced a major ''nuts and bolts'' review
of civil procedure in the Court of Session.
He appointed a committee headed by Lord Cullen which will consider
what can be done to simplify procedure and speed up the disposal of
cases.
Lord Hope said: ''I accept that we have real problems in meeting the
demands of civil litigation and the points raised by Lords Morton and
Gill will come into the remit (of Lord Cullen's review).''
It is hoped Lord Cullen's report will be available by the end of the
year.
</TEXT>
