<HEADLINE>Fisherman phones wife for help after winch severs his leg</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FISHERMAN called his wife on his mobile telephone from his boat
yesterday and told her: ''Get help. I think I've lost part of my leg.''
Mr Tom Willacy was shrimping alone near his home town of Annan,
Dumfriesshire, when he got caught in a winch cable.
It severed his right leg below the knee but Mr Willacy, 55, of Solway
Crescent, managed to free himself and reach his mobile telephone on
board his boat, the Patricia Willacy, named after his wife.
She kept the phone connected and ran to a neighbour's house, where she
called the rescue services.
Last night, Mr Willacy was transferred to Glasgow Royal Infirmary for
specialist treatment to his leg.
Efforts to save it failed despite it being taken to hospital in
Dumfries packed in ice from a nearby fish factory.
Coastguard sector officer Tony Wood of Kirkcudbright, who co-ordinated
the rescue, said: ''This is one of the bravest men I have met.
''He managed to cut his clothing free after be became entangled and
his leg was severed. Then he phoned his wife to tell her.
''I have nothing but praise for this incredibly brave man.''
The incident began just before midday when Mr Willacy was fishing
close to shore off Newbie, on his 38ft shrimper. His boat had grounded
as he worked to reverse the winch wire (which lifts the net from the
sea) and, when he stepped back, the winch wire caught round his leg.
Mr Wood explained: ''As he went to see what happened, he was caught by
the wire.
''Whether he passed out or not is unclear but within minutes he had
cut himself free and alerted his wife.''
Silloth lifeboat crossed the Solway from Cumbria and a Sea King
helicopter from Prestwick also attended. A doctor and paramedics were
taken out to the boat and after stabilising Mr Willacy the lifeboat took
him ashore, from where he was flown to Dumfries Infirmary.
A spokesman for Liverpool coastguards, who received the emergency
call, said: ''We were chatting with Mr Willacy. It was amazing how he
kept calm. He was fully aware of everything and directed us to himself.
He told us he thought he had lost part of his leg. I don't know how he
kept going.''
Last night, police were investigating the incident and the Health and
Safety Executive had been informed.
Mr Willacy comes from a fishing family in the Solway port.
A Dumfries Infirmary spokesman said: ''Mr Willacy was assessed when he
arrived but unfortunately we could not save his leg. He was taken to
Glasgow for specialist treatment.'' Mr Willacy was said to be in a
serious but stable condition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
