<DOCNO>GH950829-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warships join American military build-up in Gulf</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EIGHT ships carrying US weapons have arrived in the Gulf and more are
heading to the waterway as part of an American military build-up in the
region following fresh tension over Iraq, a US navy official said today.
American tanks and armoured vehicles on manoeuvres in Kuwait will hold
their first live fire exercise in the desert on Wednesday, US army
officers said.
''We currently have eight of the ships in the Gulf,'' said Commander T
McCreary, spokesman of the US Fifth fleet, adding that they were all in
international waters. ''Some more are coming.'' The United States has
also brought forward joint exercises with Kuwait as a precaution after
observing what it called unusual Iraqi military activity in Baghdad and
southern Iraq.
US military activity in the region has also increased since Jordan
gave asylum to two senior Iraqi defectors, one of whom called for the
overthrow of Iraq's President Saddam Hussein.
The ships carry tanks, artillery, food, fuel, water, vehicles and
other equipment required to sustain 16,500 marines in combat for 30
days, a US military spoksman has said.
In addition, they carry enough gear to sustain 5000 to 7000 US Army
troops, said McCreary.
Saddam said today that the United States had no justification in
rushing troops to the Gulf region.
''There is no credibility behind the US massing military vessels in
the Gulf and the Mediterranean . . . under the false pretext that Iraq
plans to invade Jordan, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia,'' Saddam said, quoted
by the Iraqi News Agency.
Jordan's King Hussein and US officials said after the defection to
Amman of two senior Iraqis -- both sons-in-law of Saddam -- that the
Iraqi leader had been planning to invade Kuwait and Saudi Arabia this
month.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
