<HEADLINE>Osprey wave project to rise again</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS Osprey, the world's first offshore wave-power station, was breaking
up beneath the waters of the Pentland Firth yesterday, its developer
talked with confidence about the future of the project, even welcoming
the delay that Sunday's sinking now affords his company.
Mr Allan Thomson, managing director of the Inverness-based Applied
Research and Technology, which built the Osprey, said it had been
insured in Lloyd's Marine Market and his company would begin building
Osprey Two as soon as possible. He thought the ballast tanks on the #4m
Osprey may have been damaged during its launch at UIE's Clydebank yard
at the beginning of the month.
''Obviously, this is a disappointment for us but it certainly isn't
the end of the project. Identifying and solving problems is, after all,
the function of development engineers. It is at times like this you
realise that your insurance premiums were well spent,'' he said.
Osprey One had taken six months to build and Osprey Two could be in
the water by next spring. This would mean a delay of only a few months
to the originally intended National Grid connection, provisionally set
for late autumn. It would again be sited off Dounreay.
He said that, even after only a couple of weeks in the water, ART had
been encouraged by early indications that Osprey would out perform even
their most optimistic predictions.
Mr Thomson also said there had been world-wide inquiries about Osprey
both as an electricity generator and as a desalination plant, her
alternative use. He said that, ironically, the delay of a few months
would allow ART time to deal with these new contacts.
Meanwhile, the UIE yard at Clydebank was yesterday diverting all
inquiries on the Osprey to ART.
</TEXT>
