<HEADLINE>'Even a brother could not recognise his brother because people were ripped apart' -- policeman. Carnage at the market place.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KURT SCHORK reports on the terrible scenes that followed the bombing
of Trznica covered market in Sarajevo
BOSNIA'S besieged capital was once again a scene of carnage today
after at least two shells slammed into the city centre, leaving dozens
dead and injured and severed limbs, brains, and shattered glass strewn
in pools of blood.
By day's end 37 people had died from their injuries and at least 85
lay wounded in Sarajevo's hospitals, many of them in grave condition.
One shell landed at the entrance to a busy covered market on main
street and the other near the National Theatre a few blocks away. Only
about 10 of the casualties were from the second shell, doctors said.
Later in the day another shell hit Sarajevo's Kosevo main hospital,
wounding two patients.
''Killers, bastards, they all deserve to be slaughtered,'' screamed a
woman covered in blood outside the market a few minutes after the blast.
Bosnian state radio blamed separatist Serb gunners who have laid siege
to the city since April 1992 for the attacks. The Serbs accused the
government of targeting its own people.
UN officials said most of the firing positions in the area where the
most deadly mortar bomb came from were Serb.
Dead and dying lay sprawled outside the covered Trznica market, where
the more lethal shell struck. Today's massacre occurred less than 100yd
from the open market where a shell killed 68 people and wounded 200
others in February last year.
Bodies were draped where they fell over steel railings separating
pedestrians from vehicles on Titova street.
Passers-by helped the wounded into private vehicles and drove them to
hospital with horns blaring and lights flashing to clear the way.
''Mummy, I've lost my hand, I've lost my hand,'' said a little girl
cradled in her mother's arms in the back of a reporter's car pressed
into service as an ambulance.
The girl clutched a blood-soaked blanket as her mother, missing an eye
from the blast, moaned: ''Where's my husband, I've lost my husband . . .
''
The surge of casualties swamped Kosevo Hospital, where doctors and
nurses treated wounded in the driveway once the trauma clinic had filled
to capacity.
A single smear of blood ran the length of the Trznica market from
front to rear where a wounded person had been dragged from the shell's
point of impact to safety. Yolks from eggs shattered by the blast oozed
across market counter-tops.
Outside, a human hand lay on the sidewalk among blood-spattered
packets of cigarettes vendors had been hawking. Shoes, bags of fruit,
ripped clothing, and bits of flesh were scattered everywhere.
A motorcycle lay in the centre of the street where its rider had been
struck down and blood flowed in rivulets along the asphalt channels of
the steel trolley rails.
Friends and relatives wailed in grief and some fainted when the list
of the dead was posted outside the Kosevo morgue and hospital in the
early afternoon.
As night fell on the city a single body remained unidentified and
morgue attendants escorted a few reluctant survivors into the building
to try to put a name to the victim.
Today's attack occurred just hours before Bosnian President Alija
Izetbegovic was due to meet US Assistant Secretary of State Richard
Holbrooke in Paris to talk peace.
''Every time there are peace talks Sarajevo pays the price and our
people are slaughtered,'' said a Bosnian Army soldier.
''The moment the shell landed was chaos and you couldn't recognise
anybody -- even a brother couldn't recognise his brother because people
were ripped apart,'' said Rasim, a policeman who normally stands outside
the Trznica market.
''I would have been dead but a colleague had just called me away when
the shell landed.''
Government-held Sarajevo has been surrounded by separatist Serbs
throughout the 40-month Bosnian war in which more than 10,500 city
residents have been killed and 50,000 wounded.
Serb officials have often charged that some massacres in Sarajevo have
been the result of government forces firing on their own population to
evoke international sympathy, but no such charge has ever been proved.
ZAGREB: Television footage recently filmed by the United Nations in
southern Croatia shows a Serb village in flames and two Serb civilians
slain in their homes.
Three weeks after the Croatian government army crushed the Serb
insurgence in Krajina, deserted Serb houses are still burning near Knin,
once the rebel stronghold in southern Croatia.
Depicting what officials called a fierce attack on a hamlet and its
civilians, the UN film showed one of the male victims shot from close
range through the head besides his bed and the other with his throat
slashed.
The Croatian army, which admits carrying out ''mopping-up operations''
in the village, is accused by the UN of systematically torching
homes.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
