<HEADLINE>Government timetable 'seems short'. Danger fears over nuclear privatisation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT Ministers were accused yesterday of a ''dangerous rush
towards nuclear privatisation'' after a senior member of the industry's
leading safety watchdog body admitted that the timescale allowed for the
exercise ''seems short''.
The attack, by Labour's trade and industry spokesman, Mr Brian Wilson,
was made in response to an article in next month's issue of Nuclear
Engineering International by Mr Mike Weightman, HM superintending
inspector of the Nuclear Installations Inspectorate, who also warned
that the proposed changes ''could fundamentally affect the necessary
basis for operating nuclear power stations safely''.
Mr Weightman's comments came as the Government's privatisation plans
for the industry next year, involving a proposed merger of sorts between
Scottish Nuclear and the English-based Nuclear Electric, gathered pace.
In his article, Mr Weightman warned of many safety-related
implications both at a corporate and site level and added that the
decision to split the ownership of some nuclear sites would lead to
particular complications.
''To a lesser or greater degree, all such sites share some
safety-related services and facilities,'' he wrote.
''Hence the licensee will have to make submissions to NII to justify
that any changes proposed, and the way in which they are to be made, do
not compromise the current high standards of safety.''
Mr Weightman also pointed out that there may be a need for changes in
safety or management arrangements which would include the provision of
emergency responses because all sites currently owned by Scottish
Nuclear and Nuclear Electric would require to be relicensed under new
ownership.
He argued that where central resources such as expert technical
back-up were being split between the publicly-owned Magnox and the new
privatised company, the change would have to be demonstrated to be in
the best interests of safety. He added that the NII would inspect and
assess the measures to confirm that safety was not impeded.
Referring specifically to Hunterston nuclear power station in Ayrshire
-- a shut-down Magnox station which is to be transferred to the new
Magnox company -- he said a change would necessitate a revision of
management arrangements and require additional training of personnel.
Mr Weightman added that safety-related implications about the way the
new companies would be set up also existed -- such as the relationship
of the subsidiary companies, who will be the licensees, to the holding
company.
A statutory three-month period of public consultation would be
appropriate for all sites.
He concluded: ''Only after all this work has been completed
satisfactorily will NII inspectors be able to advise the chief inspector
that new licences can be signed. Around a year to 15 months seems a
short time.''
Mr Wilson said it was ''scandalous'' that the NII was up against a
''politically-driven timetable'' when dealing with such ''life-and-death
issues''.
''What happens if, in six or 12 months' time, they conclude that they
cannot complete the task in time?'' the Labour MP for Cunninghame North
asked.
''Mr Weightman says that any changes will require to be proven to be
in the best interests of safety. How can splitting ownership and
responsibility of a nuclear site meet that test? How can introducing the
motive of private profit make a nuclear site safer?
''Will Ministers, whose sole interest is in rushing this privatisation
through in order to fund tax cuts, even allow them that option?''
Mr Wilson said he had written to Mr Ian Lang, the President of the
Board of Trade, asking him to make clear, in light of Mr Weightman's
comments, that the NII could follow its own timetable without political
pressure.
Mr Richard Killick, Scottish Nuclear's director of safety and quality,
said Mr Weightman's article illustrated the ''right and proper'' degree
of detail and care which is taken by the NII in licensing nuclear sites
and said the public could rest assured by this.
He said Scottish Nuclear would maintain its high safety standards and
would co-operate fully with the NII during the preparations for
privatisation of the UK nuclear industry, to ensure that the appropriate
licensing of its sites was carried out to the standards required under
the health and safety legislation.
Mr Killick added: ''It has already been announced that the Government
intends to privatise much of the nuclear industry next year and Scottish
Nuclear and its sister company in England and Wales will be working
towards that target.''
Scottish Nuclear also confirmed that the overall re-licensing
operation was on schedule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fringe boxes a record</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR the first time in its 49-year history, Edinburgh Festival Fringe
has sold more than #1m worth of tickets through its box office.
With the figures -- a 10% rise over last year -- taking no account of
takings at the venues, Fringe staff calculators are working overtime --
and there are still some days to go.
The sales represent only around 30% of all tickets sold.
Meanwhile, the Book Festival, which ended yesterday, was also setting
records. Around 13,000 more people attended it compared with the
previous event in 1993.
A 27% rise in ticket sales was reported, 13% more books were sold,
and, of the 210 ticketed events, 113 were a sell-out.
Fringe director Hilary Strong said they were all delighted with the
news that the #1m mark -- more than 163,000 tickets sold -- had been
surpassed.
''Our mission this year was to make the Fringe more accessible,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour pledges arts review</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHADOW Scottish Secretary George Robertson yesterday promised a major
review of arts policy and funding in Scotland if Labour wins the next
election.
He said a Scottish Parliament would assume responsibility for the
arts, marking the end of decisions taken behind closed doors in
Whitehall or St Andrew's House.
''We see a clear need for greater openness in all our Scottish arts
and cultural quangos and for a much more visible accountability of their
members.
''Clearly a review of how the Scottish arts are financed will be
essential. The new powers of the Scottish Office in relation to the Arts
Council, the funding of the four 'national' companies, and the pivotal
role of local government expenditure has to be examined to see if the
system is working,'' he told the annual meeting of the Scottish Arts
Lobby (Salvo).
Mr Robertson praised the work of Labour councils in keeping the arts
alive. This contrasted with Tory mismanagement, he said.
Labour would reform the distribution of National Lottery funds and
ensure that small schemes were not ignored at the expense of large,
prestigious projects.
Mr Robertson said there was also a need to examine broadcasting's role
in Scotland's cultural identity and London domination of BBC
programming. The successful legal challenge to the Panorama programme on
the eve of the April local elections had proved a watershed in changing
the attitude of the BBC hierarchy to Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Speyside quake is no great shakes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE earth moved for the people in the Spey Valley yesterday when the
popular tourist area experienced its first earthquake.
The event measured 2.7 on the Richter Scale and happened just before
11am, lasting three seconds.
The sophisticated monitoring equipment of the British Geological
Survey in Edinburgh pinpointed the tremor at Avielochan, three
kilometres from Aviemore.
The depth of the quake was about 9km and it was strong enough only to
cause some vibration in buildings and shake glasses in the local bars.
However, it also shook the local population, with police at Aviemore
inundated with calls. A spokesman said: ''I can't recall an earthquake
in Aviemore before. One of our constables was one of the first to report
it, as he was out on the beat and felt the earth tremble.
''Another report was from a golfer on the Boat of Garten course. He
thought a lorry had hit the clubhouse.''
Geological survey spokeswoman Ms Jan Richards said: ''We are checking
our records to determine when the last quake occurred in this area, or
indeed if this is the first. It is certainly not a location associated
with earthquakes.
''It is difficult to determine the cause and if there will be another.
But it has nothing to do with the Montserrat volcano eruption. It is too
far away.
''Sometimes there is a build-up of pressure on the earth's crust and
it has to be let out somewhere. In Britain, it is difficult to exactly
locate geological faults but we are not aware of one in the Aviemore
area.
''It is some distance south from the Highland fault, which stretches
the length of the Great Glen from west coast to east.
''This tremor could be a new fault being created. It is unlikely there
will be any after-shocks of any strength, although a weak tremor can be
followed by a strong one, although this is extremely rare.''
The strongest earthquake in the Highlands was in 1816, measuring 5.1
on the Richter Scale. It caused considerable damage in the Inverness
area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skye bridge inquiry claim. Storm over wind speed 'cover-up'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS,HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office withheld information which was unhelpful to its
case at the Skye bridge public inquiry, it was claimed yesterday.
The Skye Bridge Appeal Group says this mirrors its behaviour over the
M8 extension, which the Parliamentary Ombudsman found last week was
''significant maladministration''.
The information related to how strong winds might affect traffic on
the bridge. Ross, Cromarty, and Skye MP Charles Kennedy said last night
he would raise the matter with the Parliamentary Ombudsman as a matter
of urgency in light of the parallels with the M8 inquiry.
The appeal group, which is the umbrella organisation for opposition to
the bridge, claims that at the public inquiry in Kyle of Lochalsh in
January and February, 1992, Scottish Office officials gave repeated
assurances that the bridge would never be closed due to bad weather.
These assurances had been based on a report on winds at Kyle of
Lochalsh between April and December 1990.
A more up-to-date report, dated August 1991 and based on a 12-month
wind analysis from April 10, 1990, to April 14, 1991, was available,
however. It had been prepared for the Meteorological Office in Edinburgh
for the Glasgow-based JMP Consultants, which was advising bridge
builders Miller/Dywidag.
Mrs Pam Noble, secretary of the appeal group, said yesterday: ''We
have now got a copy of this report and it shows quite clearly that
bridge traffic flow could be impeded by strong winds gusting up to 129
mph. This could affect traffic for about 15% of the month of January,
down to 1.2% in July.
''The Scottish Office must now tell us why this information was not
made available to the public inquiry, given that they and JMP
Consultants had access to it.''
Mrs Kathleen MacRae, appeal group treasurer, said: ''All the report
does is to confirm what islanders have been saying until they are blue
in the face, that at times they may have to close the bridge because of
the dangers from wind gusts.
''But obviously we noticed the Ombudsman's comments on the M8
extension last week and the Scottish Office's role there, so we will be
taking this further.''
Mr Kennedy said last night that it appeared to him that there is a
striking similarity between the withholding of up-to-date, unhelpful
information to the M8 inquiry and the holding back of similar material
to the Skye Bridge inquiry.
''If last week's ruling has established a precedent, then surely it is
one that would have to be applied in this case as well,'' he said.
A Scottish Office spokesman last night accepted that the updated
report had been available at the time and added: ''But there was
absolutely no intention of withholding this from the public inquiry. If
we had been asked about it, it would have been produced.''
He said it had been commissioned principally to establish the
applicability of a nationally-used technical memorandum on wind loading
and whether the bridge design accorded with it. It also allowed an
assessment to be made of the bridge operator's proposals for dealing
with high-sided vehicles in stormy weather.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tax relief 'will not bridge equity gap'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESTORING mortgage tax relief will not allay the problems of home
owners whose mortgage debts are greater than the value of their houses,
a Joseph Rowntree Foundation report warned yesterday.
It says that a U-turn by the Government over recent cuts in tax relief
(Miras) as a way of helping owners, especially in the South of England,
faced with negative equity would have an inflationary effect on house
prices and create heavy pressure for interest rates to rise. It would
also cost the Exchequer #2000m to implement.
The Tory grassroots have called for the restoration of Miras to its
former level of 25% as a way of winning back disillusioned middle-class
support.
But the report by Mr Steve Wilcox of the University of Wales in
Cardiff urges the Government instead to consider a package of targeted
help for the housing market.
This would include the introduction of a mortgage benefit for home
owners on low incomes and the suspension of plans to restrict Income
Support payments to unemployed mortgage holders from October.
Mr Wilcox said negative equity remained a genuine problem for a small
but significant minority of home owners. An estimated one million were
affected but they represented just 7% of all home buyers.
Far from restoring mortgage tax relief, the fundamental case for its
complete abolition remains, the report argues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BBC is to pay for family's trip to K2</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE BBC is to pay for a pilgrimage to K2 by the husband and children
of British climber Alison Hargreaves, who died on the mountain earlier
this month, and will make a documentary of the journey.
A television crew will accompany author and mountain photographer Jim
Ballard, 48, and their children Tom, six, and Kate, four, on a
10,000-mile round trip to the 28,250ft high peak in Pakistan's Karakorum
range in mid-September.
It was also announced yesterday that two trust funds are to be set up
in the climber's memory.
Ms Hargreaves, 33, was one of seven climbers swept to their deaths in
a ferocious storm on August 13 as she descended from the summit.
In May, she had scaled Mount Everest solo without oxygen.
The financial future of her children will be secured by the Tom and
Kate Ballard Trust, in response to interest and offers from around the
world.
Mr Ballard and accountants and lawyers representing the Nevis Range
ski centre -- where he works and where Ms Hargreaves trained for her
climbing -- are looking at the best way to set up the trust.
The Alison Jane Hargreaves Foundation also will be set up to provide
funds to help women's projects.
Mr Ballard is also to complete a series of books while Ms Hargreaves's
diary, continued on an almost daily basis until her death on K2, will be
published.
He will write an account of Ms Hargreaves's last trip called One and
Two Halves to K2 to accompany the TV programme, and a biography of his
wife, entitled Alison.
Last night Sue Affleck, of the BBC's Documentaries Department in
London, said: ''It is true that we have agreed to produce a documentary
of the Ballard family's memorial trek to K2.''
She confirmed that this would involve Mr Ballard and the children
visiting the mountain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hunger striker moved to hospital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN HOME AFFAIRS CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650498</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Glasgow ice cream war murderer, Thomas ''TC'' Campbell, yesterday
was moved out of Shotts Prison for a second time after concern by
medical staff about his poor physical condition. Campbell has undergone
a lengthy period of partial hunger strike, protesting innocence.
Campbell's wife and sister said yesterday they had been told the news
by Campbell but had confirmed it from prison authorities and that
Campbell himself had told them he expected to be in Law Hospital,
Carluke, for two days.
Campbell, convicted in 1984 of the murder of six members of the Doyle
family whose home was set on fire in Ruchazie, Glasgow, during the
battle over control of ice cream van rounds, has been taking liquid
sustenance in the jail.
He has always maintained that his conviction depended on perjured
evidence by witness William Love, who has since repeatedly recanted,
saying that he was coerced into giving the vital statement incriminating
Campbell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Adams, Bruton in new call for talks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650499</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINN Fein and the Irish Government last night repeated calls for
all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland in the face of
continued British demands for prior moves towards the decommissioning of
IRA arms.
After a longer-than-expected review of the Ulster peace process in
Dublin, a joint statement from Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams and Irish
Prime Minister John Bruton said inclusive talks should go ahead in which
all parties negotiated and made the compromises necessary to achieve an
agreed political settlement.
Neither the statement nor Irish Government spokesmen afterwards made
any reference to the continuing wrangling over the future of the IRA
arsenal.
However, a less reticent Mr Adams declared the arms issue position
adopted by Britain, ''calling on the IRA in effect to actually surrender
its weapons, is a non-runner''.
He added: ''We need to move the entire process forward, to bring about
change, to encourage those with weapons to build their confidence so
that all of the guns can be taken out of Irish politics.
''Making that a pre-condition, making that an obstacle to progress, is
a formula for disaster. We want to avoid that disaster.''
Mr Adams, who headed a Sinn Fein delegation of three, said the meeting
with Mr Bruton and fellow Ministers Dick Spring and Proinsias De Rossa,
the other party leaders in Dublin's coalition Government, had been
positive.
It came after a weekend of intensifying rowing over the arms issue,
and ''differences'' between London and Dublin that seem likely to lead
to a postponement of a summit early next month between Mr John Major and
Mr Bruton.
That meeting now looks certain to be delayed until later in September,
allowing time for the remaining UK-Irish differences to be ironed out
ahead of the prime ministerial get-together.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ringo's daughter has brain surgery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650500</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE daughter of Ringo Starr was recovering from brain surgery last
night after being taken to hospital with an unidentified infection.
According to reports, Miss Lee Starkey, 24, who uses the former
Beatle's real surname, is in the #700-a-night London Clinic after
spending 36 hours recovering from the operation during which fluid was
drained from her brain.
The 55-year-old drummer cancelled an American tour to be at his
daughter's side. He was told she was well enough to leave the intensive
care unit and return to a ward.
She entered the clinic last Friday and was operated on almost at once.
She is expected to leave hospital later this week.
Miss Starkey, whose mother Maureen died earlier this year from
leukemia, ran a boutique in Los Angeles. Earlier, she worked in a record
shop and also attended drama school.
Starr spent hours at his daughter's bedside with his second wife, the
actress and former Bond girl Barbara Bach. His son Zak was also there.
Starr said: ''Lee is now on the ward and she is up and about. She is
not running about and she should be out by Saturday.
''She had been feeling unwell and the next thing we knew she was in
here. I came as soon as I heard. Lee had the operation on Friday and is
now up and about.
''We still don't know why it happened but we know it's not meningitis.
She's really brilliant today and will be coming out soon.''
The millionaire drummer lost #50,000 by cancelling his tour but said:
''Family is more important, isn't it? We are going to stay here until
she is better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sunnier outlook for tourism as number of visitors rises</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOURISTS from all over the world have been coming to Scotland in
greater numbers this year, after a depressing period over the last few
years.
Speaking on the eve of a tourist industry conference in Pitlochry,
hosted by the Scottish Tourist Board, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
said the early-season results were the best for five years and had given
tourism a considerable boost.
The number of tourists from January to May had shown a 16% increase in
bed nights, an 18% increase in trips, and a 14% increase in visitor
spending compared with the same period last year.
Mr Forsyth added that the rise in overseas visitors appeared to be
continuing. There was an overall increase of 11% of tourists to Britain
between January and April, with Scotland thought to have benefited
significantly.
The figures are in sharp contrast to an official report on the tourist
industry in Scotland last year, when consultants reported that tourism
figures had fallen by 15% over the previous five years.
It recommended a review of strategy, pointing out that many visitors
were reluctant to venture into the country's more remote areas, such as
the Highlands and islands.
Recently, however, events like the Tall Ships' Race from Leith and the
Edinburgh Festival and Tattoo -- along with major films made in Scotland
-- are thought to have helped reverse the trend.
Other factors include the promotion of Scotland's cuisine and produce,
and the Autumn Gold initiative, designed to extend the tourist season.
Next year, one of the major events will the Burns bicentenary.
Mr Forsyth last night: ''Clearly, there is some way to go before we
can draw firm conclusions about the 1995 season but this is a step in
the right direction.''
Mr Ian Grant, chairman of the Scottish Tourist Board, said he was
encouraged by the figures but would prefer to study them over a
nine-month period before being able to declare whether 1995 had been a
bumper year.
He added: ''We have been helped by the good summer but there have been
pockets which have not been so good. Exhibitions such as Deep Sea World
at North Queensferry, for example, have not been helped by the good
weather conditions which may have kept the number of visitors away.''
Nevertheless, he felt the figures would be followed by more good news.
''We would like to think that visitors to Scotland this year
encountered good hospitality, good food, and will continue to return in
the future,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BB officer earns highest honour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BOYS' Brigade staff sergeant from Stornoway will become the most
decorated member of the brigade in the UK this weekend.
Sgt Craig Macmillan, 18, of the 2nd Stornoway company, attached to
Martin's Memorial Church, holds every proficiency award available in the
BB and the President's Badge and Queen's Badge. He also holds the Duke
of Edinburgh Awards at bronze, silver, and gold level.
Mr Macmillan, who lives at Aird Tong, Lewis, will receive his King
George VI Memorial Certificate at the National Brigade Council meeting
at Eden Court in Inverness on Friday, when he will also be promoted to
lieutenant.
His family has 80 years' service in the BB and three years ago his
brother Iainwas the most decorated BB member in the UK.
His father, Mr Colin Macmillan, is captain of the 2nd Stornoway
company while his mother, Margaret, is officer in charge of its junior
section. His brother Iain is now with the 48th company in Aberdeen and
his younger brother Richard is also holder of Queen's Badge and the Duke
of Edinburgh bronze and silver awards.
Mr Craig Macmillan has been accepted as a medical student at Glasgow
University and hopes to continue his BB work in the city with the lst
Glasgow BB company.
Another member of the 2nd Stornoway company, Staff Sergeant Jonathan
Watt from Newmarket, an apprentice plumber, will also receive his King
George VI certificate this weekend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Christianity 'facing decline in Europe'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR church leader said yesterday that Christianity throughout the
world was growing more rapidly than at any time in its 2000-year history
-- but declining in Europe.
The assertion was made by Bishop Lesslie Newbigin of the United
Reformed Church, a former bishop of the Church of South India.
He was making one of the keynote speeches at the European Area Council
of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches in Edinburgh.
Delegates including the president of the alliance, Professor Jane
Dempsey Douglass, a theologian at Princeton University in the US, were
welcomed at the first of a number of workshops by Scottish Office
Minister, Lord James Douglas-Hamilton.
The bishop said that, in statistical terms, Christianity is now
primarily an African religion, claiming that in Europe, so long its
heartland, it is in decline.
His theory was that the type of consumer society developed in affluent
parts of the world in the last 50 years were being replicated in areas
previously untouched by it.
He said: ''While Europe still plays a significant part in the global
economy, it is now clear that, within a few decades, Europe will be a
very minor player, and the rules will be set by the newly emerging giant
economies of East Asia -- especially China.''
He emphasised that the gap between rich and poor would grow wider,
with the moral guidance traditionally provided by religion,
progressively lost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pull-out leaves bid for Thistle in disarray</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650504</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MP George Galloway's attempt to lead a consortium to take over
Partick Thistle Football Club was in disarray last night after leading
Asian businessmen told the MP they were pulling out of the deal because
of the way it had been handled.
Mr Galloway and newspaper columnist Ron McKay, who had been the public
voices of a supposed consortium of Asian business leaders willing to buy
the club, held a news conference yesterday to announce they themselves
were leaving the consortium.
What they did not explain however, as The Herald has since learned, is
that millionaire businessman Charan Gill already had told Mr Galloway
that he wanted nothing else to do with the consortium. The same message
was conveyed by Mr Maq Rasul, managing director of Global Video, who
also wanted to dissociate himself from any bid.
Mr Gill, owner of a string of restaurants, public houses, and a food
factory in the West of Scotland, disclosed that his involvement was
based only on a short phone call with Mr Galloway when he was told that
Partick Thistle was up for sale, and asked whether he was interested.
Mr Gill said yesterday that he pulled out when he realised that this
was not the case and that the board of Thistle did not want to sell. He
also expressed his disappointment at the public way business was being
done and said it was not the way that business is properly conducted.
''The whole situation has been handled in an improper manner,'' he
said yesterday. ''The whole thing has been blown out of all
proportion.''
Global Video stated that its board decided on Sunday not to continue
its interest in buying shares in Partick Thistle as it wanted to
concentrate its energies on expanding its core business into England.
Mr Galloway insisted yesterday that there was still a consortium of
Asian businessmen interested and he hoped that a bid would be made soon.
He refused to say, however, who was in the consortium or how much they
would offer for Partick Thistle.
He said he and Mr McKay were pulling out of the consortium as it was
clear that Mr Jim Oliver, chairman and major shareholder of Thistle,
would not do business with them.
He concentrated instead on his ''deep resentment'' of comments made by
Thistle chairman Jim Oliver, on the club's telephone newsline, when Mr
Oliver stated: ''If anyone out there thinks we are going to give away
the company for which we have worked very hard over the past few years
and incurred huge personal losses, just to satisfy the wishes of some
Indian with a curry shop, they better think again.''
It was Mr Oliver's remarks, he claimed, which were making some of the
consortium have second thoughts about becoming involved in Scottish
football.
Mr Gill said: ''I am very surprised at a man of Mr Oliver's position
making a comment like that.''
Mr Oliver, in an exclusive interview with The Herald, is adamant that
the club is not for sale. As yet, no-one has put a penny on the table to
buy it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Race on for new Ulster leader</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUSSELL EDMUNDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650505</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Belfast
FOUR MPs are emerging as the major contenders to take over the
leadership of the Ulster Unionist Party from Mr James Molyneaux, who
resigned yesterday.
As tributes were paid to Mr Molyneaux, 75, in London, Dublin, and
Belfast, it appeared that his successor will be chosen in the next few
weeks.
The resignation of the Unionist leader came as a surprise to Northern
Ireland, even though he had come under pressure to step down in the past
year.
The Prime Minister, who consulted Mr Molyneaux during the course of
the peace process but did not always take his advice, said: ''Jim
Molyneaux has been a forthright and brave leader of opinion in Northern
Ireland for very many years.''
Mr John Major added: ''Few people have made such a great
contribution.''
However, Democratic Unionist leader Mr Ian Paisley said the
resignation was ''inevitable'' and described Mr Molyneaux's trust in Mr
Major as ''catastrophic'', although he added that his relationship with
Mr Molyneaux had been ''very good, frank, and honest''.
About 900 delegates of the Ulster Unionist Party, including 100
representing the Orange Order, will be invited to choose the next
leader, who is almost certain to be one of the party's Westminster MPs
The main contenders are security spokesman Mr Ken Maginnis, 57, the
party's Chief Whip Mr William Ross, 59, Orange Order leader the Rev
Martin Smyth, 64, and former Stormont Government Minister Mr John
Taylor, 57.
Mr Ross, a traditional Unionist from the same mould as the outgoing
leader, has long been regarded as the favourite. He is the MP for East
Londonderry and a confidant of Mr Molyneaux's. However, recently, his
low profile appears to have lost him ground.
Mr Maginnis called yesterday for a swift leadership decision to enable
the political process to continue in the wake of the terrorist
ceasefires last year. Mr Maginnis is noted for his trenchant criticism
of the IRA and Sinn Fein but also as one of the few Unionist spokesmen
who has been involved in tentative talks with Irish leaders in Dublin.
Mr Smyth's strength will centre on his position as Grand Master of the
Orange Order while Mr Taylor is one of the party's most articulate
spokesmen with an involvement in Unionism dating back to his student
days.
No clear favourite has emerged so far and one outsider may still be
the Armagh MP David Trimble, who has impressed Unionists in recent
months with his television performances.
The resignation of Mr Molyneaux is certain to cause an intense
internal battle in the Unionist Party.
Not only does the party leader have a crucial role in the current
peace process but, with the Government's narrow majority at Westminster,
he could command much wider influence as Mr Molyneaux has attempted to
do with Mr Major in recent years.
Labour leader Mr Tony Blair was among those who paid tribute to Mr
Molyneaux yesterday, saying: ''James Molyneaux is a distinguished
parliamentarian who has built up a considerable reputation as leader of
his party.''
Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew said he had led his
party with ''great shrewdness and courage over many years''.
Irish Prime Minister John Bruton said Mr Molyneaux had displayed
courageous judgment during critical moments in Northern Ireland.
Sinn Fein president Mr Gerry Adams, who wished Mr Molyneaux well in
his retirement, said Mr Molyneaux's successor would have the ''difficult
but not impossible task of providing the Unionist people with the
effective pragmatic leadership which has so far been lacking''.
Battle for Unionism -- 11
Leader Comment -- 12
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950829-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950829-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950829</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots rail services could be hit by funding cuts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON, CHIEF REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976650506</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
RAILWAY privatisation was thrown into further disarray last night when
it emerged that future Government funding for train operating companies
will favour those that are sold off.
Financial support will be ''assured'' for train operators in the
private sector -- but merely be ''discretionary'' for those in state
ownership, according to a document in the possession of The Herald.
Such contrasting fortunes are of particular significance to Scotland,
because it is possible that north of the Border only InterCity East
Coast main line will be in private hands this side of a General
Election.
Any cuts in financial support would raise serious questions over the
extent and quality of service that InterCity West Coast main line -- and
ScotRail, the largest commuter network outside London -- would be able
to provide.
However, the implications go further. The report warns potential
investors that reduced funding could have ''adverse implications'' for
train operators that are privatised throughout the UK network.
Labour transport spokesman Henry McLeish last night claimed that the
report was a blatant sign that the Government was moving to a ''two-tier
level of funding the railways.''
He likened it to offers of preferential funding to English schools to
opt out of state control, and added: ''It is a blueprint for chaos.''
Concerns over future funding follows a report by the Office of
Passenger Rail Franchising, responsible for the sale of 25 train
operating companies under the break-up British Rail.
The report, an overview of the industry, underlines that once
franchise agreements are in full force, train operators will be
contractually entitled to receive financial support from Opraf.
However, it says the level of support for train operating companies
which are not franchised will remain at the Government's discretion, and
adds: ''No assurance can be given as to the future levels of financial
support for such non-franchised train operating companies (Tocs).
''Potential investors should be aware that any reduction in the level
of financial support paid to non-franchised Tocs could affect the extent
and quality of service supplied by them. This could have adverse
implications for the businesses of the franchised Tocs.''
Industry experts predict that about 60% of the UK network still will
be in the public sector by the next election, due in 1997 at the latest.
Privatisation of the West Coast main line has already been shelved,
while ScotRail has been dropped from the second tranche of operators to
be invited next month to tender to run services after privatisation.
Mr McLeish said of the Opraf report, which suggests finance will be
guaranteed over the seven-year private franchises while operators in the
public sector face cuts: ''It is not a level playing field.
''It looks as if the Government -- facing a chaotic franchising
timetable -- is now intent on frightening the train operators to move
more quickly into the private sector by building financial uncertainty
in the public sector.''
He will now call on Transport Secretary Sir George Young to ensure
that subsidies are maintained, regardless of the status of operating
companies.
Meanwhile, it is suspected that British Rail will be excluded again
from bidding for passenger franchises.
Although the Government has conceded an amendment which allows BR to
compete, it was not allowed to bid for the first three networks -- Great
Western, South West Trains, and London, Tilbury, and Southend.
Next in line under the privatisation programme are Midland Mainline,
Network South East, Gatwick Express, and InterCity East Coast.
It is understood BR will be denied the opportunity to bid when
invitations go out next month -- despite an all-party Commons committee
recommending it should always be given the opportunity to do so.
Labour is expected to demand that BR should be given the same right to
compete as anyone else, including foreign companies.
