<HEADLINE>UN on alert after mortar attack in Sarajevo marketplace kills 37. Bosnians demand revenge air raids</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976650507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE mortar which slammed into a Sarajevo market yesterday, killing at
least 37 people and injuring 85, could have bombed Bosnia back to
all-out civil war. Calls for revenge were swift.
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic threatened retaliation. ''As far
as the killers are concerned, my message to them is: we shall strike
back evenly and very soon too,'' he said.
Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic proposed suspending the US peace effort
and demanded that Nato prove its resolve by bombing Serb gun positions.
He called for ''air raids, air raids immediately'' by Nato forces.
UN Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali last night ordered military
commanders to take unspecified action against those responsible.
Last month, the West warned Bosnian Serbs after the special London
summit that even the threat of an attack on Gorazde, a safe haven, would
bring Nato air strikes. However, it was later understood that attacks on
Sarajevo would also be punished.
The West's response could be determined today in Paris, where there is
a full meeting of the Contact Group on former Yugoslavia, with Britain,
France, Germany, Russia, and the United States, being joined by
officials from Canada, Italy, and Spain.
The 120-mm mortar exploded at the entrance to an indoor market packed
with morning shoppers.
Hours later, wounded patients were injured again when fresh shells
slammed into a hospital full of victims of the morning's attack and
previous bombardments of the besieged Bosnian capital.
The Muslim-led government and the rebel Serbs quickly accused each
other but UN spokesman Alexander Ivanko noted that the first shell was
fired from the south of the city where ''most of the positions are
Bosnian Serb positions''.
The blast left bodies, some without arms or legs, lying in pools of
blood. Some corpses fell apart as rescuers tried to load them into cars.
Many of the dead were children, women, or old people. Sporadic fighting
broke out around Sarajevo following the attack.
The mortar attack, the worst in more than one year in Sarajevo, was
staged hours before Mr Izetbegovic was to meet American envoy Richard
Holbrooke in Paris to discuss the new US peace plan.
''This will not stop the peace process. It will only make us redouble
our efforts,'' Mr Holbrooke said.
In Washington, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said:
''Military pressure will not push us off the negotiating track.'' He
said it ''remains to be seen'' whether the attack was enough to trigger
retaliatory air strikes.
Mr Burns made clear Washington believed the Bosnian Serbs were behind
the shelling, although this was denied by Bosnian Serb officials. ''We
believe this attack is another crime against humanity. The obvious
target of Bosnian Serb shelling is once again the civilians of
Sarajevo,'' Mr Burns said.
In a statement, Mr Boutros-Ghali condemned the shelling
''unreservedly'' and said he had instructed military commanders ''to
investigate this attack immediately and to take appropriate action
without delay''.
His spokesman Joe Sills said any response to the attack would be
determined by French General Bernard Janvier, the overall commander of
UN forces in the Balkans, and Britain's UN commander in Bosnia,
Lieutenant General Rupert Smith.
''That's as far as I can go. I cannot speculate on what action will be
taken or what the timing will be,'' he said. ''But I want to underline
that no options will be ruled out.''
There were fears last night that British soldiers were being blocked
by Serbs from leaving the eastern enclave of Gorazde, a move to prevent
air strikes by using them as hostages. However, UN officials said the
peacekeepers were en route to the border and had not encountered any
problems.
Bosnia's Minister for UN relations, Mr Hasan Muratovic, said: ''At
this moment, Serbs are holding the last column of British soldiers that
is leaving Gorazde. I warned General Smith five days ago and told him
that the last column would be stopped. No strikes are being discussed
for this very reason.''
A spokesman for the Ministry of Defence in London said last night it
had no knowledge of British soldiers being blocked. ''It is always
difficult to say exactly what is going on but we don't think it is
true,'' he added.
Foreign Office Minister Baroness Chalker called the attack ''senseless
and depraved'' and said Britain was ready to respond to any requests for
humanitarian help.
''There can never be any justification for these attacks on civilians
and we condemn those responsible,'' she said.
''There can be no military solution to this conflict.''
It was the worst incident since 68 people were killed and some 200
wounded at a nearby outdoor market in February 1994.
The Bosnian Serbs accused the Sarajevo government of targeting its own
people.
Bosnian Serb army commander, General Ratko Mladic, said the attack was
''constructed to stop the peace process and trigger Nato strikes''.
The call for air strikes was not slow in coming. Prime Minister
Silajdzic said: ''If the United Nations wants to stop innocent people
being killed and for us to stop seeing children's arms and legs all over
our streets, they have to understand that those people (Serbs)
understand only force and nothing else.''
Asked what Nato should do, he said: ''I want air raids, air raids
immediately to punch those who are killing innocent people. Air raids
and we will have peace.''
Western governments condemned the attack. Germany demanded that those
found to be responsible be punished. The United States denounced it as a
crime against humanity, Italy said it was deplorable, and Russia said it
was barbaric.
President Izetbegovic is due to lunch with French President Jacques
Chirac today.
Mr Izetbegovic said he heard of the massacre in the town of Mostar and
considered calling off his trip.
He accused the international community of allowing the Bosnian Serbs
to attack the capital with impunity while refusing to lift a UN arms
embargo which has favoured the better-armed Serbs. ''I am going to
France to ask them how long will this situation last and how long will
this violence be tolerated,'' he said.
